tra</title>, the Mahyna.The one <foreign lang="zh">ru</foreign>, i.e. the <foreign lang="sa">bhtatathat</foreign>, or absolute, as the norm and essence of life. The 如 true suchness, or true character, or reality; the 法性 nature of things or beings. The whole of things as they are, or seem; a cosmos; a species; things of the same order. Name of a celebrated monk, Yiru. V. 一; 一实.One of the 33 representations of Guanyin ascending on the clouds.Immediate experiential enlightenment by the Tathgata truth; the immediate realization that all is 如 <foreign lang="sa">bhtatathat</foreign>.One word; a magic or esoteric word.Three homages at every word one copies of the <foreign lang="sa">stra</foreign>s.The 'Single-word Majur', the magic word is 齿 M063830; or 体哩□ 淫; or 叱洛□焰, and is used to avoid difficult parturition and to heal arrow-wounds. The image used is of a youthful smiling Majur, wearing the felicitous pearl, with one tress on his head, hence also called 一髻文殊.A cryptic single-word reply to a question, requiring meditation for its apprehension; it is a Chan or Zen method.(一字金轮顶法) The one word golden-wheel magical method (Shingon), the one word is <foreign lang="sa">bhr</foreign>; also 一字金轮佛顶法.Yining, a monk who went to Japan in 1299; v. 一山.The one precious thing, the spirit, or intelligent nature; the intelligent mind (behind all things).The one reality; the <foreign lang="sa">bhtatathat</foreign>; idem 一如, 一.The one method, of salvation, the 一实 School.The Tathgata's perfect vehicle, i.e. that of the Lotus Scripture.The one real and perfect school, i.e. the Tiantai or Lotus School.The state or realm of 一实; the realization of the spirituality of all things; it is the 如来法身 the <foreign lang="sa">tathgata-dharmakya</foreign>.The one reality being indivisible is apart from all transient (or empty) forms, and is therefore styled the formless, e.g. the invisible.The state of <foreign lang="sa">bhtatathat</foreign>, above all differentiation, immutable; it implies the Buddha-nature, or the immateriality and unity of all things; 如之理无二无别, 离诸虚妄之相; it is undivided unity apart from all phenomena.A monasterial family party, i.e. when a monk, on becoming head of a monastery, invites its inmates to a feast.A small <foreign lang="sa">kalpa</foreign>; a period of the growth and decay of a universe. See 一增一灭 and 劫.A grain of dust, an atom, a particle.The whole in an atom, a universe in a grain of dust, one grain of dust is a microcosm of the universal whole.A hill; a monastery; Yishan, the name of a Chinese monk who voyaged to Japan in A.D. 1299 and who was also styled 一宁 Yining.Unity-cum-differentiation; monism and pluralism; one and many; <foreign lang="sa">ekatva-anyatva</foreign>, oneness and otherness.An appearance, a lifetime, the period of an individual existence, also 一期 and 一生涯.One passage, or time, once; on one superficial going.A particle of dust; an atom, the smallest particle, a microcosm of the universe.With the whole mind or heart; one mind of heart; also the <foreign lang="sa">bhtatathat</foreign>, or the whole of things; the universe as one mind, or a spiritual unity.同体三惑The Tiantai 'three doubts' in the mind of a <foreign lang="sa">bodhisattva</foreign>, producing fear of illusion, confusion through multiplicity of duties, and ignorance, i.e. 见思; 尘沙 and 无明 q.v.One mind and three aspects of knowledge. The 别教 separates the three aspects into 空, 假, and 中 q.v.; Tiantai unifies them into one immediate vision, or regards the three as aspects of the one mind.The Tiantai insight 一心三智; also simultaneous vision of past, present, and future; also called 圆融三观; 不可思议三观.With undivided mind to call on the name (of Guanyin).圆顿戒 The infrangible-diamond rules of all <foreign lang="sa">bodhisattva</foreign>s and Buddhas, a term of Tiantai School, founded on the 梵网经.The first anniversary of a death; any such anniversary; also 一周忌.A <foreign lang="sa">kaa</foreign>, or thought; a concentration of mind; a moment; the time of a thought, of which there are varying measurements from 60 <foreign lang="sa">kaa</foreign> upwards; the <title>Fan-yi-ming-yi</title> makes it one <foreign lang="sa">kaa</foreign>. A reading. A repetition (especially of Amitbha's name). The Pure-land sect identify the thought of Buddha with Amitbha's vow, hence it is an assurance of salvation.In a moment's thought to obtain a myriad years and no return to mortality.In one thought to survey or embrace the 3,000 worlds, or a chiliocosmos with all its forms of existence; to see the universe as a thought; it is a Tiantai mode of meditation.Not a thought arising; beyond the necessity of thinking, as in the case of a Buddha.At one thought the work completed; karma complete in one thought. One repetition, or sincere thought of or faith in Amitbha's vow, and entrance into the Pure Land is assured.Monophysitic or 'pantheistic' sects of Mahyna, which assert that all beings have one and the same nature with Buddha.(一恒) As one Ganges, i.e. as the sands of one Ganges river.A breath, i.e. inspiration-cum-expiration; a rest, or cessation.Half a step at a breathing on arising from meditation.The one vow, i.e. the 18th of the 48 vows of Amitbha, on which his sect is established.The Huayan doctrine that the law of the universal runs through the phenomenal, therefore a speck of dust is a microcosmos; also that with the Tathgata's enlightenment all beings were enlightened in him; in the perfection of one all are perfected; one deed includes all.A sudden remark, or question, by a monk or master to test a disciple, a Chan (Zen) method.Adherence to one Buddha and one <foreign lang="sa">stra</foreign>.The one finger-tip contemplation used by a certain monk to bring to another a conception of the universe. Also a parable in the 楞伽经 <title>Lakvatra-stra</title>. The Chan or Zen sect 禅宗 regard the <foreign lang="sa">stra</foreign>s merely as indicators, i.e. pointing fingers, their real object being only attained through personal mediation.A ball (or handful) of food; one helping; a frugal meal, the sixth of the 12 <foreign lang="sa">dhta</foreign>s; also called 节量食 and 一抟食.The 一法界 one reality, or undivided absolute, is static, not phenomenal, it is effortless, just as it is 自然 self-existing.The one way without barrier, i.e. the end of reincarnations in <foreign lang="sa">nirva</foreign>; a meditation on it.A sun, or day from sunrise to sunset.<term lang="sa">ahortra</term>. One day one night, a day and night, a division of time.The three divisions of a day, morning, noon, evening.A one-day Buddha, i.e. he who lives a whole day purely.A <foreign lang="sa">stra</foreign> copied in one day (perhaps by many hands); also styled 顿写.<foreign lang="sa">ekasmin samaye</foreign> (Pali: <foreign lang="pi">
