via media</foreign> is that which lies between or embraces both the 空 and the 假, i.e. the void, or noumenal, and the phenomenal.The middle vehicle to nirvana, includes all intermediate or medial systems between Hnayna and Mahyna. It also corresponds with the state of a <foreign lang="sa">pratyekabuddha</foreign>, who lives chiefly for his own salvation but partly for others, like a man sitting in the middle of a vehicle, leaving scarcely room for others. It is a definition made by Mahayanists unknown to Hnayna.Another name for the uttar sagh, the middle garment of price, or esteem.The central Buddha in a group.The fifteenth of the seventh moon; see 孟兰盆.Middling kalpa, a period of 336, 000, 000 years.(中千世界)  A middling chiliocosm, see 三千大千世界.Central India, i. e. of the 五印 five Indies, as mentioned by Xuanzang in the 西域记.The name of a Buddha in the center of lotus.The Court of the eight-petaled lotus in the middle of the Garbhadhtu, with Vairocana in its center and four Buddhas and four bodhisattvas on the eight petals. The lotus is likened to the human heart, with the Sun-Buddha 大日 at its center. The four Buddhas are E. Akobhya, S. Ratnasambhava, W. Amitbha, N. Amoghasiddhi; the four bodhisattvas are S. E. Samantabhadra, S. W. Majur, N. W. Avalokitevara, and N. E. Maitreya.The middle Agama 阿含经.Chanting of 梵呗 Buddhist hymns is divided into three kinds 初, 中, and 后.Middle rank or class.An arrangement by the esoteric sect of the Five Dhyni-Buddhas, Vairocana being the first in position, Akobhya east, and so on.Madhyadesa. 中天 (中天竺); 中梵 The middle kingdom, i. e. Central North India, v. 中印.medium disciples, i. e. <foreign lang="sa">rvaka</foreign>s and <foreign lang="sa">pratyekabuddha</foreign>s, who can gain emancipation for themselves, but cannot confer it on others: cf. 下士 and 上士.(中天竺) Central North India, idem 中国.A monastery on the 飞来 Feilai peak at Hangchow.The school or principle of the mean, represented by the 法相宗 Dharmalakaa school, which divides the Buddha's teaching into three periods, the first in which he preached 有 existence, the second 空 non-existence, the third 中 neither, something 'between' or above them, e. g. a realm of pure spirit, vide the 深密经 <title>Sadhinirmocana-stra</title> and the <title>Lotus Sutra</title>.idem 中道实相.A monk's inner garment, i. e. the five-patch garment; also 中依.The central honored one-- in any group of Buddhas, e. g. 不动尊 among the five 明王.idem 忠心经.Repenting or recanting midway, i. e. doubting and falling away.One of the 四有, i. e. the antar-bhva or intermediate state of existence between death and reincarnation; hence 中有之旅 is an unsettled being in search of a new habitat or reincarnation; v. 中阴.An unsettled being in search of a new habitat or reincarnation; v. 中阴.Medium capacity, neither clever nor dull, of each of the six organs 六根; there are three powers of each organ 上根, 中根, and 下根.Central North India, idem 中国.Each of the four great continents at the foot of Mount Sumeru has two middling continents.In the midst of the stream, i. e. of 生死 mortality, or reincarnations.(中胎藏) The central figure of the eight-petalled group of the Garbhadhtu maala; i. e. the phenomenal Vairocana who has around him four Buddhas and four bodhisattvas, each on a petal. From this maala spring the four other great maalas.One of the five kinds of those who never recede but go on to <foreign lang="sa">parinirva</foreign>, cf. 不还.Medium-sized herbs, medium capacity, v. 三草.Meditation on the Mean, one of the 三观; also meditation on the absolute which unites all opposites. There are various forms of such meditation, that of the 法相宗, the 三论宗, the 天台宗. v. 中论.中观论 Prnyya-mla-stra-k, or Pryamula-stra-k; the Mdhyamika-stra, attributed to the bodhisattvas Ngrjuna as creator, and Nlacakus as compiler; tr. by Kumrajva A. D. 409. It is the principal work of the Mdhyamika, or Middle School, attributed to Ngrjuna. Versions only exist in Chinese and Tibetan; an English translation by Miyamoto exists and publication is promised; a German version is by Walleser. The 中论 is the first and most?? important of the 三论 q. v. The teaching of this School is found additionally in the 顺中论; 般若灯论释大乘中观释论 and 中论疏. Cf. 中道. The doctrine opposes the rigid categories of existence and non-existence 假 and 空, and denies the two extremes of production (or creation) and nonproduction and other antitheses, in the interests of a middle or superior way.The Mdhyamika school, which has been described as a system of sophisiic nihilism, dissolving every proposition into a thesis and its antithesis, and refuting both; but it is considered by some that the refuting of both is in the interests of a third, the 中 which transcends both.The third of the 三谛 three postulates of the Tiantai school, i. e. 空, 假, and 中 q. v.The middle stage of the 三辈 referred to in the 无量寿经 i. e. the middle class of those in the next life; also 中辈生.the meditation on the condition of 中辈.A treatise by Vasubandhu, translated by Xuanzang in three chuan and by 陈谛Chen Zhen-ti in two fascicles. It is an explanation of the 辨中边论颂 <title>Madhynta-vibhga-stra</title>, said to have been given by Maitreya to Asaga.The 'mean' has various interpretations. In general it denotes the mean between two extremes, and has special reference to the mean between realism and nihilism, or eternal substantial existence and annihilation; this 'mean' is found in a third principle between the two, suggesting the idea of a realm of mind or spirit beyond the terminology of 有 or 无, substance or nothing, or, that which has form, and is therefore measurable and ponderable, and its opposite of total non-existence. See 中论. The following four Schools define the term according to their several scriptures: the 法相 School describes it as the 唯识, v. 唯识中道; the 三论 School as the 八不 eight negations, v. 三论; the Tiantai as 实相 the true reality; and the Huayan as the 法界 <foreign lang="sa">dharmadhtu</foreign>. Four forms of the Mean are given by the 三论玄义.The third period of the Buddha's teaching, according to the 法相宗, giving the via media between the two extremes, the absolute as not confined to the phenomenal or the noumenal; also called 中道教.The reality of the 'mean' is neither 有 substance or existent, nor 空 void or non-existent, but a reality which is neither, or a mean between the two extremes of materialism and nihilism; also 中实.The 'mean' as the basic principle in the 别 and 圆 schools of the doctrine of the 应化身 'transformation body'.The doctrine of the 'mean', is the <foreign lang="sa">dharmadhtu</foreign>, or 'spiritual ' universe.The 'mean' is the first and chief of all principles, nothing is outside it.One of the Tiantai 三观 three meditations, i. e. on the doctrine of the Mean to get rid of the illusion of phenomena.An intermediate <foreign lang="sa">dhyna</foreign> stage between two <foreign lang="sa">dhyna</foreign>-heavens; also 中间三昧; 中间静虑.The intermediate existence between death and reincarnation, a stage varying from seven to forty-nine days, when the karma-body will certainly be reborn; v. 中有.The means used (by the deceased' s family) for ensuring a favorable reincarnation during the intermediate stage, between death and reincarnation.The midday meal, after which nothing whatever may be eaten.Abundant.Wealthy.To regard with kindness: approach, on the brink of, about to; whilst.Approaching the midday meal; near noon.A monastery during the Tang dynasty in 定府 Zhending Fu, Zhili, from which the founder of the临济school derived his title; his name was 义玄 Yixuan; cf. 禅门.Approach the end, dying.Incense balls made of various kinds of ingredients; typifying the aggregation of mortal suffering, and its destruction by the, fires of wisdom.Red, cinnabar color; a remedy, drug, elixir.
