sa">updhyya</term>, originally a subsidiary teacher of the <foreign lang="sa">vedga</foreign>s; later, through Central Asia, it became a term for a teacher of Buddhism, in distinction from 律师disciplinists and 禅师 intuitionalists, but as <foreign lang="zh">heshang</foreign> it attained universal application to all masters.Upananda (or 坞波难陀), a disciple of kyamuni; also one of the eight <foreign lang="sa">naga</foreign>-kings in the Garbhadhtu.乌婆计设尼 Upakein, one of the messengers of Majur.乌罗伽 <term lang="sa">uraga</term>, going on the belly, a serpent.<term lang="sa">uraga(sra)-candana</term>, serpent-sandal, a kind of sandal wood, used as a febrifuge.(乌瑟) <term lang="sa">ua</term>, a turban, diadem, distinguishing mark; intp. as 佛顶 the crown of the Buddha's head; and 肉髻 fleshy tuft or coif, one of the thirty-two <foreign lang="sa">lakani</foreign> of a Buddha, generally represented as a protuberance on the frontal crown. Also M046663瑟腻沙; 乌失尼沙; 郁瑟腻沙 (or □瑟腻沙).Agni, or Akni, an ancient kingdom north of Lop Nor, identified with Karashahr. Also 阿耆尼; M067729夷.Ua, Uradea, Ora, Oivisa; an ancient country of eastern India with a busy port called 折利□罗 Charitrapura (Xuanzang), probably the province of Orissa.<term lang="uig"> ulak</term>; <term lang="uig">ulag</term>; a Uigur term meaning horse, indicating relays of post-horses.Upavasaha (Pali, Uposatha). A fast-day, originally in preparation for the brahminical <foreign lang="sa">soma</foreign> sacrifice; in Buddhism there are six fast-days in the month.? Uabha, or Uakha, an ancient city of Gandhra, on the northern bank of the Indus, identified with Ohind; Eitel gives it as 'the modern Attok'.Udayana, a king of Vatsa, or Kaumb, 'contemporary of kyamuni,' of whom he is said to have had the first statue made.Lacking.lacking in the right way, shortcoming, poor, --an expression of humility.Music, that which causes joy, hence joy, joyful, glad, rejoice; also to find joy in, enjoy.The sensation, or perception of pleasure.Sunirmita, 