ddhism, situated in Anhui, and its patron Bodhisattva is Dizang 地藏.The nine monthly visits or ascents to the hall for worship, every third day.A term in Buddhist logic; the nine possible combinations of like and unlike examples in a syllogism.Nine classes, or grades, i.e. 上上, 上中, 上下 upper superior, middle superior, lower superior, and so on with 中 and 下. They are applied in many ways, e.g. 上品上生 the highest type of incarnate being, to 下品下生, the lowest, with corresponding karma; see 九品净土. Each grade may also be subdivided into nine, thus making a list of eighty-one grades, with similar further subdivision ad infinitum.An abbreviation for 上品上生 the highest grade in the Pure Land, see 九品净土.also 九品净　,  九品安养,　九品莲台, 九品往生 The nine grades, or rewards, of the Pure Land, corresponding to the nine grades of development in the previous life, upon which depends, in the next life, one's distance from Amitbha, the consequent aeons that are needed to approach him, and whether one's lotus will open early or late.The 僧伽梨 <term lang="sa">sagh</term>. There are nine grades of the monk's patch robe; the three lowest ranks have 9, 11, and 13 patches, two long patches to one short one; the three middle 15, 17, 19, three long to one short; and the three superior 21, 23, 25, four long to one short.Those born by transformation from the (heavenly) lotus into the ninefold 安养 Paradise, idem 九品净土.The nine forms of Amitbha, corresponding to the nine departments of the Pure Land; chiefly used with reference to the manual signs of his images.The ninefold future life, in the Pure Land, v. 九品净土.　It is detailed in the sutra of this name whose full title is 阿弥陀三摩地集陀罗尼经.Also九品烦恼 The four 修惑, i.e. illusions or trials in the practice of religion, i.e. desire, anger, pride, ignorance; these are divided each into 九品 q.v.; hence desire has all the nine grades, and so on with the other three.The nine karma to be attained by the conduct or practice through which one may be born into the above Pure Land.The king or lord of the bodhi of the Pure Land, Amitbha.Nine of the 十界 ten dhtu or regions are causative, the tenth is the effect or resultant.The nine lands, i.e. the 欲界 realm of desire or sensuous realm the four 色界 realms of form or material forms; and the four 无色界 formless realms, or realms beyond form; v. 九有, 九有情居, 禅 and 定. The nine realms are:--(1) 欲界五趣地; the desire realm with its five gati, i.e. hells, hungry ghosts, animals, men, and devas. In the four form-realms are:-- (2) 离生喜乐地 Paradise after earthly life, this is also the first dhyna, or subject of meditation, 初禅. (3) 定生喜乐地 Paradise of cessation of rebirth, 二禅. (4) 离喜妙乐地 Land of wondrous joy after the previous joys, 三禅. (5) 舍念净地 The Pure Land of abandonment of thought, or recollection (of past delights), 四禅. The four formless, or infinite realms, catur arpa dhtu, are:--(6) 空无边处地 knanty-yatanam, the land of infinite space; also the first samdhi, 第一定. (7) 识无边处地 vijnnamtyyatanam, the land of omniscience, or infinite perception, 二定. (8) 无所有处地 kicanyyatana, the land of nothingness, 三定. (9) 非想非非想处地 naivasajn-sajyatana, the land (of knowledge) without thinking or not thinking, or where there is neither consciousness nor unconsciousness, i.e. above either; this is the 四定. Eitel says that in the last four, "Life lasts 20,000 great kalpas in the 1st, 40,000 in the 2nd, 60,000 in the 3rd, and 80,000 great kalpas in the 4th of these heavens."v. 八十一品思惑.idem 九地 and 九界.idem Kuinagara; v. 拘.Also 九入, 九窍, 九漏, 九流, 九疮 the nine orifices, cavities, entrances, leakages, or suppurations, i.e. the two eyes, two ears, two nostrils, mouth, and two lower organs.The nine magical characters 临兵者皆陈列在前 implying that the armed forces are arrayed against the powers of evil. After reciting these words, four vertical and five horizontal lines, forming a grid, are drawn in the air to show that the forces are arrayed. It was used among Taoists and soldiers, and is still used in Japan, especially when going into the mountains.The nine character <foreign lang="sa">maala</foreign>, i.e. the lotus, with its eight petals and its centre; Avalokitevara may be placed in the heart and Amitbha on each petal, generally in the shape of the Sanskrit "seed" letter, or alphabetic letter.The eight sects 八宗 (q.v.) plus the 禅宗 Chan or Zen, or the Pure-land or Jdo sect.The nine honoured ones in the eight-petalled hall of the Garbhadhtu, i.e. Vairocana in the centre of the lotus, with four Buddhas and four bodhisattvas on the petals, the lotus representing the human heart; v. 五佛.v. 九有情居.The nine cakravla, or concentric mountain ranges or continents, separated by eight seas, of a universe. The central mountain of the nine is Sumeru 须弥 and around it are the ranges Khadiraka 佶提罗, dhara 伊沙陀罗, Yugadhara 游干陀罗, Sudaraa 苏达梨舍那, Avakara 安湿缚竭□, Nemidhara 尼民陀罗, Vinataka 毗那多迦, Cakravda 斫迦罗; v. 七金山. The Abhidharma Koa gives a different order: Sumeru, Yugadhara, dhara, Khadiraka, Sudarana, Avakara, Vinataka, Nemidhara, with an "iron-wheel" mountain encompassing all; there are also differences in the detail.The nine penetrating fames of the sword of Acala, 不动明王, emblem of the destruction of illusions and hindrances in the nine realms, v. 九地; also used for the 九尊 q.v.The nine evolutions, or movements of the mind in perception.also 九难, 九横, 九罪报 The nine distresses borne by the Buddha while in the flesh, i.e. the two women Sundar and Cac; others from Devadatta, Ajtaatru, etc.; v. 智度论 9.(九想观) or 九相 navasaj. Meditation on a corpse in order to curb desire; one of the meditations on the unclean: vydhmtakasaj, its tumefaction; vinlakas., its blue, mottled colour; vipadumakas., its decay; vilohitakas., its mess of blood,etc.; vipyakas., its discharges and rotten flesh; vikhditakas., its being devoured by birds and beasts; vikiptakas., its dismembering; asthis., its bones; vidagdhakas., their being burnt and returning to dust.The nine forms of pride: that I surpass, am equal to, not so bad as others; that others surpass, are as bad as, are inferior to me; that none surpass, are equal to, or worse than me.The nine graha, i.e. "seizers" or upholders, i.e. luminaries or planets, idem 九曜.the nine kinds of days of abstinence on which no food is eaten after twelve o'clock: noon and the commands are observed. They are: Every day of the first month, of the fifth month, of the ninth month, and the following six days of each month, 8th, 14th, 15th, 23rd, 29th, and 30th. On these days Indra and the four deva-kings investigate the conduct of men.The nine suitable stages in religious service; cf. 大日经, 7; 作礼 salutation to the universal Triratna; 出罪 repentance and confession; 归依 trust (in the Triratna); 施身 giving of self (to the Tathgata); 发菩提心 vowing to devote the mind to bodhi; 随喜 rejoicing (in all good); 劝请 beseeching (all Tathgatas to rain down the saving law); 奉请法身 praying for the Buddha-nature in self and others for entry in the Pure Land; 回向 demitting the good produced by the above eight methods, to others, universally, past, present, and future. This form of service is generally performed before engaging in esoteric observances. The verses in which these nine stages are presented are of a commendably devotional character.Of the ten pramit bodhisattvas, q.v., in the tenth or empyrean court of the Garbhadhtu, the first nine are associated with the above nine progressive steps, the tenth is associated with the last four of the nine.The nine kinds of, and meditations on, 无 q.v. There are two somewhat different groups; one has 择灭, 非择灭, 虚空, 空无边处, 识无边处, 无所有处, 非想非非想处 (v. 九有情处), 缘起支性, and 圣道支性.The nine grades (of arhats) who are no longer learning, having attained their goal.In every universe there are nine realms, in every realm there are nine illusions in practice 修, and nine ways of relief; hence the nine ways of overcoming hindrances; also there are nine uninterrupted ways of advance from one stage to another of the nine stages of the 三界 trailokya, by the wisdom of overcoming delusion in each stage; also 九无碍道 ; and cf. 九解脱道.九执 q.v. Navagraha. The nine luminaries: 日 ditya, the sun; 月 Sma, the moon; the five planets, i.e. 火星 Agraka, Mars; 水 Budha, Mercury; 木 Bhaspati, Jupiter; 金 Sukra, Venus; and 土 anaicara, Saturn; also 罗 Rhu, the spirit that causes eclipses; and 计都 Ketu, a comet. Each is associated with a region of the sky and also with a bodhisattva, etc., e.g. the sun with Guanyin, Venus with Amitbha, etc.The nine realities, states, or conditions in which sentient beings enjoy to dwell, v. next.(or 九有情处), 九生居, 九居, 九门, see also 九有, 九地, 九禅 and 九定; the nine happy abodes or states of sentient beings of the 长阿含经 9; they are the 七识住seven abodes or stages of perception or consciousness to which are added the fifth and ninth below: (1) 欲界之人天 the world and the six deva-heavens of desire in which there is variety of bodies (or personalities) and thinking (or ideas); (2) 梵天the three brahma heavens where bodies differ but thinking is the same, the first dhyna heaven; (3) 极光净天 the three bright and pure heavens where bodies are identical but thinking diners, the second dhyna heaven; (4) 遍净天the three universally pure heavens where bodies and thinking are the same, the third dhyna heaven; (5) 无想天 the no-thinking or no-thought heaven, the highest of the four dhyna heavens; (6) 空无边处 limitless space, the first of the formless realms; (7) 识无边处 limitless percepton, the second ditto; (8) 无所有处 nothingness, the place beyond things, the third ditto; and (9) 非想非非想beyond thought or non-thought, the fourth ditto.九条袈裟 The lowest rank of the patch-robe, v. 九品大衣.The nine heavens of the fourth dhyna heaven.See also 九恼.The nine kinds of irregular death; there are two groups, one connected with improper food or meals, another with improper medical treatment, lawbreaking, drowning, etc. .A stra translated in the later Han dynasty by 安世高 An Shigao.The samdhi of the nine degrees, i.e. the four dhynas 四禅, the four realms beyond form 四无色, and the samdhi beyond sensation and thought 灭受想定; see 九有情居 and 九地.九漏 idem | 孔.v. 九有情居.(九界情执) The nine realms of error, or subjection to the passions, i.e. all the realms of the living except the tenth and highest, the Buddha-realm.idem 九孔.The nine forms of complete knowledge of the four axioms and the cutting off of passion, delusion, etc., in the processes of 见 and 修, as distinct from 无学.(相承)　The succession of nine founders of the Tiantai School; v. 天台九宗.The nine kinds of Mahyna dhyna for bodhisattvas, given in the 菩萨地持经 6 and in other works; they are associated with the patience 忍 pramit and with the dhyna of the super-realms. The nine are meditations: (1) 自性禅 on the original nature of things, or mind as the real nature, from which all things derive; (2) 一切禅 on achieving the development of self and all others to the utmost; (3) 难禅 on the difficulties of certain dhyna conditions; (4) 一切禅 on the entrance to all the (superior) dhyna conditions; (5) 善人禅 on the good; (6) 一切行禅 on all Mahyna practices and actions; (7) 除烦恼禅 on ridding all sufferers from the miseries of passion and delusion; (8) 此世他世乐禅 on the way to bring joy to all people both in this life and hereafter; (9) 净净禅 on perfect purity in the termination of all delusion and distress and the obtaining of perfect enlightenment.v. 九孔.The nine kinds of birth; the four from the womb, egg, moisture, transformation are common to devas, earth, and the hells; the five others are birth into the heavens of form, of non-form, of thought, of non-thought, and of neither (i.e. beyond either).idem 九部经.The nine bonds that bind men to mortality: love, hate, pride, ignorance, (wrong)views, possessions (or grasping), doubt, envy, meanness (or selfishness).　They are the 六随眠 plus grasping, envy, and meanness.The nine states of bondage and the one state of liberation. The nine states are the hells of fire, of blood, of swords; asuras, men, devas, mras, nirgranthas, form and formless states; these are all sasra states, i.e. of reincarnation. The one state of freedom, or for obtaining freedom, is nirva.v. 九恼.The paradise of 