enty kinds of wisdom or knowledge as denied by Tiantai i.e. the Hnayna (or三藏) with seven kinds, 通教 five, 别教four, and 圆教 four; cf. 智.The twenty skandhas intp. as 章篇 sections or chapters, i.e. the thirty-one to the fifty-three chuan of the 四分律, beginning with受戒犍度 and ending with 杂犍度; they are twenty sections containing rules for the monastic life and intercourse.The eighteen Hnayna sects, together with the two original assemblies of elders.The dual receptivity or karma of pleasure and pain, the physical and the mental, i.e. 身 and 心.The two <foreign lang="sa">dukta</foreign>, doing evil and speaking evil; v. 突吉罗 .The double harmony or unity, i. e. 理 and 事, indicating those who are united in doctrine and practice, or the sagha.The two good things, 定善 the good character that arises from meditation or contemplation mdash especially of the Pure Land; 散善 the good character attainable when, though not in meditation, one controls oneself in thought, word, and deed;. Also 未生善 the good character not yet evolved; and 已生善 the good character already evolved;. Also 事理善 goodness in theory and practice.Two causes, of which there are various definitions: (1) 生因 The producing cause (of all good things); and 了因 the revealing or illuminating cause i.e. knowledge, or wisdom. (2) 能生因 The 8th 识 q. v.:  the cause that is able to produce all sense and perceptions, also all good and evil; and 方便因 the environmental or adaptive cause, which aids the 8th 识, as water or earth does the seed, etc. (3) 习因 or 同类因 Practice or habit as cause e. g. desire causing desire; and 报因 or 果熟因 the rewarding cause, or fruit-ripening cause, e. g. pleasure or pain caused by good or evil deeds. (4) 正因 Correct or direct cause i.e. the Buddha-nature of all beings; and 缘因 the contributory cause, or enlightenment (see 了因 above) which evolves the 正因 or Buddha-nature by good works. (5) 近因 Immediate or direct cause and 远因 distant or indirect cause or causes.The two perfect doctrines, a term of the Tiantai School, called 今圆 (also 开显圆 and 待圆) and 昔圆 (also 相待圆 ). 今圆 is the present really perfect 一实 doctrine arising from the Lotus Stra; 昔圆 is the older, or 相待 comparatively speaking perfect doctrine of the pre-Lotus teaching, that of the 藏, 通, and 别 schools; but the older was for limited salvation and not universal like the 今圆; these two are also termed 部圆 and 教圆 . The Huayan school has a division of the two perfections into 渐圆 gradual perfection and 顿圆 immediate perfection.There are three groups: 性土 and 相土 : the former is the ubiquitous, unadulterated or innocent 法性之理 dharma-name, or essence of things; the latter is the form-nature, or formal existence of the dharma, pure or impure according to the mind and action of the living. The 净土 and 秽土 are Pure-land or Paradise; and impure land, e.g. the present world. In the Pure-land there are also 报土 , the land in which a Buddha himself dwells and 化土 in which all beings are transformed. There are other definitions, e. g. the former is Buddha's Paradise, the latter the world in which he dwells and which he is transforming, e. g. this Sah-world.kyamuni and Prabhtaratna 多宝.The two superior kinds of bodhisattvas, 智增菩萨 bodhisattva superior in wisdom (chiefly beneficial to self); 悲增菩萨 bodhisattva superior in pity for others and devotion to their salvation.二挟侍 The two attendants by the side of Amitbha, i.e. 观音 Guanyin and 大势至 Mahsthmaprpta; also the two by Yaoshi, the Master of Medicine, i.e. 日光 sunlight and 月光 moonlight; also the two by kyamuni, i.e. 文殊 Majur and 普贤 Samantabhadra.The two places from which the Buddha is supposed to have preached the Lotus Stra, i.e. the Vulture Peak, the sky, and again the Vulture Peak; the three assemblies are (1) those he addressed from the Peak, chapters 1 to the middle of the eleventh chapter; (2) those addressed from the sky, to the end of the twenty-second chapter; and (3) again those on the Vulture Peak, from the twenty-third chapter to the end.The two devas. (1) 日天 and 月天Sun-deva and Moon-deva. (2) 同生天A deva born simultaneously with the individual and 同名天 a deva with the same name as the individual; both devas have the duty of watching over the individual. (3) 梵天 and 帝释天 Brahma and Indra.The two devas are Mahevara and Viu; the three i are Kapila, Ulka, and abha; v. 迦, 优, and 勒.The two sisters, one the deva 功德女 "merit" or "achieving", who causes people to acquire wealth; the other, 黑暗女 the "dark" one, who causes them to spend and waste; these sisters always accompany each other.There are various definitions of the two aspects of the 如 bhtatathat. (1) (a) 不变如 The changeless essence or substance, e.g. the sea; (b) 随缘如 its conditioned or ever-changing forms, as in the phenomenal world, e.g. the waves. (2) (a) 离言如 The inexpressible absolute, only mentally conceivable; (6) 依言如 aspects of it expressible in words, its ideal reflex. (3) (a) 空如 The absolute as the void, e.g. as space, the sky, a clear mirror; (b) 不空如 the absolute in manifestation, or phenomenal, e. g. images in the mirror: the womb of the universe in which are all potentialities. (4) (a) 在缠如The Buddha-nature in bonds, i.e. all beings in suffering; (b) 出缠真如the Buddha-nature set free by the manifestation of the Buddha and bodhisattvas. (5) (a) 有垢如The Buddha-nature defiled, as in unenlightened man, etc., e.g. the water-lily with its roots in the mud; (b) 无垢如 the pure Buddha-nature, purifed or bright as the full moon. (6) 安立 and 非安立如 similar to the first definition given above.
v. 二如 and 如.The dual "marvel" of the Lotus stra, the 相待妙 or comparative view, i.e. compared with all previous teaching, which is the rough groundwork; and the 绝待妙 or view of it as the perfection of teaching; hence it is "wonderful" in comparison with all previous doctrine, and absolutely 'wonderful' in itself; cf. 二圆.The two beginnings, i.e. of Hnayna, by the preaching of the 阿含 gama stras; and of Mahyna by the preaching of the 华严 Avatasaka stra.Double-letters, i.e. a monk-because a monk's name consists of two characters.The two-character Majur.The two kinds of study or learning: (a) reading and reciting, (b) meditation and thought.Two theories or schools stated by the Huayan (Kegon) school as 法相宗 and 法性宗 q.v., known also as 相宗 and 性宗. There are ten point of difference between them. Another division is the 空宗 and 性宗 q. v.The two esoteric aspects, i.e. 理密 and 事密 , the former referring to the doctrine, the latter to the esoteric acts of a Tathgata.The two honoured ones, kyamuni and Amitbha.(or 致) The two honored ones (kyamuni and Amitbha) as one in teaching.The two honored ones (kyamuni and Amitbha) as teacher and saviour, with reference to the teaching of the way of salvation of the first, and the consequent saving vows of the second.The two kinds of introductory phrase: (a) the ordinary opening phrase of a sutra-- "Thus have I heard"; and (b) specific openings referring to the circumstances in which the stra was produced.The two kinds of transformation-body of a Buddha, i.e. 胜应身 the Buddha's surpassing body as seen by bodhisattvas, and 劣应身 the Buddha's inferior human body as seen by ordinary people.再往 Twice over, a second time.The two kinds of power or virtue are 智德 and 断德; also 悲德 and 智德; also 性德 and 修德; q.v. and v. 德.The two minds, 心 the original, simple, pure, natural mind of all creatures, the Buddha-mind, i.e. 如来藏心; and 妄心 the illusion-mind, which results in complexity and confusion. Also, 定心 the meditative mind, or mind fixed on goodness; and the 散心 the scattered, inattentive mind, or mind that is only good at intervals.The two patiences or endurances: 生忍 patience towards all under all circumstances; 无生(法)忍 calm rest, as a bodhisattva、in the assurance of no (re-) birth, i.e. in immortality. Also 安受苦忍 patience under suffering, and 观察法忍 imperturbable examination of or meditation in the law or of all things. Also, physical and mental patience, or endurance.The two awakenings, or kinds of entry into bodhisattvahood, i.e. 顿悟 immediate and 渐悟 gradual.The two aspects of illusion: 见惑 perplexities or illusions and temptations arise from false views or theories. 思惑 or 修惑, ditto from thoughts arising through contact with the world, or by habit, such as desire, anger, infatuation, etc. They are also styled 理惑 illusions connected with principles and 事惑 illusions arising, in practice; v. 见思.(二我见) The two erroneous views of individualism: (a) 人我见 The erroneous view that there is an independent human personality or soul, and (b) 法我见 the like view that anything exists with an independent nature.The two reasons for clinging to the idea of the self: (a) 具生我执 the natural, or instinctive cleaving to the idea of a self, or soul; (b) 分别我执 the same idea developed as the result of (erroneous) reasoning. Cf. 二法执.The two grades of commandments, or prohibitions, e. g. 十戒 and 具足戒 for monks; 五戒 and 八戒 for the laity; 邪戒 and 正戒 heretical rules and correct rules; and numerous other pairs.The two (erroneous) tenets, or attachments: (1) 我执 or 人执 that of the reality of the ego, permanent personality, the tman, soul or self. (2) 法执 that of the reality of dharma, things or phenomena. Both are illusions. "All illusion arises from holding to the reality of the ego and of things."The dual reward. (1) 依报 or 依果 The material environment on which a person depends, resulting from former karma, e.g. country, house, property, etc. (2) 正报 or 正果 his direct reward, i. e. his body, or person.The two values of the commandments: (a) 止持 prohibitive, restraining from evil; (b) 作持 constructive, constraining to goodness.Dual division of the Buddha's teaching. There are various definitions: (1) Tiantai has (a) 显教 exoteric or public teaching to the visible audience, and (b) 密教 at the same time esoteric teaching to an audience invisible to the other assembly. (2) The 言 Shingon School by "exoteric" means all the Buddha's preaching, save that of the 大日经 which it counts esoteric. (3) (a) 渐教 and (b) 顿教 graduated and immediate teaching, terms with various uses, e.g. salvation by works Hnayna, and by faith, Mahyna, etc.; they are applied to the Buddha's method, to the receptivity of hearers and to the teaching itself. (4) Tiantai has (a) 界教 and (b) 界外教 teachings relating to the 三界 or realms of mortality and teachings relating to immortal realms. (5) (a) 半字教 and (b) 满字教 Terms used in the Nirva stra, meaning incomplete word, or letter, teaching and complete word teaching, i.e. partial and complete, likened to Hnayna and Mahyna. (6) (a) 捃收教 and (b) 扶律谈常教 of the Nirva stra, (a) completing those who failed to hear the Lotus; (b) "supporting the law, while discoursing on immortality," i.e. that the keeping of the law is also necessary to salvation. (7) Tiantai's division of (a) 偏教 and (b) 圆教 the partial teaching of the 藏, 通, and schools as contrasted with the perfect teaching of the 圆 school. (8) Tiantai's division of (a) 构教 and (6) 实教 temporary and permanent, similar to the last two. (9) (a) 世间教 The ordinary teaching of a moral life here; (b) 出世间教 the teaching of Buddha-truth of other-worldly happiness in escape from mortality. (10) (a) 了义教 the Mahyna perfect or complete teaching, and (b) 不了义教 Hnayna incompleteness. (11) The Huayan division of (a) 屈曲教 indirect or uneven teaching as in the Lotus and Nirva stras, and (b) 平道教 direct or levelled up teaching as in the Huayan stra. (12) The Huayan division of (a) 化教 all the Buddha's teaching for conversion and general instruction, and (b) 制教 his rules and commandments for the control and development of his order.Two kinds of impermanence, immediate and delayed. 念念无常 things in motion, manifestly transient; 相续无常 things that have the semblance of continuity, but are also transient, as life ending in death, or a candle in extinction.The two categories of antman: -- 人无我 no (permanent) human ego, or soul; 法无我 no (permanent) individuality in or independence of self or of things.The wisdom that recognizes the two categories of antman, v. 四谛.The two neutrals, or indeterminates which cannot be noted as good or evil.The two times or periods-- morning and evening. Also 迦罗 kla, a regular or fixed hour for meals, and 三昧耶 samaya, irregular or unfxed hours or times.The two kinds of wisdom; there are various pairs. The Huayan school uses 如理智 and 如量智; the Faxiang (法相) uses 根本智 and 后得智; the Tiantai uses 权智 and 实智. (1) (a) 如理智　or 根本智,　无分别智, 正体智, 智, 实智 is Buddha-wisdom, or Bodhisattva real wisdom; (b) 如量智　or 后得智, the same wisdom in its limitation and relation to ordinary human affairs. (2) (a) 实智　Absolute wisdom and (b) 权智 or 方便智 | relative or temporal wisdom. (3) (a)　一切智 wisdom of the all, (b) 一切种智 wisdom of all the particulars.The two kinds of Tathgata-wisdom, 实 and 权 absolute and functional (or relative), both perfect and complete.Sakdgmin; v. 裟 and 斯. The second "fruit" of the four kinds of Hnayna arhats, who have only once more to return to mortality. Also the two kinds of fruit or karma: (a) 习气果 The good or evil characteristics resulting from habit or practice in a former existence; (b) 报果the pain or pleasure resulting (in this life) from the practices of a previous life.The two "roots" or natural powers. (1) (a) 利根 keen, able (in the religion); (b) 钝根 dull. (2) (a) 正根; 胜义根The power or ability which uses the sense organs to discern the truth; (b) 扶根; 扶 (or浮) 尘根the sense organs 五根 as aids. (3) The male and female sexual organs.The two dna 檀那, i. e, kinds of donating, or almsgiving: (a) 世间檀 ordinary alms, and (b) 出世间檀 spiritual, or other-worldly gifts.The two kinds of seeking: 得求 seeking to get (e.g. pleasure) and 命求 seeking long life.The two rivers and the white path, i.e. the path leading to life between the rivers of desire and hatred, which are compared to water and fire.The two tenets in regard to things; of. 二我执, i.e. 生法执 the common or natural tendency to consider things as real; 分别法执 the tenet of the reality of things as the result of false reasoning and teaching.Contrasted types of the Dharmakya; five pairs are given, 理法身 and 智法身; 果极 and 应化法身 ; 自性法身 and 应化法身 ; 法性法身 and 方便法身 ; 理法身 and 事法身 ; cf. 法身.The two ways in the current of transmigration: 顺流 to flow with it in continual re-incarnation; 逆流 resist it and seek a way of escape by getting rid of life's delusions, as in the case of the saints.Two Nirvanas, v. 二种涅盘.The two conditions relating to the passions and delusions: 有漏 the condition in which they can prevail; 无漏 that in which they cannot prevail.The two kinds of klea, i.e. passions, delusions, temptations, or trials. (1) (a) 根本烦恼 The six fundamental kleas arising from the six senses; (b) 随烦恼 the twenty consequent kleas arising out of the six. (2) (a) 分别起烦恼 Klea arising from false reasoning; (b) 生起烦恼 that which is natural to all. (3) (a) 大烦恼地法The six great, e.g. extravagance, and (b) 小烦恼地法 ten minor afflictions, e.g. irritability. (4) (a) 数行烦恼 Ordinary passions, or temptations; (b) 猛利烦恼fierce, sudden, or violent passions, or temptations.The two kinds of love, 欲爱 ordinary human love springing from desire; 法爱 bodhisattva or religious love, i.e. desiring to save all creatures.The two kinds of sin, 止犯 and 作犯.or 二人犯 A term applied by Tiantai in criticism of Huayan, which while it is a 圆 perfect or complete doctrine, yet has the "crudities" of the 别 and comes short of the really perfect Lotus doctrine.The two guardian spirits represented on the temple gates, styled Vajrayaka 金刚夜叉 or 神 or 夜叉神.The two kinds of manifestation, or appearance, 须现 the necessary appearance in the flesh of the Buddha for ordinary people, and 不须现 the non-necessity for this to those of spiritual vision.The 250 commandments, or 具足戒 perfect or complete commandments, which are obligatory on monks and nuns. They are 四波罗夷 or 四根本极恶the four prjika; 十三残 thirteen saghvasea; 二不定法 two aniyata; 三十舍随 thirty naisargik-pyattik; 九十波逸提ninety pryacittik; 四提舍尼four pratideanya; 百学 hundred ikkaraya, and 七灭诤 seven kinds of vinaya for ending disputes.The 1,200 merits of ear in the <title>Lotus Sutra</title>.The dual advantages or benefits: profitable to the life which now is, and that which is to come.The two forms, or characteristics, of the bhutatathata, universal and particular. The 起信论 gives (a) 净智相 pure wisdom, cf. laya-vijna, out of whose primary condition arise　(b) 不思议用相 inconceivable, beneficial functions and uses. The same stra gives also a definition of the 如 as (a) 同相 that all things, pure or impure, are fundamentally of the same universal, e.g. clay which is made into tiles; (b) 异相 but display particular qualities, as affected by pure or impure causes, e.g. the tiles. Another definition, of the 智度论 31, is (a) 总相 universals, as impermanence; (b) 别相 particulars, for though all things have the universal basis of impermanence they have particular qualities, e.g. earth-solidity, heat of fire, etc.idem 二障.The second patriarch of the Chan school, Huike 慧可.the second patriarch in China 慧可 of the Chan school, who, to induce bodhidharma to receive him, is said to have cut of his left arm in the snow in order to prove his firmness and determination.The bliss of the gods, and the bliss of the saints 圣; v. also 福.The two fields for the cultivation of happiness: (a) 学人田 the eighteen Hnayna classes of those under training in religion; (b) 无学人田 the nine divisions of those no longer in training, i.e. who have completed their course. Also (a) 悲田 the pitable or poor and needy, as the field or opportunity for charity; (b) 敬田the field of religion and reverence of the Buddhas, the saints, the priesthood.Two kinds or classes For those not given below see under二, etc., as for instance 二种世间 see under二世间.The two Buddha-domains: (a) 证境 the Buddha's domain or state of absolute enlightenment; (b) 化境 the domain that the Buddha is transforming.The two forms of service, or offerings: (1) (a) 出缠供养 to those who have escaped from the toils, e.g. Buddhas; (b) 在缠供养 to those still living in the toils. (2) (a) 财供养 offerings of goods; (b) 法供养 of the Buddha-truth.The two kinds of light: (1) (a) 色光明 physical light; (b) 智慧光明 or 心光明 wisdom or mental light. (2) (a) 魔光 Mra's delusive light; (b) 佛光 the true light of the Buddha. (3) (a) 常光The constant or eternal light; (b) 现起光 the light in temporary manifestations.Two kinds of purity, according to the Huayan stra; 自性净 natural purity, i.e. the natural 如 purity; and 离垢净 acquired purity through avoiding pollution.Two aspects of cause and effect, a division of the 四谛 "four noble truths" (a) 世间因果 in the present life, the 苦谛 being the effect, and the 集谛 the cause; (b) 出世间因果 in the future life, the 灭谛, extinction (of passion, or mortality) being the fruit, and the 道谛 the " eightfold noble path " the cause.Two classes of saints or, preachers: those who preach and those who preach without words.Two kinds of seed: (1) (a) 本有种子 the seed or latent undivided (moral) force immanent in the highest of the eight 识, i.e. the laya-vijna; (b) 新薰种子the newly influenced, or active seed when acted upon by the seven other 识, thus becoming productive. (2) (a) 名言种子 The so-called seed which causes moral action similar to 本有种子, e.g. good or evil seed producing good or evil deeds; (b) 业种子 karma seed, the sixth 识 acting with the eighth.Two kinds of seclusion, or retirement from the world: Bodily withdrawal into seclusion. Spiritual withdrawal from all evil, and into meditation.Two kinds of charity: (1) (a) goods; (b) the saving truth. (2) (a) 净施 Pure charity, expecting no return; (b) the opposite.Two kinds of mind: mind in its inner character and influence; in its outer manifestations.Two kinds of patience, or endurance: (a) of the assaults of nature, heat, cold, etc.; (b) of human assaults and insults.Two kinds of seed-nature, the character of the laya seed and its development: (1) (a) 性种子 The original good seed-nature; (b) 习种子 the seed-nature in practice or development. (2) (a) 本性住种性 The immanent abiding original good seed-nature; (b) 习所成种性 the seed productive according to its ground. (3) (a) 圣种性 The seed-nature of the saints, by which they attain nirvana; (b) 愚夫种性 the seed-nature in the foolish and ignorant.Two classes of Buddha's predictions of a disciple's destiny, 无余授记prediction in finality, or complete detail; 有余授记 partial, or incomplete prediction.v. 二种布施.The two kinds of death, 命尽死 natural death, and 外缘死 violent death, or death from external cause.Two classes of monks: 多闻比丘 monks who hear and repeat many stras, but are not devoted doers; 寡浅比丘 monks who read and repeat few sutras but are devoted in their lives.Two nirvanas: (1) 有余涅盘 also 有余依 That with a remnant; the cause 因 has been annihilated, but the remnant of the effect 果 still remains, so that a saint may enter this nirvana during life, but have to continue to live in this mortal realm till the death of his body. (2) 无余涅盘 or 无余依 Remnantless nirva, without cause and effect, the connection with the chain of mortal life being ended, so that the saint enters upon perfect nirva on the death of the body; cf. 智度论 31. Another definition is that Hnayna has further transmigration, while Mahyna maintains final nirvana. "Nothing remnaining" is differently interpreted in different schools, by some literally, but in Mahyna generally, as meaning no further mortal suffering, i.e. final nirva.Two forms of esoteric baptism, v. 灌.Two kinds of sickness: physical and mental or spiritual.Two kinds of relics-- the whole body, or parts of it. Also, the Buddha's physical remains or relics, and the sutras, which form his spiritual (dharmakya) remains.Monastic and lay bodhisattvas.A bodhisattva's mortal and immortal bodies.The two kinds of (spiritual) provender: charity and wisdom.The two false views, one that of a nihilistic school which denied that earthly happiness is dependent on a moral life; the other a materialistic school which maintained the moral life in the interests of self, sought earthly happiness, and failed to apprehend nirva.(二种一阐提) Two kinds of icchantika, q.v.: (a) the utterly depraved, abandoned, and blasphemers of Buddha-truth; (b) bodhisattvas who refuse to enter upon their Buddhahood in order to save all beings.The two voids, unrealities, or immaterialities; v. 空. There are several antitheses: (1) (a) 人空; 我空 The non-reality of the atman, the soul, the person; (6) 法空 the non-reality of things. (2) (a) 性空 The Tiantai division that nothing has a nature of its own; (b) 相空 therefore its form is unreal, i.e. forms are temporary names. (3) (a) 但空 Tiantai says the 藏 and 通 know only the 空; (b) 不但空 the 别 and 圆 have 空, 假, and 中 q.v. (4) (a) 如实空 The division of the 起信论 that the 如 is devoid of all impurity; (b) 如实不空 and full of all merit, or achievement.Two kinds of meditation on the 'void', or unreality: (a) 无生观 the meditation that things are unproduced, having no individual or separate natures, i.e. that all things are void and unreal; cf. 性空; (b) 无相观 that they are therefore formless, cf. 相空. Also 人 and 法空观 see above.Two kinds of reply, one by words, the other by signs.The Pure Land will not be limited to those who repeat the name of Amitbha according to his eighteenth vow; but includes those who adopt other ways (as shown in his nineteenth and twentieth vows).v. 二种子.The two bodies or elements in a stra: 文 and 义 the words and the meaning, or ideas.The two classes of offence: (a) 性罪 crime which is wrong in itself, e.g. murder, etc.; (b) 遮罪 crime not wrong in itself, e.g. taking alcohol, but forbidden by the Buddha for the sake of the other commandments; transgression of this is therefore a sin against the Buddha.Two excellent things, i.e. meditation and wisdom.A pair of wings: charity and wisdom.The two surpassing fruits, or rewards given by Buddha, i.e. final nirva and perfect enlightenment.Two kinds of praj, or wisdom. (1) (a) 共般若 The praj of the three stages of rvaka, pratyekabuddha, and imperfect Bodhisattva schools; (b) 不共般若 the praj of the perfect Bodhisattva teaching--a Tiantai division. (2) (a) 世间般若 temporal praj; (b) 出世间般若 supernatural. (3) (a) 实相般若 The first part of the Prajpramit; (b) 观照般若 the second part.The two rpakya or incantation-bodies of a Buddha, his 报身 and 应身 or sabhogakya and nirmakya, as distinguished from 法身 the dharmakya.Two kinds of suffering: within, e.g. sickness, sorrow; from without, e.g. calamities.The two piakas or tripiakas, i.e. the Buddhist canon: (a) 声闻藏 the rvaka, or Hnayna canon: (b) 菩萨藏 the Bodhisattva, or Mahyan canon.Two classes of conduct: following wrong views; following wrong desires, or emotions. There are other pairs.The two kinds of clothing: (a) 制衣 the regulation three robes for monks and five for nuns, which must be worn; (b) 听衣optional garments.Two (wrong) views: (1) Looking on people grudgingly with regard to almsgiving and preaching the Buddha-truth. (2) (a) 有见 Holding to the real existence of (material) things; (b) 无见 holding to their entire unreality. (3) (a) 断见 Holding to the view of total annihilation; (b) 常见 to that of permanence or immortality.The two universal bases of meditation: 事观 the external forms, or the phenomenal, and 理观 the real or underlying nature, i. e. practice and theory.The two enlightenments: (1) The 起信论 has two--(a) 本觉 the immanent mind in all things, e.g. "which lighteth every man that cometh into the world", also defined as the 法身 dharmakya; (b) 始觉 initial enlightenment or beginning of illumination; this initiation leads on to Buddhahood, or full enlightenment. (2) (a) 等觉 The fifty-first stage of a bodhisattva's 行 位 practice; (b) 妙觉 the fifty-second stage, or enlightenment of Buddhahood.(3) (a)自觉 A Buddha's own or natural enlightenment; (b) 觉他 his enlightening of all others.Two kinds of deliverance, <foreign lang="sa">mukti</foreign> or <foreign lang="sa">moka</foreign>: (1) (a) 有解脱 Active or earthly deliverance to arhatship; (b) 无解脱 nirvana-deliverance. (2) (a) 性净解脱 The pure, original freedom or innocence; (b) 障尽解脱 deliverance acquired by the ending of all hindrances (to salvation). (3) (a) 慧解脱 The arhat's deliverance from hindrances to wisdom; (b) 具解脱 his complete deliverance in regard to both wisdom and vision 慧 and 定. (4) (a) 时解脱 The dull who take time or are slow in attaining to 定 vision; (b) 不时解脱 the quick or clever who take "no time". (5) (a) 心解脱 A heart or mind delivered from desires; (b) 慧解脱 a mind delivered from ignorance by wisdom.Double-tongued; also 二舌.(a) 有边 That things exist; (6) 无边 that since nothing is self-existent, things cannot be said to exist. (2) (a) 增益边 The plus side, the common belief in a soul and permanence; (b) 损减边 the minus side, that nothing exists even of karma. (3) (a) 断边见 and (b) 常边见 annihilation and immortality; v. 见.The two are the divisions which took place immediately after the Buddha's death into (a) the elder monks or intimate disciples, and (b) the general body of disciples, styled respectively 上座 and 大 q.v.; the five are the divisions, which are said to have occurred a century later, into Dharma-guptah 昙无德, Mulasarvastivadah 萨婆多, Mahisasakah 弥沙塞, Kasyapiyah迦叶遣 and Vatsiputriya 姿□富罗.The two "measurings," or parts of a syllogism : (a) 现量 appearance, e.g. smoke; (b) 比量 inference, e.g. fire from smoke.Two doors, entrances, schools, etc. There are many such pairs.The two borders, or states: according to Hnayna, nirvana and mortality; according to Mahyna the two are one.The two hindrances:(1) (a) 烦恼障 The passions and delusion which aid rebirth and hinder entrance into nirvana; (b) 智障 or所知障, worldly wisdom e.g. accounting the seeming as real, a hindrance to true wisdom. (2) (a) 烦恼障 as above; (b) 解障 hindrances to deliverance. (3) (a)理障 hindrances to truth; (b) 事障 hindrances of the passions, etc.The two immediate or direct ways to perfection, as defined by Jingxi 荆溪 of the Huayan school; the gradual direct way of the Lotus; the direct way of the Huayan sutra, which is called the 顿顿顿圆, while that of the Lotus is called the 渐顿渐圆.The two kinds of food: (1) (a) The joy of the Law; (b) the bliss of meditation. (2) (a)The right kind of monk's livelihood - by mendicancy; (b) the wrong kind - by any other means.The drake and the hen of the mandarin duck who are always together, typifying various contrasted theories and ideas, e.g. permanence and impermanence, joy and sorrow, emptiness and non-emptiness, etc.The black and white rats - night and day.Yu, a preposition, in, at, etc. , similar to 於.Kujara. Name of a tree.Kujara. Name of a tree.Used in error for 干遮那摩罗.于遁; 于殿; 于; 溪丹; 屈丹; 和阗; 澳那; 瞿萨□那 Kustana, or Khotan, in Turkestan, the principal centre of Central Asian Buddhism until the Moslem invasion. Buddhism was introduced there about 200 B.C. or earlier. It was the centre from which is credited the spread of Mahayanism, v. 西城记 12.To say, speak.
