han. Later the Yuan dynasty established one at 全陵 Chin Ling, the 天界大龙翔只庆寺 which became chief of these under the Ming dynasty.The five masters or teachers, i. e. respectively of the sutras, the vinaya, the stras, the abhidharma, and meditation. A further division is made of 异世五师 and 同世五师. The first, i. e. of different periods, are Mahkyapa, nanda, Madhyntika, avsa, and Upagupta; another group connected with the Vinaya is Upli, Dsaka, Sonaka, Siggava, and Moggaliputra Tissva. The 同世 or five of the same period are variously stated: the Sarvstivdins say they were the five immediate disciples of Upagupta, i. e. Dharmagupta, etc.; see 五部.The five lions that sprang from the Buddha's five fingers; 涅盘经 16.paca-vrika-pariad, or moka-mah-parisad, v. 般. The ancient quinquennial assembly for confession and exhortation, ascribed by some to Aoka.The five means of transportation over the sea of mortality to salvation; they are the five pramits 五波罗蜜-- almsgiving, commandment-keeping, patience under provocation, zeal, and meditation.The doctrines of the 五部 q. v.The five virtues, of which there are various definitions. The five virtues required in a confessor at the annual confessional ending the rainy retreat are: freedom from predilections, from anger, from fear, not easily deceived, discernment of shirkers of confession. Another group is the five virtues for a nurse of the sick, and there are others.The five conditions of mind produced by objective perception: 卒尔心 immediate or instantaneous, the first impression; 寻求心attention, or inquiry; 决定心conclusion, decision; 染净心the effect, evil or good; 等流心the production therefrom of other causations.The five stages of bodhisattva-<foreign lang="sa">knti</foreign>, patience or endurance according to the 别教: (1) 伏忍the causes of passion and illusion controlled but not finally cut off, the condition of 十住, 十行, and 十向; (2) 信忍 firm belief, i. e. from the 初地 to the 三地; (3) 顺忍 patient progress towards the end of all mortality, i. e. 四地 to 六地; (4) 无生忍 patience for full apprehension, of the truth of no rebirth, 七地 to 九地; and (5) 寂灭忍 the patience that leads to complete nirvana, 十地 to 妙觉; cf. 五位.The five devotional gates of the Pure-land sect: (1) worship of Amitbha with the 身 body; (2) invocation with the 口 mouth; (3) resolve with the 意 mind to be reborn in the Pure-land; (4) meditation on the glories of that land, etc.; (5) resolve to bestow one's merits, e. g. works of supererogation, on all creatures.The five angry ones, idem 五大明王.The five fears of beginners in the bodhisattva-way: fear of (1) giving away all lest they should have no means of livelihood; (2) sacrificing their reputation; (3) sacrificing themselves through dread of dying; (4) falling into evil; (5) addressing an assembly, especially of men of position.The five different natures as grouped by the 法相宗 Dharmalakana sect; of these the first and second, while able to attain to non-return to mortality, are unable to reach Buddhahood; of the fourth some may, others may not reach it; the fifth will be reborn as devas or men: (1) <foreign lang="sa">rvaka</foreign>s for arhats; (2) pratyekabuddhas for <foreign lang="sa">pratyekabuddha</foreign>-hood; (3) bodhisattvas for Buddhahood; (4) indefinite; (5) outsiders who have not the Buddha mind. The <title>Sutra of Perfect Enlightenment</title> 圆觉经 has another group, i. e. the natures of (1) ordinary good people; (2) <foreign lang="sa">rvaka</foreign>s and <foreign lang="sa">pratyekabuddha</foreign>s; (3) bodhisattvas; (4) indefinite; (5) heretics.idem 法相宗.The five sins-- killing, stealing, adultery, lying, drinking intoxicants. Cf. 五戒.idem 五见.idem 五趣 and 五道.The five stages in a penitential service. Tiantai gives: (1) confession of past sins and forbidding them for the future; (2) appeal to the universal Buddhas to keep the law-wheel rolling; (3) rejoicing over the good in self and others; (4) 向 offering all one's goodness to all the living and to the Buddha-way; (5) resolve, or vows, i. e. the 四弘誓. The Shingon sect  言宗 divides the ten great vows of Samantabhadra 普贤 into five 悔, the first three vows being included under 归命 or submission; the fourth is repentance; the fifth rejoicing; the sixth, seventh, and eighth appeal to the Buddhas; the ninth and tenth, bestowal of acquired merit.The five kinds of selfishness, or meanness: monopolizing (1) an abode; (2) an almsgiving household; (3) alms received; (4) praise; (5) knowledge of the truth, e. g. of a sutra.The feelings, or passions, which are stirred by the 五根 five senses.The five delusions, idem 五钝使.paca-verama; the first five of the ten commandments, against killing, stealing, adultery, lying, and intoxicating liquors. 不杀生; 不盗; 不邪淫; 不妄语; 不酒 They are binding on laity, male and female, as well as on monks and nuns. The observance of these five ensures rebirth in the human realm. Each command has five spirits to guard its observer 五戒二十五神.The five Buddha-ketra, or dependencies, the realms, or conditions of a Buddha. They are: (1) 法性土 his dharmakya-ketra, or realm of his 'spiritual nature', dependent on and yet identical with the 如 bhutatathata; (2) 实 with its five immortal skandhas, i. e. his glorified body for his own enjoyment;. (3) 色相土 the land or condition of his self-expression as wisdom; (4) 他受用土 his sabhogakya  realm for the joy of others; (5) 变化土 the realm on which his <foreign lang="sa">nirmakya</foreign> depends, that of the wisdom of perfect service of all, which results in his relation to every kind of condition.idem 五阐提罗.The five planets, see 五星.The five skandhas, idem 五刀.A stra of Asaga 无著, also translated as the 摄大乘论, giving a description of Mahyna doctrine; Vasubandhu prepared a summary of it; tr. by 无性 Wuxiang. Translations were also made by Paramrtha and Xuanzang; other versions and treatises under various names exist.(or 五分作法) The five parts (avayava) of a syllogism: 立宗 pratij, the proposition; 辩因 hetu, the reason; 引 udharaa, the example; 合 upanaya, the application; and 结 nigamana, the summing up, or conclusion. These are also expressed in other terms, e. g. 立义; 因; 譬如; 合譬;, and 决定.The five moral laws or principles arising out of the idea of the <foreign lang="sa">mah-nirva</foreign> in the 大涅盘经 11.The five division of Buddhism according to the Huayan School, of which there are two That of 杜顺 Dushun down to 贤首 Xianshou is (1) 小乘教 Hnayna which interprets nirvana as annihilation; (2) 大乘始教 the primary stage of Mahyna, with two sections the 相始教 and 空 始教 or realistic and idealistic, (3) 大乘终教 Mahyna in its final stage, teaching the 如 and universal Buddhahood; (4) 顿教 the immediate, direct, or intuitive school, e. g. by right concentration of thought, or faith, apart from 'works'; (5) 圆教 the complete or perfect teaching of the Huayan, combining all the rest into one all-embracing vehicle. The five are now differentiated into 十宗 ten schools. The other division, by 圭 Guifeng of the same school, is (1) 人天教 rebirth as human beings for those who keep the five commandments and as devas those who keep the 十善 as 相始教  above; (4) 大乘破相教 as 空始教 above; and (5) 一乘显性教 the one vehicle which reveals the universal Buddha-nature; it includes (3), (4), and (5) of the first group. See also 五时教.The work in three juan by 法藏 Fazang of the Tang dynasty, explaining the doctrines of the Five Schools.The five Dhyni-Buddhas of the five regions; see the esoteric 五大.An abbreviation for 五五才便, i. e. 二十五才便; also the Tiantai 五方便念佛门.The five Dhyni-Buddhas of the Vajradhtu.The five infinites, or immeasurables -- body, mind, wisdom, space, and all the living-- as represented respectively by the five Dhyni Buddhas, i. e. 宝生, 阿, 无量寿, 大日, and 不空.The uninterrupted, or no-interval hell, i. e. <foreign lang="sa">avci</foreign> hell, the worst, or eighth of the eight hells. It is ceaseless in five respects-- karma and its effects are an endless chain with no escape; its sufferings are ceaseless; it is timeless; its fate or life is endless; it is ceaselessly full. Another interpretation takes the second, third, and fifth of the above and adds that it is packed with 罪器 implements of torture, and that it is full of all kinds of living beings.or 五无间罪 The five karma, or sins, leading to the <foreign lang="sa">avci</foreign>  hell v. 五逆 and 五无间.paca-bhij. The five supernatural or magical powers; six is the more common number in Chinese texts, five is the number in Ceylon; v. 五神通.(五时教) The five periods or divisions of kyamuni's teaching. According to Tiantai they are (1) 华严时 the Avatasaka or first period in three divisions each of seven days, after his enlightenment, when he preached the content, of this sutra; (2) 鹿苑时 the twelve years of his preaching the gamas 阿含 in the Deer Park; (3) 方等时 the eight years of preaching Mahyna-cum-Hnayna doctrines, the vaipulya  period; (4) 般若时 the twenty-two years of his preaching the praj or wisdom sutras; (5) 法华涅盘时 the eight years of his preaching the <title>Lotus Sutra</title> and, in a day and a night, the <title>Nirvana Sutra</title>. According to the Nirvana School (now part of the Tiantai) they are (1) 三乘别教 the period when the differentiated teaching began and the distinction of the three vehicles, as represented by the 四谛 Four Noble Truths for <foreign lang="sa">rvaka</foreign>s, the 十二因缘 Twelve Nidnas for <foreign lang="sa">pratyekabuddha</foreign>s, and the 六度 Six Pramits for bodhisattvas; (2) 三乘通教 the teaching common to all three vehicles, as seen in the 般若经; (3) 抑扬教 the teaching of the 维摩经, the 思益梵天所问经, and other sutras olling the bodhisattva teaching at the expense of that for <foreign lang="sa">rvaka</foreign>s; (4) 同归教 the common objective teaching calling all three vehicles, through the Lotus, to union in the one vehicle; (5) 常住教 the teaehmg of eternal life i. e. the revelation through the Nirvana sutra of the eternity of Buddhahood; these five are also called 有相; 无相; 抑扬; 曾三归--; and 圆常. According to 刘 Liu Chiu of the 晋 Chin dynasty, the teaching is divided into 顿 immediate and 渐 gradual attainment, the latter having five divisions called 五时教 similar to those of the Tiantai group. According to 法宝 Fabao of the Tang dynasty the five are (1) 小乘; (2) 般 or 大乘; (3) 深密 or 三乘; (4) 法华 or 一乘; (5) 涅盘 or 佛性教.A Tiantai classification of the Buddha's teaching into five periods and eight kinds of doctrine, which eight are subdivided into two groups of four each, 化仪四教 and 化法四教.paca-vidy, the five sciences or studies of India: (1) abda, grammar and composition; ilpakarmasthna, the arts and mathematics; cikits, medicine; hetu, logic; adhytma, philosophy, which Monier Williams says is the 'knoowledge of the supreme spirit, or of tman', the basis of the four Vedas; the Buddhists reckon the Tripiaka and the 十二部教 as their 明, i. e. their inner or special philosophy.The five planets, Jupiter, Mars, Saturn, Venus, and Mercury; also 五执.The five kinds of wisdom of the 言宗 Shingon School. Of the six elements 六大 earth, water, fire, air (or wind), ether (or space) 昙空, and consciousness (or mind 识 ), the first five form the phenomenal world, or Garbhadhtu, the womb of all things 胎藏界, the sixth is the conscious, or perceptive, or wisdom world, the Vajradhtu 金刚界, sometimes called the Diamond realm. The two realms are not originally apart, but one, and there is no consciousness without the other five elements. The sixth element, vijna, is further subdivided into five called the 五智 Five Wisdoms: (1) 法界体性智 <foreign lang="sa">dharmadhtu-prakti-jna</foreign>, derived from the <foreign lang="sa">amala-vijna</foreign>, or pure 识; it is the wisdom of the embodied nature of the <foreign lang="sa">dharmadhtu</foreign>, defined as the six elements, and is associated with Vairocana 大日, in the centre, who abides in this <foreign lang="sa">samdhi</foreign>; it also corresponds to the ether 空 element. (2) 大圆镜智 <foreign lang="sa">adarana-jna</foreign>, the great round mirror wisdom, derived from the <foreign lang="sa">laya</foreign>-<foreign lang="sa">vijna</foreign>, reflecting all things; corresponds to earth, and is associated with Akobhya and the east. (3) 平等性智 <foreign lang="sa">samat-jna</foreign>, derived from <foreign lang="sa">mano-vijna</foreign>, wisdom in regard to all things equally and universally; corresponds to fire, and is associated with Ratnasabhava and the south. (4) 妙观察智 <foreign lang="sa">pratyavekaa-jna</foreign>, derived from 意识, wisdom of profound insight, or discrimination, for exposition and doubt-destruction; corresponds to water, and is associated with Amitbha and the west. (5) 成所作智 <foreign lang="sa">ktynuhna-jna</foreign>, derived from the five senses, the wisdom of perfecting the double work of self-welfare and the welfare of others; corresponds to air 风 and is associated with Amoghasiddhi and the north. These five Dhyni-Buddhas are the 五智如来. The five kinds of wisdom are the four belonging to every Buddha, of the exoteric cult, to which the esoteric cult adds the first, pure, all-refecting, universal, all-discerning, and all-perfecting.五智五佛; 五佛; 五如来 The five
