      </ref>idem 五佛宝冠.Each of the Five Dhyani-Buddhas is accredited with the three forms which represent his 身业 body, 口业 speech, and 意业 mind, e. g. the embodiment of Wisdom is Vairocana, his preaching form is 普贤, and his will form is 不动明王; the embodiment 身 of the mirror is Akobhya, his 口 is Majur, his 意 is 降三世金刚; and so on; v. 五智如来.The five vases are emblems of the five departments of the Vajradhtu, and the fragrant water the wisdom of the five. Wisdom-- Buddhas.The five night watches; also the fifth watch.(五条) The monk' s robe of five patches or lengths, also termed 下衣 as the lowest of the grades of patch-robes. It is styled 院道行杂作衣 the garment ordinarily worn in the monastery, when abroad and for general purposes; also written 五帖袈裟、五条衣.The five fruits, or effects; there are various groups, e. g. I. (1) 异熟果 fruit ripening divergently, e. g. pleasure and goodness are in different categories; present organs accord in pain or pleasure with their past good or evil deeds; (2) 等流果 fruit of the same order, e. g. goodness reborn from previous goodness; (3) 土用果 present position and function fruit, the rewards of moral merit in previous lives; (4) 增上果 superior fruit, or position arising from previous earnest endeavor and superior capacity: (5) 离果 fruit of freedom from all bonds, nirvana fruit. II. Fruit, or rebirth: (1) 识 conception (viewed psychologically); (2) 名色 formation mental and physical; (3) 六处 the six organs of perception complete; (4) 触 their birth and contact with the world; (5) 受 consciousness. III. Five orders of fruit, with stones, pips, shells (as nuts), chaff-like (as pine seeds), and with pods.pacendriyi. (1) The five roots, i. e. the five organs of the senses: eyes, ears, nose, tongue, and body as roots of knowing. (2) The five spiritual organs pr positive agents: 信 faith, 精进 energy, 念 memory, 定 visionary meditation, 慧 wisdom. The 五力 q. v. are regarded as negative agents.They are the six great <foreign lang="sa">klea</foreign>, i. e. passions, or disturbers, minus 见 views, or delusions; i. e. desire, anger, stupidity (or ignorance), pride, and doubt.see 五色.faith, white; zeal, red; memory yellow; meditation, blue; and wisdom, black. These are represented inter alia in the 五色线 (or 五色缕, or 五色□, or 五色绳) the five-colored emblematic cord; this cord is also a brahman's sign worn on the shoulder and forbidden by the Buddha.The five bad dreams of King Ajtaatru on the night that Buddha entered nirvana-- as the moon sank the sun arose from the earth. the stars fell like rain, seven comets appeared, and a great conflagration filling the sky fell on the earth.The five desires, arising from the objects of the five senses, things seen, heard, smelt, tasted, or touched. Also, the five desires of wealth, sex, foodand-drink, fame, and sleep.idem 五色.五种正行 The five proper courses to ensure the bliss of the Pure Land: (1) Intone the three sutras 无量寿经, 观无量寿经, and 阿弥陀经; (2) meditate on the Pure Land; (3) worship solely Amitbha; (4) invoke his name; (5 ) extol and make offerings to him. Service of other Buddhas, etc., is styled 五 (种) 杂行.半者蒲膳尼 pacabhojanya. The five foods considered proper for monks in early Buddhism: boiled rice, boiled grain or pease, parched grain, flesh, cakes.The first five of Buddha's converts, also called 五佛子, jta-Kauinya □陈如, Avajit 额□, Bhadrika 拔提, Daabala-Kyapa 十力迦叶, and Mahnma-Kulika 摩男拘利, i. e. but there are numerous other forms of their names.pacadharma. The five laws or categories, of which four groups are as follows: I. 相名五法 The five categories of form and name: (1) 相 appearances, or phenomena; (2) 名 their names; (3) 分别 sometimes called 妄想 ordinary mental discrimination of them-- (1) and (2) are objective, (3) subjective; (4) 正智 corrective wisdom, which corrects the deficiencies and errors of the last: (5) 如如 the 如 Bhutatathata or absolute wisdom, reached through the 如理智 understanding of the law of the absolute, or ultimate truth. II. 事理五法 The five categories into which things and their principles are divided: (1) 心法 mind; (2) 心所法 mental conditions or activities; (3) 色法 the actual states or categories as conceived; (4) 不相应法 hypothetic categories, 唯识 has twenty-four, the Abhidharma fourteen; (5) 无法 the state of rest, or the inactive principle pervading all things; the first four are the 事 and the last the 理. III. 理智五法 cf. 五智; the five categories of essential wisdom: (1) 如 the absolute; (2) 大圆镜智 wisdom as the great perfect mirror reflecting all things; (3) 平等性智 wisdom of the equal Buddha nature of all beings; (4) 妙观察智 wisdom of mystic insight into all things and removal of ignorance and doubt; (5) 成所作智 wisdom perfect in action and bringing blessing to self and others. IV. 提婆五法 The five obnoxious rules of Devadatta: not to take milk in any form, nor meat, nor salt; to wear unshaped garments, and to live apart. Another set is: to wear cast-off rags, beg food, have only one set meal a day, dwell in the open, and abstain from all kinds of flesh, milk, etc.Followers of the five ascetic rules of Devadatta, the enemy of the Buddha.idem 五相成身.idem 五分法身.The five <foreign lang="sa">pramit</foreign>s (omitting the sixth, wisdom), i. e. <foreign lang="sa">dna</foreign>, almsgiving: <foreign lang="sa">la</foreign>, commandment-keeping; <foreign lang="sa">knti</foreign>, patience (under provocation): <foreign lang="sa">vrya</foreign>, zeal; and <foreign lang="sa">dhyna</foreign>, meditation.五滓; 五浑 The five kaya periods of turbidity, impurity, or chaos, i. e. of decay; they are accredited to the 住 kalpa, see 四劫, and commence when human life begins to decrease below 20,000 years. (1) 劫浊 the kalpa in decay, when it suffers deterioration and gives rise to the ensuing form; (2) 见浊 deterioration of view, egoism, etc., arising; (3) 烦恼浊 the passions and delusions of desire, anger, stupidity, pride, and doubt prevail; (4) 生浊 in consequence human miseries increase and happiness decreases; (5) 命浊 human life time gradually diminishes to ten years. The second and third are described as the 浊 itself and the fourth and fifth its results.The period of increasing turbidity or decay; see 五浊.The five 'seas' or infinities seen in a vision by Puxian, v. 旧华严经 3, viz., (1) all worlds, (2) all the living, (3) universal karma, (4) the roots of desire and pleasure of all the living, (5) all the Buddhas, past, present, and future.Baptism with water of the five vases 五 representing the wisdom of the five Buddhas 五佛.The five Teng-lu are (1) 传灯录 A. D 1004-8; (2) 广灯录; (3) 读灯录; (4) 联灯录, and (5) 普灯录; the 灯录会元 and 灯录严统 are later collections.The five burnings, or 五痛 five pains, i. e. infraction of the first five commandments leads to state punishment in this life and the hells in the next.Five rebirths, i. e. five states, or conditions of a bodhisattva's rebirth: (1) to stay calamities, e. g. by sacrificing himself; (2) in any class that may need him; (3) in superior condition, handsome, wealthy, or noble; (4) in various grades of kingship; (5) final rebirth before Buddhahood; v. 瑜伽论 4.idem 五怖畏.idem 五烧.pacaata. Five hundred, of which there are numerous instances, e. g. 500 former existences; the 500 disciples, etc.or 五百生 500 generations.A disciple who even passes the wine decanter to another person will be reborn without hands for 500 generations; v. 梵网经下.The 'five hundred ' rules for nuns, really 348, viz. 8 波罗夷, 17 僧残, 30 舍堕, 178 单提, 8 提舍尼, 100 学, and 7 灭诤.idem 五百世.The 500 yojanas of difficult and perilous journey to the Land of Treasures: v. the <title>Lotus Sutra</title>.(五百大罗汉) 500 great arhats who formed the synod under Kanika and are the supposed compilers of the <title>Abhidharma-mahvibh-stra</title>, 400 years after Buddha entered nirvana (阿毗达磨大毗婆娑论), tr. by Xuanzang (A. D. 656-9). The 500 Lohans found in some monasteries have various definitions.五百小乘; 五百异部 The 500 sects according to the 500 years after the Buddha's death; 智度论 63.(五百问事) The 500 questions of Mah-maudgalyyana to the Buddha on discipline.The five covers, i. e. mental and moral hindrances-- desire, anger, drowsiness, excitability, doubt.The mental and physical sufferings arising from the full-orbed activities of the skandhas 五阴, one of the eight sufferings; also 五阴盛 (五阴盛苦).idem 五相成身 and 五衰.(五相成身观) A contemplation of the five stages in Vairocana Buddhahood-- entry into the bodhi-mind; maintenance of it; attainment of the diamond mind; realization of the diamond embodiment; and perfect attainment of Buddhahood. It refers also to the 五智 of the Vairocana group; also 五转成身 (or 五法成身) .The five kinds of eyes or vision: human; <foreign lang="sa">deva</foreign>  (attainable by men in <foreign lang="sa">dhyna</foreign>); Hnayna wisdom; bodhisattva truth; and Buddha-vision or omniscience. There are five more relate to omniscience making 十眼 ten kinds of eyes or vision.The five <foreign lang="sa">indriya</foreign>s or organs of perception-- eyes, ears, nose, tongue, and skin. v. 五根.idem 五障.The five patriarchs. Those of the Huayan (Kegon) sect are 终南杜顺; 云华智俨; 贤首法藏; 凉澄观, and 圭宗密. The Pure-land sect five patriarchs are 昙鸾; 道绰; 善导; 怀感 and 少康. The 莲社 (白莲社) Lianshe sect has 善导; 法照; 少康; 省常, and 宗赜.(or 五神变) pacabhij; also 五通 (力) the five supernatural powers. (1 ) 天眼通 (天眼智证通)  divyacakus ; deva-vision, instantaneous view of anything anywhere in the form-realm. (2) 天耳通 (天耳智证通) divyarotra, ability to hear any sound anywhere. (3) 他心通 (他心智证通) paracitta-jna, ability to know the thoughts of all other minds. (4) 宿命通 (宿命智证通) prvanivsnusmti-jna, knowledge of all formed existences of self and others. (5) 神通 (神通智证通) 通; 神足通; 神如意通 ddhi-sktkriy, power to be anywhere or do anything at will. See 智度论 5. Powers similar to these are also attainable by meditation, incantations, and drugs, hence heterodox teachers also may possess them.idem 五戒.The five kinds; but frequently the 种 is omitted, e. g. for 五种正食 see 五正食.The five modes of trisarana, or formulas of trust in the Triratna, taken by those who (1) 翻邪 turn from heresy; (2) take the five commandments; (3) the eight commandments; (4) the ten commandments; (5) the complete commandments.The five kinds of sexually incomplete females, 螺, 筋, 鼓, 角, and . v. 大藏法数 32.The five kinds of 般荼迦 <foreign lang="sa">paaka</foreign>s, i. e. eunuchs, or impotent males: by birth; emasculation; uncontrollable emission; hermaphrodite; impotent for half the month; they are known as 扇搋 Sandha; 留□ ? Runda; 伊梨沙掌□ Irypaaka; 半择迦 Paaka; 博叉 Pakapaaka; there are numerous subdivisions.The five kinds of terms which Xuanzang did not translate but transliterated-- the esoteric (such as 陀罗尼); those with several meanings (such as 薄伽梵); those without equivalent in China (such as 阎浮树); old-established terms (such as 阿耨菩提); and those which would be less impressive when translated.The five kinds of <foreign lang="sa">angmin</foreign>s 那含, who never return to the desire-realm: (1) 中般 the <foreign lang="sa">angmin</foreign> who enters on the intermediate stage between the realm of desire and the higher realm of form; (2) 生般 who is born into the form world and soon overcomes the remains of illusion; (3) 有行般 who diligently works his way through the final stages; (4) 无行般 whose final departure is delayed through lack of aid and slackness; (5) 上流般 who proceeds from lower to higher heavens into nirvana. Also 五种那含 and 五种般 the 般 being 'Parinirva'.Five kinds of esoteric ceremonial, i. e. (1) 扇底迦 ntika, for stopping calamities; (2) 布瑟徵迦 or 补瑟徵迦 pauika, for success or prosperity; (3) 阿畏遮迦 abhicraka, for suppressing, or exorcising; (4) 阿羯沙尼 kara, for calling, or attracting (good beings, or aid); (5) 伐施迦罗轨 vakaraa, for seeking the aid of Buddhas and bodhisattvas; also 五部尊法 and cf. 五种灌顶.The signs of the five kinds of vision, v. 五眼.The five kinds of <foreign lang="zh">weishi</foreign>, or idealistic representation in the sutras and stras as summed up by Cien 慈恩 of the 法相宗 Dharmalakana school: (1) 境唯识 wisdom or insight in objective conditions; (2) 教唯识 in interpretation; (3) 理唯识 in principles; (4) 行唯识 in meditation and practice; (5) 果唯识 in the fruits or results of Buddhahood. The first