ognized law, old age from birth; (5) 因果比量 from cause and effect, that a traveler has a destination.The five kinds of masters of the Law, v. <title>Lotus Sutra</title>, 法师品-- one who receives and keeps; reads; recites; expounds; and copies the sutra.The Huayan school's five forms of <foreign lang="sa">dharmadhtu</foreign>: (1) 有法界 or 事世界 the phenomenal realm; (2) 无法界 or 理世界 the dependent and interactive; the inactive, quiescent, or noumenal realm; (3) 亦有亦无世界 or 事理无碍世界, both, i.e., interdependent and interactive; (4) 非有非无世界 either active nor inactive, but it is also 事理无碍世界, e. g. water and wave, wave being water and water wave; (5) 无障碍世界 or 事事无碍世界 the unimpeded realm, the unity of the phenomenal and noumenal, of the collective and individual.The five kinds of a Buddha's <foreign lang="sa">dharmakya</foreign>. There are four groups. I. (1) 如如智法身 the spiritual body of <foreign lang="sa">bhtatathat</foreign>-wisdom; (2) 功德法身 of all virtuous achievement; (3) 自法身 of incarnation in the world; (4) 变化法身 of unlimited powers of transformation; (5) 虚空法身 of unlimited space; the first and second are defined as <foreign lang="sa">sabhogakya</foreign>, the third and fourth as <foreign lang="sa">nirmakya</foreign>, and the fifth as the <foreign lang="sa">dharmakya</foreign>, but all are included under <foreign lang="sa">dharmakya</foreign> as it possesses all the others. II. The esoteric cult uses the first four and adds as fifth 法界身 indicating the universe as pan-Buddha. III. Huayan gives (1) 法性生身 the body or person of Buddha born from the dharma-nature. (2) 功德生身 the <foreign lang="sa">dharmakya</foreign> evolved by Buddha virtue, or achievement; (3) 变化法身 the <foreign lang="sa">dharmakya</foreign> with unlimited powers of transformation; (4) 实相法身 the real <foreign lang="sa">dharmakya</foreign>; (5) 虚 空法身 the universal <foreign lang="sa">dharmakya</foreign>. IV. Hnayna defines them as 五分法身 q. v.The five abhiecan baptisms of the esoteric school-- for ordaining <foreign lang="sa">crya</foreign>s, teachers, or preachers of the Law: for admitting disciples: for putting an end to calamities or suffering for sins; for advancement, or success; and for controlling (evil spirits ) or getting rid of difficulties, cf. 五种修法. Also, baptism of light: of sweet dew (i. e. perfume): of the 'germ-word' as seed; of the five baptismal signs of wisdom made on the forehead, shoulders, heart, and throat, indicating the five Dhyni-Buddhas; and of the ' true word' on the breast.see 五种不还.The five 'stores', or the five differentiations of the one Buddha-nature; (1) 如来藏 the Tathgata-nature, which is the fundamental universal nature possessed by all the living: (2) 正法藏 the source or treasury of all right laws and virtues: (3) 法身藏 the storehouse of the <foreign lang="sa">dharmakya</foreign> obtained by all saints: (4) 出世藏 the eternal spiritual nature, free from earthly errors; (5) 自性净藏 the storehouse of the pure Buddha-nature. Another similar group is 如来藏, 法界藏, 法身藏, 出世间上上藏, and 自性净藏.The acts of the 五种法师 q. v.; also idem 五正行.The five kinds of those who have testified to Buddhism; also 五人说经; 五说; i. e. the Buddha,. his disciples, the <foreign lang="sa">i</foreign>s, <foreign lang="sa">deva</foreign>s, and incarnate beings. Also, the Buddha, sages, <foreign lang="sa">deva</foreign>s, supernatural beings, and incarnate beings. Also, the Buddha, bodhisattvas, <foreign lang="sa">rvaka</foreign>s, men, and things. See 五类说法.Five kinds of supernatural power: (1) 道通 of bodhisattvas through their insight into truth; (2) 神通 of arhats through their mental concentration; (3) 依通 supernatural or magical powers dependent on drugs, charms, incantations, etc.; (4) 报通 or 业通 reward or karma powers of transformation possessed by <foreign lang="sa">deva</foreign>s, <foreign lang="sa">nga</foreign>s, etc.; (5) 妖通 magical power of goblins, satyrs, etc.v. 五种不还.The five kinds of bells used by the Shingon sect in Japan, also called 金刚铃, i. e. 五钴铃, 卖铃, 一钴. 三钴铃, 塔铃; the different names are derived from their handles; the four first named, beginning with the five-pronged one, are placed each at a corner of the altar, the last in the middle.The five <foreign lang="sa">mra</foreign>s associated with the five skandhas; also 五蕴魔; 五阴魔, 五魔.(五秘) The five esoteric or occult ones, i. e. the five bodhisattvas of the diamond realm, known as Vajrasattva in the middle; 欲 desire on the east; 触 contact, south; 爱 love, west; and 慢 pride, north. Vajrasattva represents the six fundamental elements of sentient existence and here indicates the birth of bodhisattva sentience; desire is that of bodhi and the salvation of all: contact with the needy world for its salvation follows; love of all the living comes next; pride or the power of nirvana succeeds.or 十七尊曼荼罗 The maala of this group contains seventeen figures representing the five above named, with their twelve subordinates.The five arrows, i. e. the five desires 五欲.The five groups of five each of the consonants in the syllabary called 悉昙 Siddha.The five kinds of <foreign lang="sa">deva</foreign>s: (1) 上界天 in the upper realms of form and non-form; (2) 虚空天 in the sky, i. e. four of the six <foreign lang="sa">deva</foreign>s of the desire-realm; (3) 地居天 on the earth, i. e. the other two of the six <foreign lang="sa">deva</foreign>s, on Sumeru; (4) 游虚天空 wandering <foreign lang="sa">deva</foreign>s of the sky, e. g. sun, moon, starvas, (5) 地下天 under-world <foreign lang="sa">deva</foreign>s, e. g. <foreign lang="sa">nga</foreign>s, <foreign lang="sa">asura</foreign>s, <foreign lang="sa">mra</foreign>s, etc. Of. 五大明王.The five preachers in the <title>Huayan sutra</title>: the Buddha; bodhisattvas; <foreign lang="sa">rvaka</foreign>s; the <foreign lang="sa">deva</foreign>s in their praise songs; and material things, e. g. the <foreign lang="sa">bodhi</foreign>-tree; v. 五种说人.The five suspended corpses, or dead snakes, hanging from the four limbs and neck of Mara as Papiyan; v. Nirvana sutra 6.A monk's garment of patches.The five bonds to mortality: 贫 desire, 恚 hata, 慢 pride, 嫉 envy, 悭 grudging.One of Indra's musicians who praised Buddha on a crystal lute; v. 中阿含经 33.The five films, or interceptors of the light of sun and moon-- smoke, cloud dust, fog, and the hands of <foreign lang="sa">asura</foreign>s.(五股杵 or 五股金刚); also 五钴, 五古, or 五M029401 The five-pronged vajra or thunderbolt emblem of the 五部 five groups and 五智 five wisdom powers of the vajradhtu; doubled it is an emblem of the ten pramits. In the esoteric cult the 五股印 five-pronged vajra is the symbol of the 五智 five wisdom powers and the 五佛 five Buddhas, and has several names 五大印, 五智印, 五印; 金刚慧印, 大羯印, and 大率都婆印, and has many definitions.The five primary colors, also called 五正色 (or 五大色):  blue, 黄 yellow, 赤 red, 白 white, 黑 black. The 五间色 or compound colors are 绯 crimson, 红, scarlet, 紫 purple, 绿 green, 黄 brown. The two sets correspond to the cardinal points as follows: east, blue and green; west, white, and crimson; south, red and scarlet; north, black and purple; and center, yellow and brown. The five are permutated in various ways to represent various ideas.The five forms of suffering: I. (1) Birth, age, sickness, death; (2) parting with those loved; (3) meeting with the hated or disliked; (4) inability to obtain the desired; (5) the five skandha sufferings, mental and physical. II. Birth, age, sickness, death, and the shackles (for criminals). III. The sufferings of the hells, and as hungry ghosts, animals, asuras, and human beings.idem 五辛.The five <foreign lang="sa">bodhi</foreign>, or stages of enlightenment: (1) 发心菩提 resolve on supreme bodhi; (2) 伏心菩提 mind control, i. e. of the passions and observance of the <foreign lang="sa">pramit</foreign>s: (3) 明心菩提 mental enlightenment, study, and increase in knowledge and in the prajpramit: (4) 出到菩提 mental expansion, freedom from the limitations of reincarnation and attainment of complete knowledge; (5) 无上菩提 attainment of a passionless condition and of supreme perfect enlightenment;.The five <foreign lang="sa">skandha</foreign>s, paca-skandha: also 五阴; 五; 五塞犍陀 The five cumulations, substances, or aggregates, i. e. the components of an intelligent being, specially a human being: (1) 色 <foreign lang="sa">rpa</foreign>, form, matter, the physical form related to the five organs of sense; (2) 受 <foreign lang="sa">vedana</foreign>, reception, sensation, feeling, the functioning of the mind or senses in connection with affairs and things; (3) 想 <foreign lang="sa">saj</foreign>, conception, or discerning; the functioning of mind in distinguishing; (4) 行 <foreign lang="sa">saskra</foreign>, the functioning of mind in its processes regarding like and dislike, good and evil, etc.; (5) 识 <foreign lang="sa">vijna</foreign>, mental faculty in regard to perception and cognition, discriminative of affairs and things. The first is said to be physical, the other four mental qualities; (2), (3), and (4) are associated with mental functioning, and therefore with 心所; (5) is associated with the faculty or nature of the mind 心王 manas. Eitel gives-- form, perception, consciousness, action, knowledge. See also Keith's <title>Buddhist Philosophy</title>, 85-91.(or 五阴世间 or 五世间) The worlds in which the five <foreign lang="sa">skandha</foreign>s exist.The abode of the five <foreign lang="sa">skandha</foreign>s-- the human body.大乘五蕴论 A stra by Vasubandhu on the Mahyna interpretation of the five skandhas, tr. by Xuanzang; 1 chuan. Other works are the 五蕴皆空经 tr. by Yijing of the Tang dynasty. 五蕴譬经 tr. by 安世高 An Shih Kao of the Han dynasty: both are in the 杂阿含经 2 and 10 respectively; also 五蕴论释 a commentary by Vintaprabha.The Mara of the <foreign lang="sa">skandha</foreign>s, v. 五种魔.The five lines of conduct. I. According to the 起信论 <title>Awakening of Faith</title> they are almsgiving; keeping the commandments; patience under insult; zeal or progress; meditation. II. According to the 涅盘经 <title>Nirvana Sutra</title> they are saintly or bodhisattva deeds; arhat, or noble deeds; deva deeds; children's deeds (i. e. normal good deeds of men, <foreign lang="sa">deva</foreign>s, and Hinayanists); sickness conditions, e. g. illness, delusion, etc.; -- into all these lines of conduct and conditions a Bodhisattva enters. III. The five elements, or tanmtra-- wood, fire, earth, metal, and water; or earth, water, ire, air, and ether (or space) as taught by the later Mahyna philosophy; idem 五大.The five Yanas or Vehicles, idem 五乘.The five garments worn by a nun are the three worn by a monk: with two others.The five signs of decay or approaching death, of which descriptions vary. e. g. uncontrolled discharges, flowers on the head wither. unpleasant odor, sweating armpits, uneasiness (or anxiety); <title>Nirvana Sutra</title> 19.The five wrong views: (1) 身见 <foreign lang="sa">satkya-di</foreign>, i. e. 我见 and 我所见 the view that there is a real self, an ego, and a mine and thine: (2) 边见 <foreign lang="sa">antar-grha</foreign>, extreme views. e. g. extinction or permanence; (3) 邪见 <foreign lang="sa">mithy</foreign>, perverse views, which, denying cause and effect, destroy the foundations of morality; (4) 见取见 <foreign lang="sa">di-parmara</foreign>, stubborn perverted views, viewing inferior things as superior, or counting the worse as the better; (5) 戒禁取见 <foreign lang="sa">la-vrata-parmara</foreign>, rigid views in favour of rigorous ascetic prohibitions, e. g. covering oneself with ashes. Cf. 五利使.The five meditations referred to in the <title>Lotus Sutra</title> 25: (1)  on the true, idem 空观, to meditate on the reality of the void or infinite, in order to be rid of illusion in views and thoughts; (2) 净观 on purity, to be rid of any remains of impurity connected with the temporal, idem 假观; (3) 广大智慧观 on the wider and greater wisdom, idem 中观, by study of the 'middle' way; (4) 悲观 on pitifulness, or the pitiable condition of the living, and by the above three to meditate on their salvation; (5) 慈观 on mercy and the extension of the first three meditations to the carrying of joy to all the living.The five <foreign lang="sa">bodhi</foreign>, or states of enlightenment, as described in the 起信论 <title>Awakening of Faith</title>; see also 五菩提 for a different group. (1) 本觉 Absolute eternal wisdom, or <foreign lang="sa">bodhi</foreign>; (2) 始觉 <foreign lang="sa">bodhi</foreign> in its initial stages, or in action, arising from right observances; (3) 相似觉 bodhisattva. attainment of <foreign lang="sa">bodhi</foreign> in action, in the 十信; (4) 随分觉 further bodhisattva-enlightenment according to capacity, i. e. the stages 十住, 十行, and 十向; (5) 究竟觉 final or complete enlightenment, i. e. the stage of 妙觉, which is one with the first, i. e. 本觉. The 本觉 is bodhi in the potential, 始觉 is <foreign lang="sa">bodhi</foreign> in the active state, hence (2), (3), (4), and (5) are all the latter, but the fifth has reached the perfect quiescent stage of original <foreign lang="sa">bodhi</foreign>.The five wheels of liberation, or salvation, i. e. the five maalas in which are the Five Dhyni-Buddhas, see 五智如来; also called五大月轮 and五轮塔婆.It idem 五部大论.The five <foreign lang="sa">parijna</foreign>s, perceptions or cognitions; ordinarily those arising from the five senses, i. e. of form-and-color, sound, smell, taste, and touch. The 起信论 <title>Awakening of Faith</title> has a different set of five steps in the history of cognition; (1) 业识 initial functioning of mind under the influence of the original 无明 unenlightenment or state of ignorance; (2) 转识 the act of turning towards the apparent object for its observation; (3) 现识 observation of the object as it appears; (4) 知识 the deductions derived from its appearance; (5) 相续识 the consequent feelings of like or dislike, pleasure or pain, from which arise the delusions and incarnations.idem 五种说人.idem 五音.The five axioms: (1) 因谛 the cause, which is described as 集谛 of the Four Noble Truths; (2) 果谛 the effect as 苦谛; (3) 智谛 or 能知谛 diagnosis as 道谛; (4) 境谛 or 所知谛 the end or cure as 灭谛; to these add (5) 胜谛 or 至谛, the supreme axiom, i. e. the 如; v. 四谛.The five <foreign lang="sa">gati</foreign>, i. e. destinations, destinies: the hells, hungry ghosts, animals, human beings, <foreign lang="sa">deva</foreign>s; cf. 五恶趣 and 五道.A series of pictures to show the course of life and death, ascribed in the <title>Sarvstivda Vinaya</title> 34 to the Buddha.see 五种法身.The five evolutions, or developments; (1) resolve on Buddhahood; (2) observance of the rules; (3) attainment of enlightenment; (4) of nirvana; (5) of power to aid others according to need.idem 五相成身.The above five developments are given the colors respectively of yellow, red, white, black, and blue (or green), each color being symbolic, e. g. yellow of Vairocana, red of Majur, etc.The five wheels, or things that turn: I. The 五体 or five members, i. e. the knees, the elbows, and the head; when all are placed on the ground it implies the utmost respect. II. The five foundations of the world. first and lowest the wheel or circle of space; above are those of wind; of water; the diamond, or earth; on these rest the nine concentric circles and eight seas. III. The esoteric sect uses the term for the 五大 five elements, earth, water, fire, wind, and space; also for the 五解脱轮 q. v. IV. The five fingers (of a Buddha).The five are the 五大 five elements, to which the sixth 大 is added, i. e. the six elements, earth, water, fire, air and space, and 识 intelligence or mind.(五轮率塔婆) A <foreign lang="sa">stpa</foreign> with five wheels at the top; chiefly used by the Shingon sect on graves as indicating the indwelling Vairocana.五轮三摩地 A meditation of the esoteric school on the five elements, earth, water, fire, air, and space, with their germ-words, their forms (i. e. square, round, triangular, half-moon, and spherical), and their colors (i. e. yellow, white, red, black, and blue). The five wheels also represent the Five Dhyni-Buddhas, v. 五智. The object is that 五轮成身 the individual may be united with the five Buddhas, or Vairocana.The fifth wheel limit, or world foundation, i. e. that of space.The five forbidden pungent roots, 五荤 garlic, three kinds of onions, and leeks; if eaten raw they are said to cause irritability of temper, and if eaten cooked, to act as an aphrodisiac; moreover, the breath of the eater, if reading the sutras, will drive away the good spirits.pacnantarya; 五无间业 The five rebellious acts or deadly sins, parricide, matricide, killing an arhat, shedding the blood of a Buddha, destroying the harmony of the sangha, or fraternity. The above definition is common both to Hnayna and Mahyna. The lightest of these sins is the first; the heaviest the last. II. Another group is: (1) sacrilege, such as destroying temples, burning sutras, stealing a Buddha's or a monk's things, inducing others to do so, or taking pleasure therein; (2) slander, or abuse of the teaching of <foreign lang="sa">rvaka</foreign> s, <foreign lang="sa">pratyekabuddha</foreign>s, or bodhisattvas; (3) ill-treatment or killing of a monk; (4) any one of the five deadly sins given above; (5) denial of the karma consequences of ill deeds, acting or teaching others accordingly, and unceasing evil life. III. There are also five deadly sins, each of which is equal to each of the first set of five: (1) violation of a mother, or a fully ordained nun; (2) killing a bodhisattva in a sangha; (5) destroying a Buddha's <foreign lang="sa">stpa</foreign>. IV. The five unpardonable sin of Devadatta who (1) destroyed the harmony of the community; (2) injured kyamuni with a stone, shedding his blood; (3) induced the king to let loose a rutting elephant to trample down kyamuni; (4) killed a nun; (5) put poison on his finger-nails and saluted kyamuni intending to destroy him thereby.v. 五神通.One who by non-Buddhistic methods has attained to the five supernatural powers 五通.Spirits possessed of the five supernatural powers. They are also identified five bodhisattvas of the 鸡头摩: monastery in India, who, possessed of supernatural powers, went to the Western Paradise and begged the image of Maitreya, whence it is said to have been spread over India.The five universal mental activities associated with every thought-- the idea, mental contact, reception, conception, perception, 作意, 触, 受, 想, 思; cf. 五蕴.idem 五趣.There is difference of statement whether there are five or six <foreign lang="sa">gati</foreign>, i. e. ways or destinies; if six, then there is added the <foreign lang="sa">asura</foreign>, a being having functions both good and evil, both deva and demon.An officer in the retinue of the ten kings of Hades.A general in the retinue of the ten kings of Hades, who keeps the book of life.One of the ten kings of Hades who retries the sufferers on their third year of imprisonment.idem 五净居天.(五邪) The five improper ways of gain or livelihood for a monk, i. e. (1) changing his appearance, e. g. theatrically; (2) advertising his own powers and virtue; (3) fortuning by physiognomy, etc.; (4) hectoring and bullying; (5) praising the generosity of another to induce the hearer to bestow presents.The five classes, or groups  I. The 四谛 four truths, which four are classified as 见道 or theory, and 修道 practice, e. g. the eightfold path. II. The five early Hnayna sects, see 一切有部 or Sarvastivadah. III. The five groups of the Vajradhtu maala.(居 炎 摩 罗) Yama as protector in the retinue of the thousand-hand Guanyin.To cut off the five classes of misleading things, i. e. four 见 and one 修, i. e. false theory in regard to the 四谛 four truths, and erroneous practice. Each of the two classes is extended into each of the three divisions of past, three of present, and three of future, making eighteen mental conditions.The five chief Mahyna sutras according to Tiantai are: 华严经; 大集经; 大品般若经; 法华经, and 涅盘经, i. e. Avatasaka, Mahsanghta, Mahprajpramit, Lotus, and Nirvana sutras.Asaga, founder of the Yogcra school, is said, by command of Maitreya, to have edited the five great stras, 瑜伽师地论, 分别瑜伽论, 大乘庄严经论, 辨中论颂论, and 金刚般若论.五种坛法 (or 五部护摩 or 五部悉地). Ceremonials of the esoteric cult for ridding from calamity; for prosperity; subduing evil (spirits); seeking the love of Buddhas; calling the good to aid; cf. 五种修法.The five Dhyni-Buddhas, v. 五智如来.The first five Hnayna sects-- Dharmagupta, Sarvstivda, Mahsaka, Kyapya, and Vtsputrya; see 五师.The five Dhyni-Buddhas   v.五 智 如 来.idem 五部尊法.idem 五部尊法.The five graduated series of universes: (1) 三千大千世界 <foreign lang="sa">tri-sahasra-mah-sahasra-loka-dhtu</foreign>; a universe, or chiliocosm; (2) such chiliocosms, numerous as the sands of Ganges, form one Buddha-universe; (3) an aggregation of these forms a Buddha-universe ocean; (4) an aggregation of these latter forms a Buddha-realm seed; (5) an infinite aggregation of these seeds forms a great Buddha-universe, 智度论 50. Another division is (1) a world, or universe; (2) a Buddha-nature universe, with a different interpretation; and the remaining three areas above, the sea, the seed, and the whole Buddha-universe.The five banks of clouds or obstructions for a woman, see 五障.The five heavy blockages, or serious hindrances; see 五钝使 infra.paca-klea 五重滞; 五惑 The five dull, unintelligent, or stupid vices or temptations: 贪 desire, 嗔 anger or resentment, 痴 stupidity or foolishness, 慢 arrogance, 疑 doubt. Overcoming these constitutes the <foreign lang="sa">paca-la</foreign>, five virtues, v. 尸罗. Of the ten 十使 or agents the other five are styled 五利 keen, acute, intelligent, as they deal with higher qualities.(五股金刚杵, 五钴金刚) The five-armed vajra, 五智金刚杵; 五金刚杵, 五光明; emblem of the powers of the 五智如来 q. v.idem 五停心观; there is also a fivefold meditation on impermanence, suffering, the void, the non-ego, and nirvana.five compound colors are 绯 crimson, 红, scarlet, 紫 purple, 绿 green, 黄 brown.
The five compound colours, v. 五色.The five <foreign lang="sa">ahil</foreign>s, i. e. five bad monks who died, went to the hells, and were reborn as <foreign lang="sa">ahil</foreign>s or imperfect males; also 五扇提罗.五 see 五蕴. 阴 is the older term.idem 五蕴世间.(五阴盛苦)  idem 五盛阴苦.idem 五蕴魔.(五阿含经) The five Agamas, 五阿笈魔, i. e. (1) 长阿含经 <title>Drghgama</title>; (2) 中阿含经 <title>Madhyamgama</title>; (3) 僧育多阿含经 <title>Samyuktgama</title>; (4) 鸯掘多罗阿含经 <title>Ekottarikgama</title>, and (5) 屈陀伽阿合经 <title>Kudrakgama</title>.The five hindrances, or obstacles; also 五碍; 五云. I. Of women, i. e. inability to become Brahma-kings, Indras, Mra-kings, Caikravarti-kings, or Buddhas. II. The hindrances to the five 五力 powers, i. e. (self-) deception a bar to faith, as sloth is to zeal, anger to remembrance, hatred to meditaton, and discontent to wisdom. III. The hindrances of (1) the passion-nature, e. g. original sin; (2) of karma caused in previous lives; (3) the affairs of life; (4) no friendly or competent preceptor; (5) partial knowledge.The five hindrances to woman, see above, and her three subordinations, i. e. to father, husband. and son.The five musical tones, or pentatonic scale-- do, re, mi, sol, la; also 五声; 五调子.pacaikha, the five locks on a boy's head; also used for 五佛顶尊 q. v.idem Wu-Tai Shan 五台.idem 五佛顶尊.The five kinds of spiritual food by which roots of goodness are nourished: correct thoughts; delight in the Law; pleasure in meditation; firm resolve, or vows of self-control; and deliverance from the karma of illusion.The incense composed of five ingredients (sandalwood, aloes, cloves, saffron, and camphor) offered by the esoteric sects in building their altars and in performing their rituals. Cf. 五分香.The five c, topknots or locks, emblems of the 五智 q. v.A five-pointed crown with a meaning similar to 五髻.Majur of the five locks.A well.Like ladling the moon out of the well; the parable of the monkeys who saw the moon fallen into a well, and fearing there would be no more moonlight, sought to save it; the monkey-king hung on to a branch, one hung on to his tail and so on, but the branch broke and all were drowned.The flower of the water, i. e. that drawn from the well in the last watch of the night, at which time the water is supposed not to produce animal life.'Like the well and the river', indicating the impermanence of life. The 'well ' refers to the legend of the man who running away from a mad elephant fell into a well; the 'river ' to a great tree growing on the river bank yet blown over by the wind.Second, inferior; used in translit. as 阿 '<foreign lang="sa">a</foreign>', e. g. 亚 rya.Haste, urgency.Leather sandals.Gone, lost, dead, ruined; not.The things left behind at death by any one of the five orders of monks or nuns; clothing, etc., being divided among the other monks or nuns; valuables and land, etc., going to the establishment.Dead; the dead.The soul of the dead.Interlock, intersect; crossed; mutual; friendship; to hand over, pay.交付 To hand over, entrust to.To hand over charge of a hall, or monastery.To hand over and check (as in the case of an inventory).束芦 A tripod of three rushes or canes-- an illustration of the mutuality of cause and effect, each cane depending on the other at the point of intersection.A curtain festooned with jewels, resembling hanging dewdrops.Also; moreover.Both reality and unreality (or, relative and absolute, phenomenal and non-phenomenal), a term for the middle school; Mdhyamika.Offer up; enjoy.The hall of offerings, an ancestral hall.Enmity and friendship.
