he sixteenth patriarch.Monastic companions, or company.Monks and the laity.<term lang="sa">sghika</term>, relating to a <foreign lang="sa">sagha</foreign>; a complete set of land and buildings for a monastery.Sghik-vinaya, the rules for monks and nuns.<term lang="sa">sakakik</term> or <term lang="sa">uttarasagh</term>, described as a kind of toga passed over the left shoulder and under the right armpit; also 僧迦; 僧竭支; 僧崎; 僧欹迦; 只支; 竭支.Monastic possessions, or things.Sghik, the Mahsghik school, v. 大部.Name of 慧可 Huike, second patriarch of the Intuitive School.铄 <term lang="sa">saklea</term>, whatever defiles, e.g. the passions.僧房 A <term lang="sa">vihra</term>, or <term lang="sa">saghrma</term>, a monastery; also a nunnery.<term lang="sa">saskra</term>, impressions resulting from action, the fourth <foreign lang="sa">skandha</foreign>.Director of monks, an official first appointed by the government in the fourth century A.D.; then and later the office was called 僧正; 僧统; 僧录 (僧录司).<term lang="sa">sagha</term>, the idealized church, the third member of the <foreign lang="sa">triratna</foreign>.The perfect <foreign lang="sa">arhat</foreign> who has not to be reborn.Monks and nuns.The ten prohibitions; the complete commands for monks.<term lang="sa">sasktam</term>, which means composite, compounded, perfected, but intp. as active, phenomenal, causally produced, characterized by birth, existence, change, and death.idem僧迦舍. <term lang="sa">skya</term>.In order of monastic age, according to years of ordination.The Director or Pope of monks; an office under Wudi, A.D. 502550, of the Liang dynasty, for the control of the monks. Wendi, 560-7, of the Ch'en dynasty appointed a 大僧统 or Director over the monks in his capital.<term lang="sa">saghvaea</term>; Pali, <term lang="pi">saghdiea</term>. A sin of an ordained person, requiring open confession before the assembly for absolution, or riddance 残; failing confession, dismissal from the order. Thirteen of these sins are of sexual thoughts, or their verbal expression, also greed, even for the sake of the order, etc.The 15th of the 7th month; the last day of the summer retreat, on which the monks confessed their sins.<term lang="sa">saj</term>; <term lang="sa">saj</term>, the third of the five <foreign lang="sa">skandha</foreign>s, i.e. 想 thought, ideation, consciousness.<term lang="sa">siha</term>, a lion, also 僧伽.Skya, an ancient kingdom and city in Northern India (v. Kapitha 劫). The modern Samkassam, now a village 45 miles north-west of Kanauj. Also 僧伽施.(僧那僧涅) <term lang="sa">sannha</term> (<term lang="sa">-sannaddha</term>), girding on armour, intp. as a Buddha's or <foreign lang="sa">bodhisattva</foreign>'s great Vow.Stiff, rigid; prostrate.<term lang="sa">sasra</term>, course, transmigration, v. 散 and 生死.Perverse, base, depraved; partial, prejudiced; rustic, secluded.Perverse, incorrect, or depraved views.A scholar; learned. Confucian.Learned-youth Bodhisattva, i.e. Confucius, he having been sent from India by the Buddha to instruct China! Also a name of kyamuni in a previous existence.Sincere, true; to assent.Yun-k'an, a famous monk of the Sung dynasty.Yun-jo, a famous monk of the Yuan dynasty.Beginning, first, original, head; dollar; Mongol (dynasty).The tree of the origin of felicity, i. e. the <foreign lang="sa">bodhi</foreign>-tree or <foreign lang="la">ficus religiosa</foreign>, also styled 佛树; 道树, and 菩提树.Primal ignorance; the original state of avidya, unenlightenment, or ignorance; original innocence. Also 根本无明; 无始无明.原因 The original or fundamental cause which produces phenomena, e. g. karma, reincarnation, etc.; every cause has its fruit or consequences. The idea of cause and effect is a necessary condition of antecedent and consequence; it includes such relations as interaction, correlation, interdependence, co-ordination based on an intrinsic necessity.The original or fundamental marvel or mystery, i. e. the conception of nirvana.Prabh, 波罗赴; 利部 beginning, in the beginning, primordial. Prabh is a title of Viu as a personification of the sun.The original or primal mind behind all things, idem the 一心 of the 起信论 <title>Awakening of Faith</title>, the 森罗万象之元 source of all phenomena, the mind which is in all things.本明 Original brightness or intelligence; the 如 or <foreign lang="sa">bhtatathat</foreign> as the source of all light or enlightenment.Yuan-hsiao, a famous Korean monk who traveled, and studied and wrote in China during the Tang dynasty, then returned to Korea; known as 海东师 Hai-tung Shih.Name of 湛然 Chan-jan, the seventh head of the Tiantai School; he died 1116.The original patriarch, or founder of a sect or school; sometimes applied to the Buddha as the founder of virtue.The Yuan <foreign lang="sa">tripiaka</foreign>, compiled by order of Shih Tsu (Kublai), founder of the Yuan dynasty, and printed from blocks; begun in 1277, the work was finished in 1290, in 1, 422 部 works, 6, 017 卷 sections, 558  cases or covers. It contained 528 Mahayanist and 242 Hinayanist sutras; 25 Mahyna and 54 Hnayna vinaya; 97 Mahyna and 36 Hnayna stras; 108 biographies; and 332 supplementary or general works. In size, and generally, it was similar to the Sung edition. The 元藏目录 or Catalogue of the Yuan <foreign lang="sa"> tripiaka</foreign> is also known as 大普宁寺大藏经目录.元神星 A star that controls the attainment of honors, and the riddance of sickness and distresses. The star varies according to the year star of the suppliant which is one of the seven stars in Ursa Major.Elder brother.Elder and younger brothers; brother, brethren, i. e. members of the fraternity.An omen; a million.The perpetual aeon of millions of years, the kalpa beyond numbers.Fore, before, former, first; precede.A previous life, or world.Karma from a previous life.先达 One who has preceded (me) in understanding, or achievement.西迦; 霰尼 sainika, senika, martial, a commander; a class of non-Buddhists, perhaps the Jains; it may be connected with raiya, reika.The rising sun first shines on the highest mounta