) postulates on constitution and function, e.g. of the skandhas; (6) on cause and effect, e.g. the 四谛; (7) on the void, the immaterial, or reality; and (8) on the pure inexpressible ultimate or absolute.The eight (spoke) wheel, idem 八正道.The eight grades, i.e. those who have attained the 四向 and 四果.Eight characteristics of a Buddha's speaking: never hectoring; never misleading or confused; fearless; never haughty; perfect in meaning; and in flavour; free from harshness; seasonable (or, suited to the occasion).The eight misleading terms, which form the basis of the logic of the 中论, i.e. 生 birth, 灭 death, 去 past, 来 future, 一 identity, 异 difference, 断 annihilation, 常 perpetuity (or eternity). The 三论宗 regards these as unreal; v. 八不中道.(八支 or 八船 or 八行) idem 八正道.A 三论 term for 八不中道 q.v.The eight heterodox or improper practices, the opposite of the eight correct paths八正道.(八部) The eight classes of supernatural beings in the Lotus stra: 天 deva, 龙 nga, 夜叉yaka, 干闼婆 gandharva, 阿修罗 asura, 迦楼罗 garua, 紧那罗 kinnara, 摩喉罗迦 mahoraga. Also called 天龙八部 and 龙神八部.The eight groups of demon-followers of the four mahrjas, i.e. gandharvas, picas, kumbhas, pretas, ngas, ptanas, yakas, and rkasas.The eight weighty and truly precious things, i.e. the eight metals, which depend for evaluation on gold, the highest and greatest, used to illustrate the Buddha as supreme and the other classes in grades beneath him. Also 八重无价, i.e. the eight priceless things.(八门二悟 or 八门两益) Eight kinds of syllogisms in Buddhist logic; v. 因明八正理谕. (1) 能立a valid proposition; (2) 能破 an invalid proposition; (3) 似能立 doubtful, or seemingly valid but faulty; (4) 似能破 seemingly invalid, and assailable; (5) 现量manifest, or evidential; (6) 比量 inferential; (7) 似现量 seemingly evidential; (8) 似比量 seemingly inferential.The eight conditions in which it is difficult to see a Buddha or hear his dharma: in the hells: as hungry ghosts; as animals; in Uttarakuru (the northern continent where all is pleasant); in the long-life heavens (where life is long and easy); as deaf, blind, and dumb; as a worldly philosopher; in the intermediate period between a Buddha and his successor. Also 八无暇.The eight tones of a Buddha's voicebeautiful, flexible, harmonious, respect-producing, not effeminate (i.e. manly), unerring, deep and resonant.The eight winds, or influences which fan the passions, i.e. gain, loss; defamation, eulogy; praise, ridicule; sorrow, joy. Also 八法.The eight Mras, or destroyers: 烦恼魔 the
