idem 六比丘.The six 'coarser' stages arising from the 三细 or three finer stages which in turn are produced by original 无明, the unenlightened condition of ignorance; v. Awakening of Faith 起信论. They are the states of (1) 智相 knowledge or consciousness of like and dislike arising from mental conditions; (2) 相续相 consciousness of pain and pleasure resulting from the first, causing continuous responsive memory; (3) 执取相 attachment or clinging, arising from the last; (4) 计名字相 assigning names according to the seeming and unreal with fixation of ideas); (5) 起业 the consequent activity with all the variety of deeds; (6) 业苦相 the suffering resulting from being tied to deeds and their karma consequences.The sixty thousand verses of the Buddha-law which Devadatta could recite, an ability which did not save him from the <foreign lang="sa">avci</foreign> hell.The six things which enable a bodhisattva to keep perfectly the six <foreign lang="sa">pramit</foreign>s -- worshipful offerings, study of the moral duties, pity, zeal in goodness, isolation, delight in the law; these are described as corresponding to the <foreign lang="sa">pramit</foreign>s seriatim; v. 庄严经 12.The six immediate relations-- father and mother, wife and child, elder and younger brothers.The six stages of Bodhisattva development, i. e. 十信位; 十住位; 十向位; 十地位; 等觉位; 佛地位; these are from the order <title>Huayan jing</title>.The sixth of the 十住 q. v.Buddha in six forms; (1) 理佛 as the principle in and through all things, as pan-Buddha-- all things being of Buddha-nature; (2) 名字佛 Buddha as a name or person. The other four are the last four forms above.idem 六受.The six articles for worship-- flowers, a censer, candles, hot liquid, fruits, tea.The six senses on which one relies, or from which knowledge is received; v. 六情.The "six entries" ayatana, which form one of the links in the chain of causaton, v. 十二因缘 the preceding link being触contact, and the succeeding link 识 perception. The six are the qualities and effects of the six organs