some connected with Majur, and all with Guanyin. There are several 六字 <foreign lang="sa">dhra</foreign>s, e. g. the aakara-vidymantra. The six words generally associated with Guanyin are 安荼詈般茶詈 (or 安荼隶般茶詈). There is also the six word Lamaistic charm <foreign lang="sa">o mai padme h</foreign> □?呢叭 M061971 □.The six schools, i. e. 三论宗; 法相宗; 华严宗; 律宗; 成实宗, and 舍宗 q. v.; the last two are styled Hnayna schools. Mahyna in Japan puts in place of them 天台宗 and 言宗 Tendai and Shingon.v. 六种定; also 七深信.The six <foreign lang="sa">gua</foreign>s, qualities produced by the objects and organs of sense, i. e. sight, sound, smell, taste, touch, and idea; the organs are the 六根, 六入, 六处, and the perceptions or discernments the 六识; cf. 六境. Dust 尘 is dirt, and these six qualities are therefore the cause of all impurity. Yet 六尘说法 the Buddha made use of them to preach his law.The six <foreign lang="sa">trthika</foreign>s or heterodox teachers-- Praa-Kyapa, Maskarin, Sajayin, Ajita-keakambala, Kakuda-Ktyyana, and Nirgrantha; see 外道.Name of the king who, thirteen years after the destruction of the Jetavana vihra. which had been rebuilt 'five centuries ' after the nirvana, again restored it.The six years of kyamuni's austerities before his enlightenment.The six things that ferry one beyond the sea of mortality to nirvana, i. e. the six <foreign lang="sa">pramit</foreign>s 波罗蜜 (波罗蜜多): (1) 布施 <foreign lang="sa">dna</foreign>, charity, or giving, including the bestowing of the truth on others; (2) 持戒 <foreign lang="sa">la</foreign>, keeping the command rents; (3) 忍辱 <foreign lang="sa">knti</foreign>, patience under insult; (4) 精进 <foreign lang="sa">vrya</foreign>, zeal and progress; (5) 阐定 <foreign lang="sa">dhyna</foreign>, meditation or contemplation; (6) 智慧 <foreign lang="sa">praj</foreign>; wisdom, the power to discern reality or truth. It is the last that carries across the <foreign lang="sa">sasra</foreign> (sea of incarnate life) to the shores of nirvana. The opposites of these virtues are meanness, wickedness, anger, sloth, a distracted mind, and ignorance. The 唯识论 adds four other pramits: (7) 方便 <foreign lang="sa">upya</foreign>, the use of appropriate means; (8) 愿 <foreign lang="sa">praidhna</foreign>, pious vows; (9) 力 <foreign lang="sa">bala</foreign>, power of fulfillment; (10) 智 <foreign lang="sa">jna</foreign>  knowledge.The six infinite means of crossing the sea of mortality, i. e. the six <foreign lang="sa">pramit</foreign>s 六度.The reward s stimulated by the six <foreign lang="sa">pramit</foreign>s are 富 enrichment; 具色 all things, or perfection; 力 power; 寿 long life; 安 peace (or calmness); 辩 discrimination, or powers of exposition of the truth.The six characteristics of a bhagavat, which is one of a Buddha's titles: sovereign, glorious, majestic, famous, propitious, honored.(六念法) The six thoughts to dwell upon: Buddha, the Law, the Order, the commands, almsgiving, and heaven with its prospective joys.The six stages of the six kinds of mindfulness 六念.The emotions arising from the six organs of sense 六根 for which term 六情 is the older interpretation; v. 六依.The six kinds of wisdom. Each is allotted seriatim to one of the six positions 六位 q. v. (1) 闻慧 the wisdom of hearing and apprehending the truth of the middle way is associated with the 十住; (2) 思慧 of thought with the 十行; (3) 修慧 of observance with the 十向; (4) 无相慧 of either extreme, or the mean, with the 十地; (5) 照寂慧 of understanding of nirvana with 等觉慧; (6) 寂照慧 of making nirvana illuminate all beings associated with 佛果 Buddha-fruition. They are a 别教 Differentiated School series and all are associated with 中道 the school of the 中 or middle way.Six perfections (some say five, some seven) found in the opening phrase of each sutra: (1) 'Thus' implies perfect faith; (2) ' have I heard, ' perfect hearing; (3) 'once, 'the perfect time; (4) 'the Buddha, ' the perfect lord or master; (5) 'on Mt. Gdhraka, ' the perfect place; (6) 'with the great assembly of <foreign lang="sa">bhiku</foreign>s, ' the perfect assembly.The six monthly <foreign lang="sa">poadha</foreign>, or fast days: the 8th, 14th, 15th, 23rd, 29th, and 30th. They are the days on which the Four Mahrjas 四天王 take note of human conduct and when evil demons are busy, so that great care is required and consequently nothing should be eaten after noon, hence the 'fast', v. 梵王经 30th command. The 智度论 13 describes them as 恶日 evil or dangerous days, and says they arose from an ancient custom of cutting of the flesh and casting it into the fire.The six directions-- E. W. N. S. above and below.六方证明 (or 六方证诚) The praises of Amitbha proclaimed by the Buddhas of the six directions.The brahman morning act of bathing and paying homage in the six directions; observing the 'well-born' do this; the Buddha is said to have given the discourse in the 善生经.v. 六.The six 'hours' or periods in a day, three for night and three for day, i. e. morning noon, evening; night, midnight, and dawn. Also, the six divisions of the year, two each of spring, summer, and winter.six daily periods of meditation.six daily periods of unintermitting devotions.six daily periods of worship.six daily periods of worship of ceremonial.idem 六种外道; see 六行.The six mental 'taints' of the <title>Awakening of Faith</title> 起心论. Though mind-essence is by nature pure and without stain, the condition of 无明 ignorance, or innocence, permits of taint or defilement corresponding to the following six phases: (1) 执相应染 the taint interrelated to attachment, or holding the seeming for the real; it is the state of 执取相 and 名字相 which is cut off in the final pratyeka and rvaka stage and the bodhisattva 十住 of faith; (2) 不断相应染 the taint interrelated to the persisting attraction of the causes of pain and pleasure; it is the 相续相 finally eradicated in the bodhisattva 初地 stage of purity; (3) 分别智相应染 the taint interrelated to the 'particularizing intelligence' which discerns things within and without this world; it is the first 智相, cut off in the bodhisattva 七地 stage of spirituality; (4) 现色不相应染 the non-interrelated or primary taint, i. e. of the 'ignorant' mind as yet hardly discerning subject from object, of accepting an external world; the third 现相 cut of in the bodhisattva 八地 stage of emancipation from the material; (5) 能见心不相应染 the non-interrelated or primary taint of accepting a perceptive mind, the second 转相, cut of in the bodhisattva 九地 of intuition, or emancipation from mental effort; (6) 根本业不相应染 the non-interrelated or primary taint of accepting the idea of primal action or activity in the absolute; it is the first 业相, and cut of in the 十地 highest bodhisattva stage, entering on Buddhahood. See Suzuki's translation, 80-1.The six <foreign lang="sa">indriya</foreign>s or sense-organs: eye, ear, nose, tongue, body, and mind. See also 六入, 六境, 六尘, and 六处.Substitution of one organ for another, or use of one organ to do the work of all the others, which is a Buddha's power.The six organs and their purification in order to develop their unlimited power and interchange, as in the case of a Buddha. This full development enables e. g. the eye to see everything in a great chiliocosm from its highest heaven down to its lowest hells and all the beings past, present, and future, with all the karma of each.The state of the organs thus purified is defined by Tiantai as the 十信位 of the 别教, or the 相似 of the 圆教, v. 六.The powers of the six senses, i. e. the achievement by purification of their interchange of function.A penitential service over the sins of the six senses.The six sexual attractions arising from color; form; carriage; voice (or speech); softness (or smoothness); and features.the six heavens where sexual desire continues, and the four <foreign lang="sa">dhyna</foreign> heavens of purity above them free from such desire.The <foreign lang="sa">devaloka</foreign>s, i. e. the heavens of desire, i. e. with sense-organs; the first is described as half-way up Mt. Sumeru, the second at its summit, and the rest between it and the Brahmalokas; for list v. 六天