) 持业释 or 同依释 karmadhraya, referring to the equality of dependence of both terms, e. g. 大乘 Mahyna, 'great' and 'vehicle'), both equally essential to 'Mahyna' with its specific meaning; (2) 依主释 (or 六士释) tatpurua, containing a principal term, e. g. 眼识 eye-perception, where the eye is the qualifying term; (3) 有财释 (or 多财释) bahuvrhi, the sign of possession, e. g. 觉者 he who has enlightenment; (4) 相违释 dvandva, a term indicating two separate ideas, e. g. 教观 teaching and meditation; (5) 邻近释 avyaybhava, an adverbial compound, or a term resulting from 'neighboring' association, e. g. 念处 thought or remembering place, i. e. memory; (6) 带数释 dvigu, a numerative term, e. g. 五蕴 pacaskandha, the five skandhas. M. W. gives the order as 4, 3, 1, 2, 6, and 5.The six Bodhisattva-stages in the <title>Bodhisattva-bhumi sutra</title> 菩萨地持经 are: (1) 种性住 the attainment of the Buddha-seed nature in the 十住; (2) 解行住 of discernment and practice in the 十行 and 十向; (3) 净心住 of purity by attaining reality in the 初地见道; (4) 行道住 of progress in riddance of incorrect thinking, in the 二地 to the 七地; (5) 决定住 of powers of correct decision and judgment in the eighth and ninth 地; (6) 究竟住 of the perfect Bodhisattva stage in the tenth 地 and the 等觉位, but not including the 妙觉位 which is the Buddha-stage.The six kinds of certainty resulting from observance of the six pramits: 财成决定 the certainty of wealth; 生胜决定 of rebirth in honorable families; 不退决定 of no retrogression (to lower conditions); 修习决定 of progress in practice; 定业决定 of unfailingly good karma; 无功用决定 of effortless abode in truth and wisdom. 大乘庄严论 12.The six seals, or proofs, i. e. the six <foreign lang="sa">pramit</foreign>s, 六度.v. 六因.The six kinds of ascetics; also 六种苦行外道; 六术; v. 六行.The six able devices of Bodhisattvas: (1) preaching deep truths in simple form to lead on people gladly to believe; (2) promising them every good way of realizing their desires, of wealth, etc.; (3) showing a threatening aspect to the disobedient to induce reform; (4) rebuking and punishing them with a like object; (5) granting wealth to induce grateful offerings and almsgiving; (6) descending from heaven, leaving home, attaining bodhi, and leading all to joy and purity. 菩萨地持经 8.For the first five see 五种道; the sixth is the Buddha stage of 妙觉性.  Cf. 六种位.The fifth of the 五种正行 q. v. is expanded into six kinds of proper practice: reading and intoning, studying, worshipping, invoking, praising, and making offerings.The six deceivers common to all the living-- greed, anger, torpor, ignorance, doubt, and incorrect views.The meditation on the six natures 六种性.idem 六离合释.The six earthquakes, or earth-shakings, also 六种动相, of which there are three different categories. I, Those at the Buddha's conception, birth, enlightenment, first preaching, when Mra besought him to live, and at his nirvana; some omit the fifth and after 'birth' add 'leaving home '. II. The six different kinds of shaking of the chiliocosm, or universe, when the Buddha entered into the <foreign lang="sa">samdhi</foreign> of joyful wandering, see 大品般若经 1, i. e. east rose and west sank, and so on with w. e., n. s., s. n., middle and borders, borders and middle. III. Another group is shaking, rising, waving, reverberating, roaring, arousing, the first three referring to motion, the last three to sounds; see the above 般若经; which in later translations gives shaking, rising, reverberating, beating, roaring, crackling.Six windows and one monkey (climbing in and out), i. e. the six organs of sense and the active mind.The six arrows, i. e. the six senses; v. 六尘.A cloth or cord tied in six consecutive double loops and knots. The cloth represents the fundamental unity, the knots the apparent diversity. v. 楞伽经 5.The six arhats i. e. kyamuni and his first five disciples, cf. 五罗汉.The six kinds of offender, i. e. one who commits any of the 四重 four grave sins, or destroys harmony in the order, or sheds a Buddha's blood.The six common-herd <foreign lang="sa">bhiku</foreign>s, to whose improper or evil conduct is attributed the laying down of many of the laws by kyamuni; also 六; different lists of names are given, the generally accepted list indicating Nanda, Upananda, Avaka, Punarvasu, Chanda, and Udyin. Udyin is probably Kalodayin, a name given in other lists.The six sovereign rulers, i. e. the six senses, see 六根.The six boats, i. e. the six pramits 六度 for ferrying to the bank beyond mortality.The six supernatural signs; idem 六瑞.The heretics of the six austerities are referred to as 六苦行外道; v. 六行.(六著) The six bonds, or the mind of the six bonds: greed, love, hate, doubt, lust, pride.The six sins that smother the six <foreign lang="sa">pramit</foreign>s: grudging, commandment-breaking, anger, family attachment, confused thoughts, and stupid ignorance.Among Buddhists the term means the practice of the 六度 six <foreign lang="sa">pramit</foreign>s; it is referred, among outsiders, to the six austerities of the six kinds of heretics: (1) 自饿 starvation; (2) 投渊 naked cave-dwelling (or, throwing oneself down precipices); (3) 赴火 self-immolation, or self-torturing by fire; (4) 自坐 sitting naked in public; (5) 寂默 dwelling in silence among graves; (6) 牛狗 living as animals.The six meditations, also called 厌欣观; 六妙行 comparing the 下地 lower realms with the 上地 higher, the six following characters being the subject of meditation: the three lower represent □ coarseness, 苦 suffering, and 障 resistance; these in meditation are seen as distasteful: while the higher are the 静 calm, 妙 mystic, 离 free, which are matters for delight. By this meditation on the distasteful and the delectable the delusions of the lower realms may be overcome.The six ruiners, i. e. the attractions of the six senses, idem 六尘, 六贼 q. v.The six decisions, i. e. the concepts formed through the mental contact of the six senses; later called 六触.(六观) cf. 六种性 and 六位.The six kinds of Guanyin. There are two groups-- I. That of Tiantai: 大悲 most pitiful; 大慈 most merciful; 师子无畏 of lion-courage; 大光普照 of universal light; 天人丈夫 leader