isattvas to attain the十地 by fulfilling the ten pramits, v. 十波.Ten objects of or stages in meditation观 in the Tiantai school, i.e. 阴境 the five skandhas; 烦恼境 life's distresses and delusion; 病患境 sickness, or dukha, its cause and cure; 业相境 age-long karmaic influences; 魔事境 Mra affairs, how to overthrow their rule; 禅定境 the conditions of dhyna and samdhi; 诸见境 various views and doubts that arise; 慢境 pride in progress and the delusion that one has attained nirva; 二乘境 temptation to be content with the lower nirva, instead of going on to the greater reward; 菩萨境 bodhisattvahood; see the 止观 5.v. 十一切处.(十夜) The ten nights (and days) from the sixth to the fifteenth of the tenth moon, when the Pure-land sect intones stras.The ten chief discip1es of kyamuni, each of whom was master of one power or gift. riputra of wisdom; Maudgalyyana of supernatural powers; Mahkyapa of discipline; Aniruddha of 天眼 deva vision; Subhti of explaining the void or immaterial; Pra of expounding the law; Ktyyana of its fundamental principles; Upli of maintaining the rules; Rhula of the esoteric; and nanda of hearing and remembering.idem 十使.The ten vows of Puxian 普贤, or Samantabhadra.The ten aspects of the bhtatathat or reality attained by a bodhisattva during his fifty-two stages of development, cf. 十地 and 十障, each of which is associated with one of these <foreign lang="zh">zhenru</foreign>: (1) 遍行如 the universality of the <foreign lang="zh">zhenru</foreign>; (2) 最胜如 its superiority over all else; (3) 流如 its ubiquity; (4) 无摄受如 its independence or self-containedness; (5) 无别如 subjective indifferentiation; (6) 无染净如 above differences of impurity and purity; (7) 法无别如 objective indifferentiation; (8) 不增减如 invariable, i.e. can be neither added to nor taken from; (9) 智自在所依 the basis of all wisdom; (10) 业自在等所依如 and all power. The above are the 别教 group from the 唯识论 10. Another group, of the 圆教, is the same as the 十如是 q.v.The ten essential qualities, or characteristics, of thing, according to the 方便chapter of the Lotus stra: 相如是 form; 性如是 nature; 体如是 corpus or embodiment; 力如是 powers; 作如是 function; 因如是 primary cause; 果如是 environmental cause; 果如是 effect; 报如是 karmic reward; 本末究竟等 the inseparability, or inevitability of them all.v. 十地.The ten wonders, or incomprehensibles; there are two groups, the ｖ traceable or manifested and 本门妙 the fundamental. The 门十妙 are the wonder of: (1) 境妙 the universe, sphere, or whole, embracing mind, Buddha, and all things as a unity; (2) 智妙 a Buddha's all-embracing knowledge arising from such universe; (3) 行妙 his deeds, expressive of his wisdom; (4) 位妙 his attainment of all the various Buddha stages, i.e. 十住 and十地; (5) 三法妙 his three laws of 理, 慧, and truth, wisdom, and vision; (6) 感应妙 his response to appeal, i.e. his (spiritual) response or relation to humanity, for "all beings are my children"; (7) 神通妙 his supernatural powers; (8) 说法妙 his preaching; (9) 眷属妙 his supernatural retinue; (10) 利益妙 the blessings derived through universal elevation into Buddhahood. The 本门十妙 are the wonder of (1) 本因妙 the initial impulse or causative stage of Buddhahood; (2) 本果妙 its fruit or result in eternity, joy, and purity; (3) 国土妙 his (Buddha) realm; (4) 感应妙 his response (to human needs); (5) 神通妙 his supernatural powers; (6) 说法妙 his preaching; (7) 眷属妙 his supernatural retinue; (8) 涅盘妙 his nirva; (9) 寿命妙 his (eternal) life; (10) his blessings as above. Both groups are further defined as progressive stages in a Buddha's career. These "wonders" are derived from the Lotus stra.The ten schools of Chinese Buddhism: I. The (1) 律宗 Vinaya-discipline, or 南山|； (2) 舍 Koa, Abhidharma, or Reality (Sarvstivdin) 有宗； (3) 成实宗 Satyasiddhi sect founded on this stra by Harivarman; (4) 三论宗 Mdhyamika or 性空宗； (5) 法华宗 Lotus, "Law-flower" or Tiantai 天台宗； (6) 华严Huayan or法性 or贤首宗； ( 7) 法相宗 Dharmalakana or 慈恩宗 founded on the唯识论 (8) 心宗 Ch'an or Zen, mind-only or intuitive, v. 禅宗 ; (9) 言宗 (Jap. Shingon) or esoteric 密宗 ; (10) 莲宗 Amitbha-lotus or Pure Land (Jap. Jdo) 净士宗. The 2nd, 3rd, 4th, and 9th are found in Japan rather than in China, where they have ceased to be of importance. II. The Hua-yen has also ten divisions into ten schools of thought: (1) 我法有 the reality of self (or soul) and things, e.g. mind and matter; (2) 法有我无 the reality of things but not of soul; (3) 法无去来 things have neither creation nor destruction; (4) 现通假实 present things are both apparent and real; (5) 俗妄实 common or phenomenal ideas are wrong, fundamental reality is the only truth; (6) things are merely names; (7) all things are unreal 空; (8) the bhtatathat is not unreal; (9) phenomena and their perception are to be got rid of; (10) the perfect, all-inclusive, and complete teaching of the One Vehicle. III. There are two old Japanese divisions: 大乘律宗, 宗 , 成实 宗 , 法和宗 , 三论宗 , 天台宗 , 华严宗 , 言宗 , 小乘律宗 , and 净土宗 ; the second list adds 禅宗 and omits 大乘律宗. They are the Ritsu, Kusha, Jjitsu, Hoss, Sanron, Tendai, Kegon, Shingon, (Hnayna) Ritsu, and Jdo; the addition being Zen.The ten precious things; 十宝山 the ten precious mountains, or mountain of ten precious things; v. 十善 and 十善王.The spirit king of each of the ten mountainsHimlaya, Gandhamdana, Vaidhar, 神仙山, Yugadhara, Avakara, Nemindhara, Cakrava, Ketumat, and Sumeru.The ten monks necessary for a full ordination of a monk, i.e. 三师七证 three leaders and seven witnesses.The ten pramits or virtues transporting to nirva; idem 十波罗蜜 q.v.each of the pramits has three forms of observance, e.g. the first, 施 dna or giving has 财施 almsgiving, 法施 truth-giving, and 无畏施 courage-giving. The three forms differ with each pramit.The ten acolytes or attendants on an crya, or superior religious teacher, in his ceremonial offices, following the pattern of the ten principal disciples of kyamuni.The ten virtues, powers, or qualities, of which there are several groups, e.g. in the 华严经,十地品 there are 法师十德 the ten virtues of a teacher of the Law, i.e. he should be well versed in its meaning; able widely to publish it; not be nervous before an audience; be untiring in argument; adaptable; orderly so that his teaching can be easily followed; serious and dignified; bold and zealous; unwearied; and enduring (able to bear insult, etc.). The 弟子十德 ten virtues or qualities of a disciple according to the 大日经疏 4, are faith; sincerity; devotion to the trikya; (seeking the) adornment of true wisdom; perseverance; moral purity; patience (or bearing shame); generosity in giving; courage; resoluteness.The ten kinds of heart or mind; there are three groups. One is from the 止观 4, minds ignorant and dark; affected by evil companions; not following the good; doing evil in thought, word, deed; spreading evil abroad; unceasingly wicked; secret sin; open crime; utterly shameless; denying cause and effect (retribution)all such must remain in the flow 流 of reincarnation. The second group (from the same book) is the 逆流 the mind striving against the stream of perpetual reincarnation; it shows itself in devout faith, shame (for sin), fear (of wrong-doing), repentance and confession, reform, bodhi (i.e. the bodhisattva mind), doing good, maintaining the right law, thinking on all the Buddhas, meditation on the void (or, the unreality of sin). The third is the 言 group from the 大日经疏 3; the "seed" heart (i.e. the original good desire), the sprout (under Buddhist religious influence), the bud, leaf, flower, fruit, its serviceableness; the child-heart, the discriminating heart, the heart of settled judgment (or resolve).The ten inexpressible joys of the Pure-land; also 十乐.The ten repetitions of an invocation, e.g. namo Amitbha.A bodhisattva's ten objects of thought or meditation, i.e. body, the senses, mind, things, environment, monastery, city (or district), good name, Buddha-learning, riddance of all passion and delusion.These ten invocations will carry a dying man with an evil karma into the Pure-land.See 十念往生, but cf. 十声.The arteries of the "ten invocations", i.e. the teacher's giving and the disciple's receiving of the law.The ten irate rjas, or protectors, whose huge images with many heads and limbs are seen in temples; perhaps the ten krodha gods of the Tibetans (Khro-bo); their names are 焰□得迦 Yamntaka; 无能胜 Ajita; 纳 □得迦 ? Padmhtaka; 尾觐那得迦 Vighnntaka; 不动尊 Acala; 吒枳 ? Dkin; 罗难□ ? Nladaa; 大力, 送婆 Sambara; and缚日罗播多罗 Vrabhadra.Ten kinds of the Buddha's grace: his (1) initial resolve to universalize (his salvation); (2) self-sacrifice (in previous lives); (3) complete altruism; (4) his descent into all the six states of existence for their salvation; (5) relief of the living from distress and mortality; (6) profound pity; (7) revelation of himself in human and glorified form; (8) teaching in accordance with the capacity of his hearers, first hnayna, then mhayna doctrine; (9) revealing his nirva to stimulate his disciples; (10) pitying thought for all creatures, in that dying at 80 instead of at 100 he left twenty years of his own happiness to his disciples; and also the tripiaka for universal salvation.Dakuala. The ten "not right" or evil things are killing, stealing, adultery, lying, double-tongue, coarse language, filthy language, covetousness, anger, perverted views; these produce the ten resultant evils 十恶业 (道) Cf. 十善; 十戒.The ten disturbers of the religious life: a domineering (spirit); heretical ways; dangerous amusements; a butcher's or other low occupation; asceticism (or selfish hnayna salvation); (the condition of a) eunuch; lust; endangering (the character by improper intimacy); contempt; breeding animals, etc. (for slaughter).idem 十使.The king of the ten vows, Puxian普贤, or Samantabhadra.Entirely completed, perfect.ikpada. The ten prohibitions (in Pli form) consist of five commandments for the layman: (1) not to destroy life 不杀生 ptiptveramai; (2) not to steal 不伦盗 adinndnver; (3) not to commit adultery 不淫欲 abrahmacaryaver.; (4) not to lie 不妄语musvdver.; (5) not to take intoxicating liquor 不酒 suramereyya-majjapamdahnver. Eight special commandments for laymen consist of the preceding five plus: (6) not to eat food out of regulated hours 不非时食 vikla-bhojanver.; (7) not to use garlands or perfumes 不著华□好香涂身 ml- gandha-vilepana-dhraa-maana-vibhanahn; (8) not to sleep on high or broad beds (chastity) 不坐高广大 uccsayan-mahsayan. The ten commandments for the monk are the preceding eight plus: (9) not to take part in singing, dancing, musical or theatrical performances, not to see or listen to such 不歌舞倡伎不往观听 nacca-gta-vdita-viskadassanver.; (10) to refrain from acquiring uncoined or coined gold, or silver, or jewels 不得捉钱金银宝物 jtarpa-rajata-paggahaver. Under the Mhayna these ten commands for the monk were changed, to accord with the new environment of the monk, to the following: not to kill, not to steal, to avoid all unchastity, not to lie, not to slander, not to insult, not to chatter, not to covet, not to give way to anger, to harbour no scepticism.The ten guardians of the law, assistants to the 十大明王.The ten Yoga books, the foundation work being the 瑜伽论, the other ten are 百法论, 五蕴论, 显扬论, 摄大乘论, 杂集论, 辨中边论, 二十唯识论, 三十唯识论, 大庄严论, and 分别瑜伽论 .v. 十宗.(十斋日佛)　The ten Buddhas or bodhisattvas connected with the ten days of fasting days who in turn are 定光, 药师, 普贤, 阿弥陀, 观音, 势至, 地藏毗虑遮那, 药王, 释迦.(十斋) The ten 'fast' days of a month are 1, 8, 14, 15, 18, 23, 24, 28, 29, and 30. In certain periods flesh was forbidden on these days, also all killing, hunting, fishing, executions, etc.The ten directions of space, i.e. the eight points of the compass and the nadir and zenith. There is a Buddha for each direction 十方十佛.The worlds in all directions.A Buddha-realm, idem 大千世界.十方现前僧物 see 四种僧物.Ten powers only possessed by Buddhas: (1) prediction; (2) knowing and fulfilling the desires of the living; (3)-(10) are various forms of omniscience, i.e. (3) of all Buddha-realms and their inhabitants; (4) their natures; (5) good roots; (6) laws; (7) wisdom; (8) every moment; (9) evolving domains, or conditions; (10) language, words, and discussions. v. 宗镜录 99.idem 十重禁戒.The ten boundless treasuries of a bodhisattva: (1) 信 belief and faith; (2) 戒