n>s and <foreign lang="sa">pratyekabuddha</foreign>s-- as a burning house, uneasily; of bodhisattvas-- as an empty flower; of Buddhas-- as mind, all things being for (or of) intelligent mind.The three gen, or founders of systems, together with 若提子 Nirgranthajti; v. 二天三仙.The four wise men who sought escape from death: one in the mountains, another in the ocean, another in the air, and a fourth in the market place-- all in vain.yu-t'an-na, ? udna, the four dogmas: all is impermanent, all is suffering, there is no ego, nirvana.The four abodes or states in the 智度论 3, i. e. (1) 天住 the <foreign lang="sa">devaloka</foreign>s, equivalents of charity, morality, and goodness of heart; (2) 梵住 the <foreign lang="sa">brahmaloka</foreign>s, equivalents of benevolence, pity, joy, and indifference; (3) 圣住 the abode of <foreign lang="sa">rvaka</foreign>s, <foreign lang="sa">pratyekabuddha</foreign>s, and bodhisattvas, equivalent of the <foreign lang="sa">samdhi</foreign> of the immaterial realm, formless and still; (4) 佛住 the Buddha-abode, the equivalent of the <foreign lang="sa">samdhi</foreign>s of the infinite. v. 四住地.(四住) The four states or conditions found in mortality; wherein are the delusions of misleading views and desires. They are (1) 见一切住地 the delusions arising from seeing things as they seem, not as they really are. (2) 欲爱住地 the desires in the desire-realm. (3) 色爱住地 the desires in the form-realm. (4) 有爱住地 the desires in the formless realm. When 无明住地 the state of ignorance is added we have the 五住地 five states. These five states condition all error, and are the ground in which spring the roots of the countless passions and delusions of all mortal beings.Four of the Five Dhyni-Buddhas. i.e. the four regional Buddhas; they are variously stated. The 金光明经 gives E. 阿; S. 相; W. 无量寿; N. 微妙声. The 大日经 gives E. 幢; S. 大勤勇遍觉华开敷; W. 仁胜 (i. e. 无量寿); N. 不动, i. e. 鼓音如来. The 金刚顶经 gives 不动; 生; 观自在, and 不 空 成就如来. v. 五智如来.idem 四土.The four purposes of the Buddha's appearing, that the Buddha-knowledge might be 开示悟入revealed, proclaimed, understood, and entered; v. Lotus 方便品.The four necessaries, or things on which the religious rely. (1) 行四依 The four of ascetic practitioners-- rag clothing; begging for food; sitting under trees; purgatives and diuretics as moral and spiritual means; these are also termed 四圣种. (2) 法四依 The four of the dharma: i. e. the truth, which is eternal, rather than man, even its propagator; the sutras of perfect meaning i. e. of the 道实相 the truth of the 'middle' way; the meaning, or spirit, not the letter; wisdom 智, i.e. Buddha-wisdom rather than mere knowledge 识. There are other groups. Cf. 四事.The first four of the four 四依, 行四依, and the 八正道 q. v.v.四种信心.The four right objects of faith and the five right modes of procedure; the 如 <foreign lang="sa">bhtatathat</foreign> and the 三 Three Precious Ones are the four; the five are almsgiving, morality, patience, zeal (or progress), and 观 meditation.The four <foreign lang="sa">viparyaya</foreign> i. e. inverted or false beliefs in regard to 常, 乐, 我, 净. There are two groups: (1) the common belief in the four above, denied by the early Buddhist doctrine that all is impermanent, suffering, impersonal, and impure; (2) the false belief of the Hnayna school that nirvana is not a state of permanence, joy, personality, and purity. Hnayna refutes the common view in regard to the phenomenal life; bodhisattvism refutes both views.The thirty-two marks of a Buddha.catur-an.gabalakya; the four divisions of a <foreign lang="sa">cakravarti</foreign>'s troops-- elephant, <foreign lang="sa"> hastikya</foreign>; horse, <foreign lang="sa"> avakya</foreign>; chariot, <foreign lang="sa">rathakya</foreign>; and foot, <foreign lang="sa">pattikya</foreign>.The 'pure' <foreign lang="sa">dhyna</foreign>, i. e. one of the 三定 three <foreign lang="sa">dhyna</foreign>s; this <foreign lang="sa">dhyna</foreign> is in four parts.The 法相 Dharmalakana school divides the function of 识 cognition into four, i. e. 相分 mental phenomena, 见分 discriminating such phenomena, 自证分 the power that discriminates, and 证自证 the proof or assurance of that power. Another group is: 信 faith, 解 liberty, 行 action, and 证 assurance or realization.Extracts from the 四分律 four-division Vinaya with verses, for use on days when the discipline is recited; there are other works under a similar title.idem 律宗.The 法相 school which divides the 识心 cognition-mind into four parts, v. 四分.The four-division Vinaya or discipline of the Dharmagupta school, divided into four sections of 20, 15, 14, and 11 chuan. The 四分律藏 <title>Dharma-gupta-vinaya</title> was tr. in A. D. 405 by Buddhayasas and 竺佛念 Chu Fo-nien; the 四分比丘尼羯磨法 <title>Dharmagupta-bhiku-karman</title> was tr. by Gunavarman in 431: and there are numerous other works of this order.The four powers for attaining enlightenment: independent personal power; power derived from others; power of past good karma; and power arising from environment.v. 四善根.The four kalpas, or epochs, of a world, 成劫 that of formation and completion; 住劫 existing or abiding; 怀劫 destruction; and 空劫 annihilation, or the succeeding void. 舍论 12.The 四无矶辩 q. v. whereby all beings may be saved.catvriat; forty.(or 四十一地) Forty-one of the fifty-two bodhisattva stages (of development), i. e. all except the 十信 and 妙觉. For this and 四十二位 v. 五十二位.and 四十九灯. The service to 药师 the Master of Healing, when forty-nine lamps are displayed and forty-nine monks engaged; seven of his images are used, seven of the lamps being placed before each image.The seven times seven days of funeral services; the forty-ninth day.(or 四十九重如意殿) . The <foreign lang="sa">mai</foreign>, or Pearl palace of forty-nine stories above the Tuita heaven.The forty-two stages, i. e. all above the 十信 of the fifty-two stages.The forty-two messengers, or angels of 不动尊 q. v.The forty-two species of ignorance which, according to Tiantai, are to be cut off seriatim in the above forty-two stages.The doctrine of the forty-two 悉昙 Siddham letters as given in the 华严 76 and 般若经 4. They have special meanings, independent of their use among the fourteen vowels and thirty-five consonants, i. e. forty-nine alphabetic signs. The forty-two are supposed by the 智度论 47 to be the root or basis of all letters; and each letter has its own specific value as a spiritual symbol; Tiantai associates each of them with one of the forty-two 位. The letters begin with 阿 and end with 荼 or 佗.The 'Sutra of Forty-two Sections' generally attributed to Kyapa Mtaga, v. 迦, and Gobharaa, v. 竺, the first Indian monks to arrive officially in China. It was, however, probably first produced in China in the 晋 Chin dynasty. There are various editions and commentaries.The 'forty bodhisattva positions' of the 梵网经. They are classified into four groups: (1) 十发趣 Ten initial stages, i. e. the minds 心 of abandoning things of the world, of keeping the moral law, patience, zealous progress, <foreign lang="sa">dhyna</foreign>, wisdom, resolve, guarding (the Law), joy, and spiritual baptism by the Buddha. These are associated with the 十住. (2) 十长养 Ten steps in the nourishment of perfection, i. e. minds of kindness, pity, joy, relinquishing, almsgiving, good discourse, benefiting, friendship, <foreign lang="sa">dhyna</foreign>, wisdom. These are associated with the 十行. (3) 十金刚 Ten 'diamond' steps of firmness, i. e. a mind of faith, remembrance, bestowing one's merits on others, understanding, uprighthess, no-retreat, Mahyna, formlessness, wisdom, indestructibility; these are associated with the 十向. (4) The 十地 q. v.For forty and more years (the Buddha) was unable to unfold the full truth (until he first gave it in the <title>Lotus Sutra</title>).The forty-eight demon satellites of rycalantha 不动明王 as subduer of demons, etc.The forty-eight years of service demanded by an old physician of his pupil in order to acquire his skill-- likened to the slow and difficult methods of Hnayna and of early Mahyna.The forty-eight vows of Amitbha that he would not enter into his final nirvana or heaven, unless all beings shared it; the lists vary.catu-parmara, the four attachments, i. e. desire, (unenlightened) views, (fakir) morals, and ideas arising from the conception of the self. Also, the possible delusions of the 四住地. Also, seeking fame in the four quarters.The four terms, phrases, or four-line verses, e. g. 四句分别 The four terms of differentiation, e. g. of all things into 有 the existing; 空 nonexisting; both; neither; or phenomenal, noumenal, both, neither. Also, double, single, both, neither; and other similar applications.The swan-song of an <foreign lang="sa">arhat</foreign>, who has attained to the perfect life: --  All rebirths are ended,<lb></lb>  The noble life established,<lb></lb> My work is accomplished.<lb></lb> No further existence is mine.<lb></lb>The four tenets held by various non-Buddhist schools: (1) the permanence of the ego, i. e. that the ego of past lives is the ego of the present; (2) its impermanence, i. e. that the present ego is of independent birth; (3) both permanent and impermanent, that the ego is permanent, the body impermanent; (4) neither permanent nor impermanent; that the body is impermanent but the ego not impermanent.The four-phrase classification that phenomena are 自因 self-caused, 他因 caused by another, 共因 by both, 无因 by neither; cf. 四不生.The four stages in Hnayna sanctity: <foreign lang="sa">srota-panna</foreign>, <foreign lang="sa">sakdgmin</foreign>, <foreign lang="sa">angmin</foreign> and arhan.idem 四阿含经.The four 'tastes': the Tiantai definition of the four periods of the Buddha's teaching preliminary to the fifth, i. e. that of the <title>Lotus Sutra</title>; cf. 五味.The four commanders or leaders; see <title>Lotus Sutra</title> 15.catu-kuala-mla, the four good roots, or sources from which spring good fruiy or development. In Hnayna they form the stage after 总相念住 as represented by the 舍 and 成实; in Mahyna it is the final stage of the 十向 as represented by the 法相宗. There are also four similar stages connected with <foreign lang="sa">rvaka</foreign>, <foreign lang="sa">pratyekabuddha</foreign>, and Buddha, styled 三品四善根. The four of the 舍宗 are 法, 顶法, 忍法, and 世第一法. The four of the 成实宗 are the same, but are applied differently. The 法相宗 retains the same four terms, but connects them with the four <foreign lang="sa">dhyna</foreign> stages of the 唯识观 in its four first 加行 developments.idem 四苑.The four Buddha-ketra, or realms, of Tiantai: (1) 凡圣居同土 Realms where all classes dwell-- men, devas, Buddhas, disciples, non-disciples; it has two divisions, the impure, e. g. this world, and the pure, e. g. the 'Western' pure-land. (2) 方便有余土 Temporary realms, where the occupants have got rid of the evils of 见思 unenlightened views and thoughts, but still have to be reborn. (3) 实报无障碍土 Realms of permanent reward and freedom, for those who have attained bodhisattva rank. (4) 常寂光土 Realm of eternal rest and light (i. e. wisdom) and of eternal spirit (<foreign lang="sa">dharmakya</foreign>), the abode of Buddhas; but in reality all the others are included in this, and are only separated for convenience, sake.The four kinds of holy men-- <foreign lang="sa">rvaka</foreign>s, <foreign lang="sa">pratyekabuddha</foreign>s, bodhisattvas, and Buddhas. Also, the four chief disciples of Kumrajva, i. e. 道生 Daosheng, 僧肇 Sengzhao, 道融 Daorong, and 僧睿 Sengrui.The four holy ways-- wearing rags from dust-heaps, begging for food, sitting under trees, and entire withdrawal from the world. The meaning is similar in 四良药; 行四依; and 四圣种.The four holy or noble truths, idem 四谛.The four firm or 四不怀信 indestructible beliefs, in the Buddha, the law, the order, and the commandments.(四堕落法) The four causes of falling from grace and final excommunication of a monk or nun; adultery, stealing, killing, falsity; v. 四波罗夷.The four <foreign lang="sa">stpa</foreign>s at the places of Buddha's birth, Kapilavastu; enlightenment, Magadha: preaching, Benares; and parinirva, Kuinagara. Four more are located in the heavens of the Travastrias gods, one each tor his hair, nails, begging bowl, and teeth, E., S., W., N., respectively.The sixteen assemblies, or addresses in the four places where the 大般若经 complete <title>Prajpramit Sutra</title> is said to have been delivered.To inquire (or worship at) the four places for lighting incense at a monastery.The four hours of the night 成亥子丑, i. e. 7 to 3, and the eight hours of the day from 寅 to 酉 3 a. m. to 7 p. m.mahbhta, 四界; 四大界. The four elements of which all things are made; or the four realms; i. e. earth, water, fire, and wind (or air); they represent 坚, 湿, 暖, and 动 solid, liquid, heat, and motion; motion produces and maintains life. As 实 active or formative forces they are styled 四界 (四大界) ; as 假 passive or material objects they are 四大; but the 成实论 <title>Satyasiddhi stra</title> disputes the 实 and recognizes only the 假.The inharmonious working of the four elements in the body, which causes the 440 ailments; cf. 四蛇.The verse uttered by 肇法师 Zhao Fashi when facing death under the 姚秦 Yao Qin emperor, fourth century A. D.: --  'No master have the four elements,<lb></lb> Unreal are the five skandhas,<lb></lb> When my head meets the white blade,<lb></lb> Twill be but slicing the spring wind.<lb></lb>' The 'four elements' are the physical body.The four famous 'hills' or monasteries in China: 普陀 P'u-t'o, for Guanyin, element water; 五台 Wu-tai, Wen-shu, wind; 峨眉 O-mei, P'uhsien, fire; and 九华 Chiu-hua, Tizang, earth.The four great <foreign lang="sa">rvaka</foreign>s, idem 四大弟子.see 四天王. The four deva-kings of the four quarters, guardians in a monastery.The four monastic heads imperially appointed during, the Tang dynasty.The four great disciples of the Buddha-- riputra, Mahmaudgalyyana, Subhti, and Mahkyapa. Another group is Mahkyapa, Piola, Rhula, and ? Kauinya.The guardian <foreign lang="sa">deva</foreign>s of the four quarters: south 金刚无胜结护; east 无畏结护; north 怀诸怖结护; and west 难降伏结护. The 四大佛护院 is the thirteenth group of the Garbhadhtu.v. 大明王.The four great oceans in a world, around Sumeru, in which are the four great continents; cf. 九山八海.idem 四大.The four great Bodhisattvas of the <title>Lotus Sutra</title>, i. e. Maitreya, Majur, Avalokitevara, and Samantabhadra. Another list of previous Bodhisattvas is 上行 Viitacritra; 无边行 Anantacritra; 净行 Viuddhacritra, and 安立行 Supratihitacritra.The four great continents. See 四洲.Four great sutras: 华严经 Huayan; 涅盘经 Nirvana; 积经Mahratnakta, and 般若经 Praj.In the upper regions there are the four heavens of the four deva-kings; below are the people of the four continents.The four quarters or continents of the world.(四大天王) catur-mahrjas, or Lokaplas; the four <foreign lang="sa">deva</foreign>-kings. Indra's external 'generals 'who dwell each on a side of Mount Meru, and who ward off from the world the attacks of malicious spirits, or asuras, hence their name 护世四天王 the four deva-kings, guardians of the world. Their abode is the 四天王天 catur-maharja-kyikas; and their titles are: East 持国天 Deva who keeps (his) kingdom; colour white; name Dhtarsatra. South 增长天 Deva of increase and growth; blue; name Virhaka. West 广目天 The broad-eyed (also ugly-eyed) <foreign lang="sa">deva</foreign> (perhaps a form of Siva); red; name Virpka. North 多闻天 The <foreign lang="sa">deva</foreign> who hears much and is well-versed; yellow; name Vairavaa, or Dhanada; he is a form of Kuvera, the god of wealth. These are the four giant temple guardians introduced as such to China by Amogha; cf. 四天王经.catur-maharja-kyikas; the four heavens of the four deva-kings.(四夷戒 or 四夷罪) v. 四波罗夷.A meditation method on the 四加行位 q. v.四神足 ddhi-pda; the third group of the 三十七科道品 <foreign lang="sa">bodhi-pakikadharma</foreign>; the four steps to supernatural powers, making the body independent of ordinary or natural law. The four steps are said to be the 四种禅定 four kinds of <foreign lang="sa">dhyna</foreign>, but there are several definitions, e. g. 欲神足 chanda-ddhi-pda, desire (or intensive longing, or concentration); 勤神足 virya-ddhi-pda, energy (or intensified effort); 心神足 citta-ddhi-pda, memory (or intense holding on to the position reached); 观神足 mmsa-ddhi-pda., meditation (or survey, the state of <foreign lang="sa">dhyna</foreign>).The four Indian 'clans' or castes-- <foreign lang="sa">brhmaa</foreign>, <foreign lang="sa">katriya</foreign>, <foreign lang="sa">vaiya</foreign>, and <foreign lang="sa">dra</foreign>, i. e. (1) priestly, (2) military and ruling, (3) farmers and traders, and (4) serfs; born respectively from the mouth, shoulders, flanks, and feet of Brahma.Four respect-inspiring forms of demeanour in walking, standing, sitting, lying.The four senior or prime months, i. e. the first of each season, first, fourth, seventh, and tenth.(四安乐行) The four means of attaining to a happy contentment, by proper direction of the deeds of the body; the words of the mouth; the thoughts of the mind; and the resolve (of the will) to preach to all the <title>Lotus Sutra</title>.The four kinds of inference in logic-- common, prejudged or opposing, insufficiently founded, arbitrary. Also, the four schools of thought I. According to 净影 Jingying they are (1) 立性宗 that everything exists, or has its own nature; e. g. Sarvstivda, in the 'lower' schools of Hnayna; (2) 破性宗 that everything has not a nature of its own; e. g. the 成实宗 a 'higher' Hnayna school, the Satyasiddhi; (3) 破相宗 that form has no reality, because of the doctrine of the void, 'lower' Mahyna; (4) 愿实宗 revelation of reality, that all comes from the <foreign lang="sa">bhtatathat</foreign>, 'higher ' Mahyna. II. According to 昙隐 Tanyin of the 大衍 monastery they are (1) 因缘宗, i. e. 立性宗 all things are causally produced; (2) 假名宗, i. e. 破性宗 things are but names; (3) 不宗, i. e. 破相宗, denying the reality of form, this school fails to define reality; (4) 宗, i. e. 显实宗 the school of the real, in contrast with the seeming.The four <foreign lang="sa">dhyna</foreign> heavens of form, and the four degrees of dhyna corresponding to them.v. 四记.The schools of 般若, 谛, 舍烦恼, and 苦 likened by 章安 Zhangan of the Tiantai to the 四教, i. e. seriatim: 别, 圆, 通, and 三藏.A study or contemplation of the 法相宗 Dharmalakana sect, on 名 the terms used, 义 the meanings of the things or phenomena, 自性 the nature of the things, 差别 their differentiation.Like four closing-in mountains are birth, age, sickness, and death; another group is age, sickness, death, and decay (衰, i. e. of wealth, honours, etc., or 无常 impermanence).Special study of or advancement in the four degrees, a method of the esoterics, formerly extending over 800 or 1, 000 days, later contracted to 200. The four 'degrees ' are 十八道, 胎藏, 金刚, and 护摩, but the order varies.The four <foreign lang="sa">prjika</foreign> sins resulting in excommunication, v. 波.The four universal vows of a Buddha or bodhisattva: 生无边誓愿度 to save all living beings without limit; 烦恼无数誓愿断 to put an end to all passions and delusions however numerous; 法门无尽誓愿学 to study and learn all methods and means without end; 佛道无上誓愿成 to become perfect in the supreme Buddha-law. The four vows are considered as arising one by one out of the 四谛 Four Noble Truths.The four vinaya and the five stras. The four vinaya 四律, or disciplinary regulations, are the 十诵律 Sarvstivda version tr. in 61 chuan by Punyatara; 四分律 Dharmagupta's version, tr. in 60 chuan by Buddhayaas; 僧祗律 Sghika version or Mahsghika version, tr. in 40 chuan, by Buddhabhadra; and 五部律 Mahsaka version, tr. in 30 chuan by Buddhajva and others, also known as <title>Mahsaka-nikya-pacavargavinaya</title>. The five stras 五论 are 毗尼母论; 摩得勒伽论; 善见论; 萨婆多论; and 明了论. v. 论.The four minutest forms or atoms perceptible to the four senses of sight, smell, taste, or touch; from these arise the 四大 four elements, from which arise the 五智 five wisdoms, q. v.The four nirvana virtues, or values, according to the Mahyna <title>Nirvana Sutra</title>: (1) 常德 permanence or eternity; (2) 乐德 joy; (3) 我德 personality or the soul; (4) 净德 purity. These four important terms, while denied in the lower realms, are affirmed by the sutra in the transcendental, or nirvana-realm.四德波罗蜜 The joyful realm, or acme of the above four virtues, the nirvana realm, the abode or <foreign lang="sa">dharmakya</foreign> of the Tathgata.The hearts of kindness, pity, joy, and indifference, idem 四无量心.copulation in the first and in the second <foreign lang="sa">devaloka</foreign>s, i. e. 四王 and 忉利 heavens; in the third it is by embrace; in the fourth, by holding hands; in the fifth, by mutual smiling; in the sixth by a mutual look.The state of a saint, i. e. beyond, or oblivious of the four conditions of 一异有无 unity, difference, existence, non-existence.idem 四念处.(四念处观); 四念住 smtyupasthna. The fourfold stage of mindfulness, thought, or meditation that follows the 五停心观 five-fold procedure for quieting the mind. This fourfold method, or objectivity of thought, is for stimulating the mind in ethical wisdom. It consists of contemplating (1) 身 the body as impure and utterly filthy; (2) 受 sensation, or consciousness, as always resulting in suffering; (3) 心 mind as impermanent, merely one sensation after another; (4) 法 things in general as being dependent and without a nature of their own. The four negate the ideas of permanence, joy, personality, and purity 常, 乐, 我, and 净, i. e. the four 倒, but v. 四德. They are further subdivided into 别 and 总 particular and general, termed 别相念处 and 总相念处, and there are further subdivisions.
Four objects on which memory or the thought should dwell-- the impurity of the body, that all sensations lead to suffering, that mind is impermanent, and that there is no such thing as an ego. There are other categories for thought or meditation.The four classes of 'prayer-beads', numbering 27, 54, 108, or 1, 080, styled 下品, 中品, 最胜, and 上品, lower, middle, superior, and most superior.The four kinds of conduct natural to a Bodhisattva, that arising from his native goodness, his vow-nature, his compliant nature, i. e. to the six <foreign lang="sa">pramit</foreign>s, and his transforming nature, i. e. his powers of conversion or salvation.The four enemies-- the passions-and-delusion mras, death mra, the five-<foreign lang="sa">skandha</foreign>s mras, and the supreme mra-king.As the sands of four Ganges.The four wicked <foreign lang="sa">bhiku</foreign>s who threw over the teaching of their Buddha 大庄严 Dazhuangyan after his nirvana; these suffered in the deepest hells, came forth purified, but have not been able to attain perfection because of their past unbelief; v. 佛藏经往古品. Also four disobedient <foreign lang="sa">bhiku</foreign>s who through much purgation ultimately became the Buddhas of the four points of the compass, 阿, 相, 无量寿, and 微妙声.(or 四恶道) The four <foreign lang="sa">apya</foreign>, or evil destinies: the hells, as hungry ghosts, animals, or <foreign lang="sa">asura</foreign>s. The <foreign lang="sa">asura</foreign>s are sometimes evil, sometimes good, hence the term 三恶道 'three evil destinies' excepts the <foreign lang="sa">asura</foreign>s.The four <foreign lang="sa">siddhnta</foreign>, v. 悉檀. The Buddha taught by (1) mundane or ordinary modes of expression; (2) individual treatment, adapting his teaching to the capacity of his hearers; (3) diagnostic treatment of their moral diseases; and (4) the perfect and highest truth.see 五悔 and omit the first.idem 烦恼.idem 四正勤.The four kinds of wisdom received: (1) by birth, or nature; (2) by hearing, or being taught; (3) by thought; (4) by <foreign lang="sa">dhyna</foreign> meditation.Four stages in moral development: that of release, or deliverance from the world on becoming a monk; that arising from the four meditations on the realms of form; that above the stage of 见道 q. v.; that in which all moral evil is ended and delusion ceases.The four erroneous tenets; also 四邪; 四迷; 四术; there are two groups: I. The four of the 外道 outsiders, or non-Buddhists, i. e. of Brahminism, concerning the law of cause and effect: (1) 邪因邪果 heretical theory of causation, e. g. creation by Mahesvara; (2) 无因有果 or 自然, effect independent of cause, e. g. creation without a cause, or spontaneous generation; (3) 有因无果 cause without effect, e. g. no future life as the result of this. (4) 无因无果 neither cause nor effect, e. g. that rewards and punishments are independent of morals. II. The four erroneous tenets of 内外道 insiders and outsiders, Buddhist and Brahman, also styled 四宗 the four schools, as negated in the 中论 <title>Mdhyamika stra</title>: (1) outsiders, who do not accept either the 人 <foreign lang="zh">ren</foreign> or 法 <foreign lang="zh">fa</foreign> ideas of 空 <foreign lang="zh">kong</foreign>; (2) insiders who hold the Abhidharma or Sarvstivd tenet, which recognizes 人空 human impersonality, but not 法空 the unreality of things; (3) also those who hold the 成实 Satyasiddhi tenet which discriminates the two meanings of 空 <foreign lang="zh">kong</foreign> but not clearly; and also (4) those in Mahyna who hold the tenet of the realists.The four Vajra-rulers of the four elements -- earth, water, fire, wind, and of the S. E., S. W., N. W,. and N. E.idem 四种总持.(or 四摄事) catu-sagraha-vastu; four all-embracing (bodhisattva) virtues: (1) 布施 <foreign lang="sa">dna</foreign>, giving what others like, in order to lead them to love and receive the truth; (2) 爱语 <foreign lang="sa">priyavacana</foreign>, affctionate, speech, with the same purpose; (3) 利行 <foreign lang="sa">arthaktya</foreign>, conduct proftable to others, with the same purpose; (4) 同事 <foreign lang="sa">samnrthat</foreign>, co-operation with and adaptation of oneself to others, to lead them into the truth.四摄; 四摄全刚 The four bodhisattvas in the Vajradhtu with the hook, the rope, the chain, and the bell, whose office is to 化他 convert the living.(四摩室) sm. A boundary, a separate dwelling, or dwellings (for monks and/or visitors).Four teachings, doctrines, or schools; five groups are given, whose titles are abbreviated to 光天晓苑龙: (1) 光宅四教 The four schools of 法云 Fayun of the 光宅 Guangzhai monastery are the four vehicles referred to in the burning house parable of the <title>Lotus Sutra</title>, i. e. <foreign lang="sa">rvaka</foreign>, <foreign lang="sa">pratyekabuddha</foreign>, bodhisattva, and the final or one vehicle teaching. (2) 天台四教 The Tiantai four are 藏通, 别, and 圆, v. 八教. (3) 晓公四教 The group of 元晓 Wnhyo of 海东 Haedong are the 三乘别教 represented by the 四谛缘起经; 三乘通教 represented by the 般若深密教; 一乘分教 represented by the 究网经; and 一乘满教 represented by the 华严经. (4) 苑公四教 The group of 慧苑 Huiyuan: the schools of unbelievers, who are misled and mislead; of <foreign lang="sa">rvaka</foreign>s and <foreign lang="sa">pratyekabuddha</foreign>s who know only the phenomenal <foreign lang="sa">bhtatathat</foreign>; of novitiate bodhisattvas who know only the noumenal <foreign lang="sa">bhtatathat</foreign>; and of fully developed bodhisattvas, who know both. (5) 龙树四教 Ngrjuna's division of the canon into 有 dealing with existence, or reality, cf. the 四阿含; 空 the Void, cf. 般若经; 亦有亦 空 both, cf. 深密经; and 非有非 空 neither, cf. 中论.Now a 言 Shingon term; the 四教 are the Tiantai four schools of 显 open or exoteric teaching; the 三密 are the Shingon esoteric teaching in which the three 身口意 body, mouth, and mind have special functions.The Tiantai four main doctrinal divisions as above and its three kinds of meditation.Tiantai's doctrine of the four developments of the Buddha's own teaching, v. above, and the five periods of the same, v. 五时教.A work of 智□ Zhiyi of Tiantai.Four stages, as given in the 大日经, 具缘品, i. e. 藏, 通, 别, and 圆 q. v.The four fast days, i. e. at the quarters of the moon-- new, full 8th, and 23rd.A summary of the 临济 Linji school, an offshoot of the Chan, in reference to subjective, objective, both, neither.The four quarters of the compass; a square, square; the E. is ruled by Indra, S. by Yama, W. by Varua, and N. by Vairamaa; the N. E. is ruled by 伊舍尼 Ina, S. E. by 护摩 Homa, S. W. by 涅哩底 Nirti, and the N. W. by 瘐 Varua.The four Buddhas of the four regions -- E. the world of 香积 abundant fragrance where reigns 阿 Akobhya; S. of 欢喜 pleasure, 相 Ratnaketu; W. of 安乐 restfulness, or joyful comfort, 无量寿 Amitbha; and N. of 莲华庄严 lotus adornment, 微妙声 ? Amoghasiddhi, or kyamuni.The four 'generals' or guardians of the Law, of the four directions: N. 散脂四方, E. 乐欲四方, S. 檀帝四方, W. 善现四方. Each has 500 followers and twenty-eight companies of demons and spirits. Cf. 四天王.Four benefactions, i. e. pen, ink, sutras, preaching.(or 四非常偈)  Eight stanzas in the 仁王经, two each on 无常 impermanence, 苦 suffering, 空 the void, and 无我 non-personality; the whole four sets embodying the impermanence of all things.(四无畏)  The four kinds of fearlessness, or courage, of which there are two groups: Buddha-fearlessness arises from his omniscience; perfection of character; overcoming opposition; and ending of suffering. Bodhisattva-fearlessness arises from powers of memory; of moral diagnosis and application of the remedy; of ratiocination; and of solving doubts. v. 智度论 48 and 5.(or 四无碍智 or 四无碍辩). pratisavid, the four unhindered or unlimited bodhisattva powers of interpretation, or reasoning, i. e. in 法 dharma, the letter of the law; 义 artha, its meaning; ? nirukti, in any language, or form of expression; 乐说 pratibhna, in eloquence, or pleasure in speaking, or argument.idem 四空处, 四空定.<term lang="sa">catvri apramni</term>; the four immeasurables, or infinite Buddha-states of mind, also styled 四等 the four equalities, or universals, and 四梵行 noble acts or characteristics; i. e. four of the twelve 禅 <foreign lang="sa">dhyna</foreign>s: 慈无量心 boundless kindness, <foreign lang="sa">maitr</foreign>, or bestowing of joy or happiness; 悲无量心 boundless pity, <foreign lang="sa">karu</foreign>, to save from suffering; 喜无量心 boundless joy, <foreign lang="sa">mudit</foreign>, on seeing others rescued from suffering; 舍无量心 limitless indifference, <foreign lang="sa">upek</foreign>, i. e. rising above these emotions, or giving up all things, e. g. distinctions of friend and enemy, love and hate, etc. The esoteric sect has a special definition of its own, connecting each of the four with 普贤; 虚 空 藏; 观自在; or 卢 空 库.catvra sry the four suns, i. e. Avaghoa, Devabodhisattva, Ngrjuna, and Kumralabdha (or -lata).Four Shingon emblems, aids to Yoga-possession by a Buddha or bodhisattva; they are 钩, 索, , 铃, a hook, a cord, a lock, and a bell; the hook for summoning, the cord for leading, the lock for firmly holding, and the bell for the resultant joy. Also, the four Veda stras.A mountain range in Ningbo prefecture where the 四明 are clearly seen, i. e. sun, moon, stars, and constellations. 知礼 Zhili of the Sung dynasty is known as the 四明尊者 honoured one of Siming and his school as the 四明家 Siming school in the direct line of Tiantai. In Japan Mt. Hiei 比睿山 is known by this title, through Dengyo 传教 the founder of the Japanese Tiantai School.The four forms of wisdom of a Buddha according to the 法相 Dharmalakana school: (1) 大圆镜智 the great mirror wisdom of Akobhya; (2) 平等性智 the universal wisdom of Ratnaketu; (3) 妙观察智 the profound observing wisdom of Amitbha; (4) 成所作智 the perfecting wisdom of Amoghasiddhi. There are various other groups.Four wisdom symbols of the Shingon cult: 大智印 or 摩诃岐若勿他罗 mahjna-mudr, the forms of the images; 三昧耶印 samaya-jna-mudr, their symbols and manual signs; 法智印 dharma-jna-mudr, the magic formula of each; 羯摩智印 karma-jna-mudr, the emblems of their specific functions.The praise hymns of the four 'wisdoms ', v. 四智.ha, the fourth month.The eighth of the fourth moon, the Buddha's birthday.The four functioning forms, i. e. 生 birth, 住 stay, 异 change, and 灭 extinction; v. 四相.The four books of Tiantai on meditation 止观, i. e. 摩诃止观; 禅波罗蜜; 六妙门; and 坐禅法要.The four fundamental states-- birth, stay, change, and extinction (or death), v. 四相.idem 四执.The four <foreign lang="sa">phala</foreign>, i. e. fruitions, or rewards -- <foreign lang="sa">srota-panna-phala</foreign>, sakradgmi-<foreign lang="sa">phala</foreign>, <foreign lang="sa">angmiphala</foreign>, <foreign lang="sa">arhat-phala</foreign>, i. e. four grades of saintship; see 须陀洹; 斯陀含, 阿那含, and 阿离汉. The four titles are also applied to four grades of <foreign lang="sa">ramaa</foreign>s-- yellow and blue flower <foreign lang="sa">ramaa</foreign>s, lotus <foreign lang="sa">ramaa</foreign>s, meek <foreign lang="sa">ramaa</foreign>s, and ultra-meek <foreign lang="sa">ramaa</foreign>s.When the Buddha died, of the eight <foreign lang="sa">la</foreign> trees surrounding him four are said to have withered while four continued in full leaf-- a sign that the four doctrines of 苦 suffering, 空 the void, 无常 impermanence, and 无我 impersonality were to perish and those of 常 permanence, 叶 joy, 我 personality, and 净 purity, the transcendent bodhisattva doctrines, were to flourish.(or 四根本重罪)  idem 四波罗夷.The noble state of unlimited 慈, 悲, 喜, 舍 love, pity, joy, and indifference.Four ways of attaining arhatship, idem 四梵住, except that the last of the four is 护 protection (of others).The four Brahmacrins who resolved to escape death each on mountain, sea, in the air, or the: market place, and yet failed; v. 山.The four desires or passions: 情 sexual love; 色 sexual beauty or attractiveness; 食 food; 淫 lust.<foreign lang="sa">sayakpraha</foreign>, v. 三十七道品; the four right efforts一to put an end to existing evil; prevent evil arising; bring good into existence; develop existing good; 四正断; 四意断 are similar but the third point is the conservation of the good.Four poisonous snakes (in a basket), e. g. the four elements, earth, water, fire, and air, of which a man is formed.v. 四恶比丘.The four rivers-- Ganges, Sindhu (Indus), Vku (Oxus), and Trm, all reputed to arise out of a lake, Anavatapta, in Tibet.There are several groups of four dharma: (1) 教法 the teaching of the Buddha); 理法 its principles, or meaning; 行法 its practice; 果法 its fruits or rewards. (2) Another group relates to bodhisattvas, their never losing the <foreign lang="sa">bodhi</foreign>-mind, or the wisdom attained, or perseverance in progress, or the monastic forest life (<foreign lang="sa">rayaka</foreign>). (3) Also 信解行证 faith, discernment, performance, and assurance. (4) The Pure-land 'True' sect of Japan has a division: 教法, i. e. the 大无量寿经; 行法 the practice of the seventeenth of Amitbha's vows; 信法 faith in the eighteenth; and 证法 proof of the eleventh. The most important work of Shinran, the founder of the sect, is these four, i. e. 教行信证. (5) A 'Lotus ' division of 四法 is the answer to a question of Puxian (Samantabhadra) how the Lotus is to be possessed after the Buddha's demise, i. e. by thought (or protection) of the Buddhas; the cultivation of virtue; entry into correct <foreign lang="sa">dhyna</foreign>; and having a mind to save all creatures.idem 四法 #4; the three vows are the seventeenth, eighteenth, and eleventh of Amitbha.The four imperishables-- the correctly receptive heart, the diamond, the relics of a Buddha, and the palace of the <foreign lang="sa">deva</foreign>s of light and sound, bhasvras.The seal or impression of the four dogmas, suffering, impermanence, non-ego, nirvana, see 四法本末.idem 四种檀法.The Buddha' s gift of the four laws or dogmas, that all things are impermanent, that all (sentient) existence is suffering, that there is no (essential) personality, that all form (or matter) returns to the void.The alpha and omega in four laws or dogmas-- that nothing is permanent, that all things involve suffering, that there is no personality, and that nirvana is 永寂 eternal rest.四种法界 The four dharma-realms of the Huayan School: (1) 事法界 the phenomenal realm, with differentiation; (2) 理四法 noumenal with unity; (3) 理事无碍法界 both 理 noumenal and 事 phenomenal are interdependent; (4) 事事无碍法界 phenomena are also interdependent.An abbreviation for 四波罗蜜菩萨. The four female attendants on Vairocana in the Vajradhtu, evolved from him, each of them a 'mother' of one of the four Buddhas of the four quarters; v. 四佛, etc.四重; 四弃, 四极重感堕罪 The four <foreign lang="sa">prjika</foreign>s, or grievous sins of monks or nuns: (1) <foreign lang="sa"> abrahmacarya</foreign>, sexual immorality, or bestiality; (2) <foreign lang="sa">adattdna</foreign>, stealing; (3) <foreign lang="sa">vadhahia</foreign> killing; (4) <foreign lang="sa"> uttaramanuyadharma-prlapa</foreign>, false speaking.catur-dvpa; the four inhabited continents of every universe; they are situated S., E., W., and N. of the central mountain Sumeru; S. is Jambudvpa 暗部洲; E. Prva-videha 东毗提诃; W. Apara-godnya 牛货; and N. Uttarakuru 瞿卢.The four currents (that carry the unthinking along): i. e. the illusions of 见 seeing things as they seem, not as they really are; 欲 desires; 有 existence, life; 无明 ignorance, or an unenlightened condition.The four oceans around Mount Sumeru; cf. 九山八海.Honorific title of the monk 敬脱 Jingtuo of the Sui dynasty.The four furnaces, or altars of the esoteric cult, each differing in shape: earth, square; water, round; fire, triangular; wind, half-moon shape.The four delusions in reference to the ego: 我痴 ignorance in regard to the ego; 我见 holding to the ego idea; 我慢 self-esteem, egotism, pride; 我爱 self-seeking, or desire, both the latter arising from belief in the ego. Also 四惑.(or 四爱起) Four sources of affection: the giving or receiving of clothing, or food, or bedding, or independently of gifts.(四王天) catur-mahrja-kyiks, the four heavens of the four <foreign lang="sa">deva</foreign>-kings, i. e. the lowest of the six heavens of desire; v. 四天王.The 四王天 and <foreign lang="sa">tryastrias</foreign>, Indra's heaven.catur-yoni, the four forms of birth: (1) 胎 or 生 jaryuja, viviparous, as with mammalia; (2) 卵生 aaja, oviparous, as with birds; (3) 湿生 or 寒热和合生 sasvedaja, moisture, or water-born, as with worms and fishes; (4) 化生 aupapduka, metamorphic, as with moths from the chrysalis, or with <foreign lang="sa">deva</foreign>s, or in the hells, or the first beings in a newly evolved world.A <foreign lang="sa">pratyekabuddha</foreign> method of obtaining release, by intensive effort, at the shortest in four rebirths, at the longest in a hundred kalpas.The four fields for cultivating happiness -- animals; the poor; parents, etc.; the religion.The four realms, idem 四大 earth, water, fire, and air.The four are the substance and upholders of all things.The four ailments, or mistaken ways of seeking perfection: 作病 'works' or effort; 任病 laissez-faire; 止病 cessation of all mental operation; 灭病 annihilaon (of all desire).Four hundred.The 404 ailments of the body; each of the four elements-- earth, water, fire, and wind -- is responsible for 101; there are 202 fevers, or hot humours caused by earth and fire; and 202 chills or cold humours caused by water and wind; v. 智度论 65.The 400 disciplinary laws of a bodhisattva, referred to in the 药师经 but without detail.The four <foreign lang="sa">avasth</foreign>, or states of all phenomena, i. e. 生住异灭 birth, being, change (i. e. decay), and death; also 四有相. There are several groups, e. g. 果报四相 birth, age, disease, death. Also 藏识四相 of the <title>Awakening of Faith</title> referring to the initiation, continuation, change, and cessation of the <foreign lang="sa">laya-vijna</foreign>. Also 我人四相 The ideas: (1) that there is an ego; (2) that man is different from other organisms; (3) that all the living are produced by the <foreign lang="sa">skandha</foreign>s; (4) that life is limited to the organism. Also 智境四相 dealing differently with the four last headings 我; 人; 生; and 寿相.The four powers of sight of bodhisattvas, a Buddha has a fifth power; v. 五眼.The four who know the workings of one's mind for good or evil-- heaven, earth, one's intimates, and oneself.idem 四如意足.(四禅天) The four <foreign lang="sa">dhyna</foreign> heavens, 四静虑 (四静虑天), i. e. the division of the eighteen <foreign lang="sa">brahmaloka</foreign>s into four <foreign lang="sa">dhyna</foreign>s: the disciple attains to one of these heavens according to the <foreign lang="sa">dhyna</foreign> he observes: (1) 初禅天 The first region, 'as large as one whole universe' comprises the three heavens, Brahma-priadya, Brahma-purohita, and Mahbrahma, 梵辅, 梵, and 大梵天; the inhabitants are without gustatory or olfactory organs, not needing food, but possess the other four of the six organs. (2) 二禅天 The second region, equal to 'a small chiliocosmos' 小千界, comprises the three heavens, according to Eitel, 'Parttbha, Aprambha, and bhsvara, ' i. e. 少光 minor light, 无量光 infinite light, and 极光净 utmost light purity; the inhabitants have ceased to require the five physical organs, possessing only the organ of mind. (3) 三禅天 The third region, equal to 'a middling chiliocosmos '中千界, comprises three heavens; Eitel gives them as Parttaubha, Apramaubha, and ubhaktsna, i. e. 少净 minor purity, 无量净 infinite purity, and 净 universal purity; the inhabitants still have the organ of mind and are receptive of great joy. (4) 四禅天 The fourth region, equal to a great chiliocosmos, 大千界, comprises the remaining nine <foreign lang="sa">brahmaloka</foreign>s, namely, Puyaprasava, Anabhraka, Bhatphala, Asajisattva, Avha, Atapa, Suda, Sudarana, and Akaniha (Eitel). The Chinese titles are 福生 felicitous birth, 无云 cloudless, 广果 large fruitage, 无烦 no vexations, atapa is 无热 no heat, suda is 善见 beautiful to see, sudarana is 善现 beautiful appearing, two others are 色究竟 the end of form, and 无想天 the heaven above thought, but it is difficult to trace avha and akaniha; the inhabitants of this fourth region still have mind. The number of the <foreign lang="sa">dhyna</foreign> heavens differs; the Sarvstivdins say 16, the 经 or Sutra school 17, and the Sthavir school 18. Eitel points out that the first <foreign lang="sa">dhyna</foreign> has one world with one moon, one mem, four continents, and six <foreign lang="sa">devaloka</foreign>s; the second <foreign lang="sa">dhyna</foreign> has 1, 000 times the worlds of the first; the third has 1, 000 times the worlds of the second; the fourth <foreign lang="sa">dhyna</foreign> has 1, 000 times those of the third. Within a kalpa of destruction 坏劫 the first is destroyed fifty-six times by fire, the second seven by water, the third once by wind, the fourth 'corresponding to a state of absolute indifference' remains 'untouched' by all the other evolutions; when 'fate (天命) comes to an end then the fourth <foreign lang="sa">dhyna</foreign> may come to an end too, but not sooner'.The four <foreign lang="sa">dhyna</foreign>s on the form-realms and the eight concentrations, i. e. four on the form-realms and four on the formless. realms.The four <foreign lang="sa">dhyna</foreign>-concentrations which lead to the four <foreign lang="sa">dhyna</foreign> heavenly regions, see above.Four kinds; where phrases containing the 种 are not found here, they may occur direct, e. g. 四法界.The four <foreign lang="sa">samaya</foreign>, i. e. the four <foreign lang="sa">prjika</foreign>s-- killing, stealing, carnality, lying.The four kinds of faith given in the <title>Awakening of Faith</title>, i. e. (1) in the 如 q. v. as the teacher of all Buddhas and fount of all action; (2) in Buddha, or the Buddhas; (3) in the Dharma; and (4) in the Sarogha.The four classes of <foreign lang="sa">deva</foreign>s include (1) 名天 famous rulers on earth styled 天王, 天子; (2) 生天 the highest incarnations of the six paths; (3) 净天 the pure, or the saints, from <foreign lang="sa">rvaka</foreign>s to <foreign lang="sa">pratyekabuddha</foreign>s, and (4) 义天 all bodhisattvas above the ten stages 十住. The Buddhas are not included; 智度论 22.The four kinds of <foreign lang="sa">dhra</foreign>  陀罗尼 q. v.The four deadly sins, i. e. the four <foreign lang="sa">prjika</foreign>s-- killing, stealing, carnality, lying.四种悉地; 四种成就法 The four kinds of altar-worship of the esoteric sect for (1) averting calamities from self and others; (2) seeking good fortune; (3) seeking the love and protection of Buddhas; (4) subduing enemies.Four kinds of rebirth dependent on present deeds: from obscurity and poverty to be reborn in the same condition; from obscurity and poverty to be reborn in light and honour; from light and honour to be reborn in obscurity and poverty; from light and honour to be reborn in the heavens.v. 四法界.The four grades of earnest doers, who follow the bodhisattva discipline and attain to the 十住, 十行, 十向, and 十地.The four kinds of examination, a method of repentance as a way to get rid of any sin: study the cause of the sin, which lies in ignorance, or lack of clear understanding, e. g. moth and fame; study its inevitable effect, its karma; study oneself, introspection; and study the Tathgata in his perfect character, and saving power.(or四空天) <term lang="sa">catur-rpya brahmaloka</term>s; also 四无色界 and see 四空定. The four immaterial or formless heavens, arpa-dhtu, above the eighteen <foreign lang="sa">brahmaloka</foreign>s: (1) 空无边处 <foreign lang="sa">knantyyatana</foreign>, also termed 虚空 处 the state or heaven of boundless space; (2) 识无边处 <foreign lang="sa">vijnanntyyatana</foreign>, of boundless knowledge; (3) 无所有处 kicanyyatana, of nothing, or nonexistence; (4) 非想非非想处 <foreign lang="sa">naivasanjnasajnyatana</foreign>, also styled 非有想非无想 the state of neither thinking nor not thinking (which may resemble a state of intuition). Existence in the first state lasts 20, 000 great kalpas, increasing respectively to 40, 000, 60, 000 and 80, 000 in the other three.四无色定 The last four of the twelve <foreign lang="sa">dhyna</foreign>s; the auto-hypnotic, or ecstatic entry into the four states represented by the four <foreign lang="sa">dhyna</foreign> heavens, i. e. 四 空 处 supra. In the first, the mind becomes void and vast like space; in the second, the powers of perception and understanding are unlimited; in the third, the discriminative powers of mind are subdued; in the fourth, the realm of consciousness or knowledge) without thought is reached, e. g. intuitive wisdom. These four are considered both as states of <foreign lang="sa">dhyna</foreign>, and as heavens into which one who practices these forms of <foreign lang="sa">dhyna</foreign> may be born.A verse from the 庄严论 <title>Zhuangyan lun</title>--  Health is the best wealth,<lb></lb>Contentment the best riches,<lb></lb> Friendship the best relationship,<lb></lb>Nirvana the best joy.<lb></lb>The four virtues which a Buddha out of his infinite heart manifests equally to all; also called 四无量 q. w. They are: 慈悲喜舍 <foreign lang="sa">maitr</foreign>, <foreign lang="sa">karu</foreign>, <foreign lang="sa">mudit</foreign>, <foreign lang="sa">upek</foreign>, i. e. kindness, pity, joy and indifference, or 护 protection. Another group is 字语法身, i. e. 字 that all Buddhas have the same title or titles; 语 speak the same language; 法 proclaim the same truth; and 身 have each the threefold body, or <foreign lang="sa">trikya</foreign>. A third group is 诸法 all things are equally included in the <foreign lang="sa">bhtatathat</foreign>; 发心 the mind-nature being universal, its field of action is universal; 道等 the way or method is also universal; therefore 慈悲 the mercy (of the Buddhas) is universal for all.The four knots, or bonds, <foreign lang="sa"> sayojana</foreign>, which hinder free development; they are likened to the 四翳 q. v. four things that becloud, i. e. rain clouds, resembling desire; dust-storms, hate; smoke, ignorance; and <foreign lang="sa">asura</foreign>s, gain.The four half points of the compass, N. E., N. W., S. E., S. W.The four <foreign lang="sa">bandhana</foreign>, or bonds are (1) desire, resentment, heretical morality, egoism; or (2) desire, possession (or existence), ignorance, and unenlightened views.The four films, or things that becloud, i. e. rain-clouds; dust-storms; smoke; and <foreign lang="sa">asura</foreign>s, i. e. eclipses of sun and moon; emblematic of desire, hate, ignorance, and pride; cf. 四结.The four-armed svastika, or thunderbolt.idem 四谛.The four with victorious bodies, who were transformed independently of normal rebirth; also styled 解行身 bodies set free from all physical taint, thus attaining to Buddhahood. The four are the 龙女 dragon daughter of the <title>Lotus Sutra</title>, who instantly became a male bodhisattva; and three others of the 华严 Huayan sutra, i. e. 善财童子; 兜率天子, and 普庄严童子.The four self-raidings, or self-injuries -- in youth not to study from morn till night; in advancing years not to cease sexual intercourse; wealthy and not being charitable; not accepting the Buddha's teaching.The four sovereign powers: 戒 the moral law; 神通 supernatural powers; 智 knowledge; and 慧 wisdom.The four givings, i. e. of goods of the Truth, of courage (or fearlessness), and the giving up of the passions and delusions; cf. <foreign lang="sa">dna-pramit</foreign>, 舍.The four good physicians, or medicines; idem 四圣行.The four monastic annual periods -- beginning of summer, end of summer, winter solstice, and the new year.The four (divine) flowers-- mandra, mahmandra, majaka, and mahmajaka. Also, puarka, utpala, padma, and kumuda or white, blue, red, and yellow lotuses.The pleasure grounds outside 善见城 Sudarana, the heavenly city of Indra: E. 车苑 Caitrarathavana, the park of chariots; S. □恶苑 Parakavana, the war park; W. 杂林苑 Mirakvana, intp. as the park where all desires are fulfilled; N. 喜林苑 Nandanavana, the park of all delights. Also 四园.The four miseries, or sufferings -- birth, age, disease, and death.The four bodhisattvas-- Avalokitevara, Maitreya, Samantabhadra, and Majur. Also, the four chief bodhisattvas in the Garbhadhtu. There are also the 本化四菩萨 of the <title>Lotus Sutra</title>, named 上行, 无边行, 净行, and 安立行.idem 四毒蛇. The <title>Fanyimingyi</title> under this heading gives the parable of a man who fled from the two bewildering forms of life and death, and climbed down a rope (of life) 命根, into the well of impermanence 无常, where two mice, night and day, gnawed the rattan rope; on the four sides four snakes 四蛇 sought to poison him, i. e. the 四大 or four elements of his physical nature); below were three dragons 三毒龙 breathing fire and trying to seize him. On looking up he saw that two 象 elephants (darkness and light) had come to the mouth of the well; he was in despair, when a bee flew by and dropped some honey (the five desires 五欲) into his mouth, which he ate and entirely forgot his peril.The four disciplinary processes: enlightenment; good deeds; wisdom; and worship.To meditate upon the implications or disciplines of pain, unreality, impermanence, and the non-ego.The four <foreign lang="sa">yna</foreign>s or vehicles, idem 四乘.The four most important chapters of the <title>Lotus Sutra</title>, i. e. 方便品; 安乐行品; 寿量品, and 普门品; this is Tiantai's selection; the Nichiren sect makes 劝持品 the second and 神力品 the fourth.The 'four intelligences, or apprehensions' of the <title>Awakening of Faith</title> 起信论, q. v., viz. 本觉, 相似觉, 随分觉, and 究竟觉.(or 四答) The Buddha's for methods of dealing with questions: direct answer, discriminating answer, questioning in return, and silence.Four famous stras: (1) 中观论<title>Pryamla-strak</title>  by Ngrjuna, four <foreign lang="zh">juan</foreign>; (2) 百论 <title>ata-stra</title> by <foreign lang="sa">deva</foreign>bodhisattva, two <foreign lang="zh">juan</foreign>; (3) 十二门论 <title>Dvdaanikya(-mukha)-stra</title> by Ngrjuna, one <foreign lang="zh">juan</foreign>; (4) 大智度论 <title>Mahprajpramit-stra</title> by Ngrjuna, 100 <foreign lang="zh">juan</foreign>. During the Sui dynasty the followers of these four stras formed the 四论宗.The four great scholars (among the 500 <foreign lang="sa">arhat</foreign>s) who made the <title>Vibh-stra</title>, a critical commentary on the Abhidharma. Their names are 世友 Vasumitra, 妙音 Ghoa, 法救 Dharmatrta, and 觉天 Buddhadeva.catvri-rya-satyni; 四圣谛; 四谛. The four dogmas, or noble truths, the primary and fundamental doctrines of kyamuni, said to approximate to the form of medical diagnosis. They are pain or 'suffering, its cause, its ending, the way thereto; that existence is suffering, that human passion (<foreign lang="sa">tah</foreign>, 欲 desire) is the cause of continued suffering, that by the destruction of human passion existence may be brought to an end; that by a life of holiness the destruction of human passion may be attained'. Childers. The four are 苦, 聚 (or 集), 灭, and 道谛, i. e. <foreign lang="sa">dukha</foreign> 豆□, <foreign lang="sa">samudaya</foreign> 三牟提耶, <foreign lang="sa">nirodha</foreign> 尼栖陀, and <foreign lang="sa">mrga</foreign> 末加. Eitel interprets them (1) 'that 'misery' is a necessary attribute of sentient existence'; (2) that 'the 'accumulation' of misery is caused by the passions'; (3) that 'the 'extinction' of passion is possible; (4) <foreign lang="sa">mrga</foreign> is 'the doctrine of the 'path' that leads to the extinction of passion'. (1) 苦 suffering is the lot of the 六趣 six states of existence; (2) 集 is the aggregation (or exacerbation) of suffering by reason of the passions; (3) 灭 is nirvana, the extinction of desire and its consequences, and the leaving of the sufferings of mortality as void and extinct; (4) 道 is the way of such extinction, i. e. the 八正道 eightfold correct way. The first two are considered to be related to this life, the last two to 出世间 a life outside or apart from the world. The four are described as the fundamental doctrines first preached to his five former ascetic companions. Those who accepted these truths were in the stage of <foreign lang="sa">rvaka</foreign>. There is much dispute as to the meaning of 灭 'extinction' as to whether it means extinction of suffering, of passion, or of existence. The <title>Nirvana Sutra</title> 18 says that whoever accepts the four dogmas will put an end to births and deaths 若能见四谛则得断生死 which does not of necessity mean the termination of existence but that of continued transmigration. v. 灭.The sutra of the four dogmas, tr. by 安世高 An Shih Kao, one <foreign lang="zh">juan</foreign>. 四趣 Durgati; the four evil directions or destinations: the hells, hungry ghosts, animals, <foreign lang="sa">asura</foreign>s; v. 四恶.The four <foreign lang="sa">kya</foreign>, or 'bodies'. The <title>Lakvatra-stra</title> gives 化佛; 功德佛; 智慧佛 and 如如佛; the first is the <foreign lang="sa">nirmakya</foreign>, the second and third <foreign lang="sa">sabhogakya</foreign>, and the fourth <foreign lang="sa">dharmakya</foreign>. The 唯识论 gives 自性身; 他受用身; 自受用身, and 变化身, the first being 法身, the second and third 报身, and the fourth 化身. The Tiantai School gives 法身; 报身; 应身, and 化身. The esoteric sect has four divisions of the 法身. See 三身.The four vehicles 四乘 of the <title>Lotus Sutra</title> 譬品, i. e. goat, deer, bullock, and great white-bullock carts.The Lotus School, which adds to the <foreign lang="sa">tryna</foreign>, or Three Vehicles, a fourth which includes the other three, viz. the 一佛乘 q. v.The four yokes, or fetters, i. e. 欲 desire, 有 possessions and existence, 见 (unenlightened or non-Buddhist) views, 无明 ignorance.The four wheels or circles: (1) 大地四轮 the four on which the earth rests, wind (or air), water, metal, and space. (2) Four images with wheels, yellow associated with metal or gold, white with water, red with fire, and black with wind. (3) The four <foreign lang="sa">dhyni</foreign>-buddhas, 金刚轮 Akobhya; 轮 Ratnasabhava; 法轮 Amitbha; 羯磨轮 Amoghasiddhi. (4) Also the four metals, gold, silver, copper, iron, of the <foreign lang="sa">cakravartin</foreign> kings.The four kinds of <foreign lang="sa">cakravartin</foreign> kings.The four grades: (1) <foreign lang="sa">bhiku</foreign>, <foreign lang="sa">bhiku</foreign>, <foreign lang="sa">upsaka</foreign>, <foreign lang="sa">upsik</foreign>, i. e. monks, nuns, male and female disciples, v. 四; (2) men, <foreign lang="sa">deva</foreign>s, <foreign lang="sa">nga</foreign>s, and ghosts 鬼.saindhava, 先陀婆 rock-salt, but intp. as salt, water, a utensil, and a horse, the four necessaries, i. e. water for washing, salt for food, a vessel to contain it, and a horse for progress; also called 四实.(四运心) The four stages of a thought: not yet arisen, its initiation, its realization, its passing away, styled 未念, 欲念, 正念, and 念巳.idem 四执.The Dao or road means the nirvana road; the 'four' are rather modes of progress, or stages in it: (1) 加行道 discipline or effort, i. e. progress from the 三贤 and 四善根 stages to that of the 三学位, i. e. morality, meditation, and understanding; (2) 无间道 uninterrupted progress to the stage in which all delusion is banished; (3) 解脱道 liberaton, or freedom, reaching the state of assurance or proof and knowledge of the truth; and (4) 胜进道 surpassing progress in <foreign lang="sa">dhyni</foreign>-wisdom. Those four stages are also associated with those of <foreign lang="sa">srota-panna</foreign>, <foreign lang="sa">sakdgmin</foreign>, <foreign lang="sa">angmin</foreign>, and <foreign lang="sa">arhat</foreign>.idem 四执.The four classes, e. g. <foreign lang="sa">srota-panna</foreign>, <foreign lang="sa">sakdgmin</foreign>, <foreign lang="sa">angmin</foreign>, and <foreign lang="sa">arhat</foreign>. v. 四道.
