ra. As Pica, head of the demons, he is represented with three eyes and eight arms, and riding on a white bull; a bull or a linga being his symbol. The esoteric school takes him for the transformation body of Vairocana, and as appearing in many forms, e.g. Viu, Nryana (i.e. Brahm), etc. His wife (akti) is Bhm, or 大自在天妇. As uddhvsa, or Pure dwelling, he is described as a bodhisattva of the tenth or highest degree, on the point of entering Buddhahood. There is dispute as to whether both are the same being, or entirely different. The term also means the sixth or highest of the six desire heavens.The abode of Mahevara at the apex of the form realm. Also, the condition or place from which the highest type of bodhisattva proceeds to Buddhahood, whence it is also styled 净居天 the pure abode heaven.mahparinirva, explained by 大入灭息 the great, or final entrance into extinction and cessation; or 大圆寂入 great entrance into perfect rest; 大灭度 great extinction and passing over (from mortality). It is interpreted in Mahyna as meaning the cessation or extinction of passion and delusion, of mortality, and of all activities, and deliverance into a state beyond these concepts. In Mahyna it is not understood as the annihilation, or cessation of existence; the reappearance of Dpakara 然灯 (who had long entered nirva) along with kyamuni on the Vulture Peak supports this view. It is a state above all terms of human expression. See the <title>Lotus Sutra</title> and the <title>Nirva stra</title>.The Mah-parinirva stras, commonly called the 涅盘经 Nirva stras, said to have been delivered by kyamuni just before his death. The two Hnayna versions are found in the 长阿含游行经. The Mahyna has two Chinese versions, the northern in 40 juan, and the southern, a revision of the northern version in 36 juan. Faxian's version is styled 大般泥洹经 6 juan. Treatises on the stra are  大般涅盘经后分 2 juan tr. by Jnabhadra; 大般涅盘经疏 33 juan; 大般涅盘经论 1 juan by Vasubandhu, tr. by Bodhidharma.The worship of a new copy of the stra when finished, an act first attributed to Xuanzang.Mah-prajpramit stra, said to have been delivered by kyamuni in four places at sixteen assemblies, i.e. Gidhraka near Rjagha (Vulture Peak); rvast; Paranirmitavaavartin, and Veluvana near Rjagha (Bamboo Garden). It consists of 600 juan as translated by Xuanzang. Parts of it were translated by others under various titles and considerable differences are found in them. It is the fundamental philosophical work of the Mahyna school, the formulation of wisdom, which is the sixth pramit.The Mah-prajpramit-stra.The great ship of salvation -- Mahyna.The captain of the great ship of salvation, Buddha.The great bitter sea, or great sea of suffering i.e. of mortality in the six <foreign lang="sa">gati</foreign>, or ways of incarnate existence.puarka, 分陀利; 芬利; 奔茶 the great white lotus; the last of the eight cold hells is so called.The wisdom of the great lotus, <foreign lang="sa">samdhi</foreign>-wisdom, the penetrating wisdom of Amitbha.The great Lotus heaven in the Paradise of the West.The banner of great bodhi, an esoteric symbol of Buddha-enlightenment.The great bodhi, i.e. Mahyna or Buddha-enlightenment, as contrasted with the inferior bodhi of the <foreign lang="sa">rvaka</foreign> and <foreign lang="sa">pratyekabuddha</foreign>.bodhisattva-mahsattva, a great Bodhisattva.Mahsatya-nirgrantha. An ascetic who is said to have become a disciple of the Buddha."The Tripitaka at a Glance" in 10 juan by 陈实 Chen Shi of the Ming dynasty.A catalogue of the Korean canon in 3 juan.The Tripiaka; the Buddhist canon.The monk's patch-robe, made in varying grades from nine to twenty-five patches.The supreme bodhi, or enlightenment, and the enlightening power of a Buddha.The World-honored One of the great enlightenment, an appellation of the Buddha.The mother of the great enlightenment, an appellation of Majur.The great enlightened golden <foreign lang="sa">i</foreign>, a name given to Buddha in the Song dynasty.idem 大智度论.Mahvdin, Doctor of the stras, a title given to eminent teachers, especially of the Skhya and Vaiseika schools.Great elephant (or nga) treasure, an incense supposed to be produced by ngas or dragons fighting.Daxian (Jap. Daiken), a Korean monk who lived in China during the Tang dynasty, of the 法相 Dharmalakaa school, noted for his annotations on the stras and styled 古记 the archaeologist.mahmajaka 摩诃曼珠沙 or <foreign lang="la">rubia cordifolia</foreign>, from which madder is made.Born by the highway side, v. 周那 Cunda; also 纯陀.The great body, i.e. the <foreign lang="sa">nirmakya</foreign>, or transformable body 化身 of a Buddha. Also, Mahkya, a king of garuas.The great bullock-cart in the parable of the burning house, i.e. Mahyna, v. <title>Lotus Sutra</title>.idem 佛顶尊.v. 大胜金刚.One of the thirty-three bodhisattvas in the 金刚手 court of the <foreign lang="sa">Garbhadhtu</foreign> group, destroyer of delusion. Also 大轮明王.Sarasvat 大辩才天 (大辩才女); 大辩功德天 (大辩才功德天); 萨罗婆缚底; 萨罗酸底 A river, 'the modern Sursooty'; the goddess of it, who 'was persuaded to descend from heaven and confer her invention of language and letters on the human race by the sage Bhrata, whence one of her names is Bharat'; sometimes assumes the form of a swan; eloquence, or literary elegance is associated with her. Cf. M. W. Known as the mother of speech, eloquence, letters, and music. Chinese texts describe this deity sometimes as male, but generally as female, and under several forms. As 'goddess of music and poetry' she is styled 妙 (or 美 ) 音天; 妙音乐天; 妙音佛母. She is represented in two forms, one with two arms and a lute, another with eight arms. Sister of Yama. 'A consort of both Brahm and Majur,' Getty. In Japan, when with a lute, Benten is a form of Saravast, colour white, and riding a peacock. Tib. sbyas-can-ma, or ag-gi-lha-mo; M. kele-yin iikin tegri; J. ben-zai-ten, or benten.Mahkyapa, v. 摩诃迦叶.Mahktyyana or Ktyyana 摩诃迦旃延; 迦延, v. 摩 and 迦. (1) A disciple of kyamuni. (2) Name of many persons.大通智胜 Mahbhij Jnbhibhu. The great Buddha of supreme penetraton and wisdom. "A fabulous Buddha whose realm was Sambhava, his kalpa Mahrpa. Having spent ten middling kalpas in ecstatic meditation he became a Buddha, and retired again in meditation for 84,000 kalpas, during which his sixteen sons continued (as Buddhas) his preaching. Incarnations of his sons are," Akobhya, Meruka, Sihaghoa, Sihadhvaja, kapratihita, Nityapavrtta, Indradhvaja, Brahmadhvaja, Amitbha, Sarvalokadht- padravodvegapratyuttrna, Tamla-patra-candanagandha, Merukalpa, Meghasvara, Meghasvararja, Sarvaloka-bhayastambhitatva- vidhvasanakra, and kyamuni; v. Eitel. He is said to have lived in a kalpa earlier than the present by kalpas as numerous as the atoms of a chiliocosm. Amitbha is his ninth son. kyamuni his sixteenth, and the present 大 or assembly of believers are said to be the reincarnation of those who were his disciples in that former aeon; v. <title>Lotus Sutra</title>, chapter 7.Title of 神秀 Shenxiu, a disciple of the fifth patriarch.The basis or condition laid 84,000 <foreign lang="sa">kalpa</foreign>s ago (by Mahbhija-jnbhibh 大通智胜佛 in his teaching of the Lotus scriptures to 16 disciples who became incarnate as 16 Buddhas) for the subsequent teaching of the Lotus scriptures by kyamuni, the last of the 16 incarnations, to his disciples.One who has the mind of or for supreme enlightenment, e.g. a bodhisattva-mahsattva.摩调僧只部 Mahsghik, the school of the community, or majority; one of the chief early divisions, cf. 上坐部 Mahsthavir or Sthavir, i.e. the elders. There are two usages of the term, first, when the sthavira, or older disciples assembled in the cave after the Buddha's death, and the others, the 大, assembled outside. As sects, the principal division was that which took place later. The Chinese attribute this division to the influence of 大天 Mahdeva, a century after the Nirva, and its subsequent five subdivisions are also associated with his name: they are Prvasail, Avaraail, Haimavat, Lokottara-vdina, and Prajapti-vdina; v. 小乘.The great mirror, 