Great cock peak, any outstanding peak.Mahsaghata-stra 大方等大集经 The stra of the great assembly of Bodhisattvas from 十方 every direction, and of the apocalpytic sermons delivered to them by the Buddha; 60 juan, tr. in parts at various times by various translators. There are several works connected with it and others independent, e.g. 大集须弥藏经, 大集日藏经 (and 大集月藏经) , 大集经贤 护,  大集会正法经, 大集譬王经, etc.Mahsanipta. A division of the strapiaka containing avadnas, i.e. comparisons, metaphors, parables, and stories illustrating the doctrines.Great Storms, the third of the three destructive calamities to end the world.Abhyudgata-rja. Great august monarch, name of the kalpa in which ubha-vyha 妙庄严王, who is not known in the older literature, is to be reborn as a Buddha.makara 摩竭罗 a monster fish.Mahkla 摩诃迦 (or ) 罗 the great black <foreign lang="sa">deva</foreign> 大黑神. Two interpretations are given. The esoteric cult describes the <foreign lang="sa">deva</foreign> as the masculine form of Kl, i.e. Durg, the wife of iva; with one face and eight arms, or three faces and six arms, a necklace of skulls, etc. He is worshipped as giving warlike power, and fierceness; said also to be an incarnation of Vairocana for the purpose of destroying the demons; and is described as 大时 the "great time"　(-keeper) which seems to indicate Vairocana, the sun. The exoteric cult interprets him as a beneficent <foreign lang="sa">deva</foreign>, a Pluto, or god of wealth.  Consequently he is represented in two forms, by the one school as a fierce <foreign lang="sa">deva</foreign>, by the other as a kindly happy <foreign lang="sa">deva</foreign>. He is shown as one of the eight fierce guardians with trident, generally blue-black but sometimes white; he may have two elephants underfoot. Six arms and hands hold jewel, skull cup, chopper, drum, trident, elephant-goad. He is the tutelary god of Mongolian Buddhism. Six forms of Mahkla are noted: (1) 比丘大黑 A black-faced disciple of the Buddha, said to be the Buddha as Mahdeva in a previous incarnation, now guardian of the refectory. (2) 摩诃迦罗大黑女 Kl, the wife of iva. (3) 王子迦罗大黑 The son of iva. (4) 陀大黑 Cintmai, with the talismanic pearl, symbol of bestowing fortune. (5) 夜叉大黑 Subduer of demons. (6) 摩迦罗大黑 Mahkla, who carries a bag on his back and holds a hammer in his right hand. J., Daikoku; M., Yeke-gara; T., Nag-po c'en-po.The black <foreign lang="sa">deva</foreign>'s flying shard magic: take the twig of a □ jia tree (Catalpa Bungei), the twig pointing north-west; twist it to the shape of a buckwheat grain, write the Sanskrit letter  on each of its three faces, place it before the <foreign lang="sa">deva</foreign>, recite his spell a thousand times then cast the charm into the house of a prosperous person, saying may his wealth come to me.The Bodhisattva who, having attained the 大地 stage, by the power of his vow transformed himself into a dragon-king, 西域记 1.Heaven; the sky; a day; cf. <foreign lang="sa">dyo</foreign>, <foreign lang="sa">dyaus</foreign> also as 提婆 a <foreign lang="sa">deva</foreign>, or divine being, deity; and as 素罗 <foreign lang="sa">sura</foreign>, shining, bright.
