To honour. <term lang="sa">rya</term>; honoured, honourable.A monk honoured and advanced in years.The honourable commands, Buddha's teaching.<term lang="sa">rya</term>, honourable one, a sage, a saint, an <foreign lang="sa">arhat</foreign>.Honoured and victorious, the honoured victorious one, one of the five 佛顶, also known as 除障佛顶, one of the divinities of the Yoga school.The prediction of Buddhahood to his disciples by the Honoured One; the honourable prediction.尊重 Honoured, honourable; to honour.Small, little; mean, petty; inferior.Hnayna 希那衍. The small, or inferior wain, or vehicle; the form of Buddhism which developed after kyamuni's death to about the beginning of the Christian era, when Mahyna doctrines were introduced. It is the orthodox school and more in direct line with the Buddhist succession than Mahynism which developed on lines fundamentally different. The Buddha was a spiritual doctor, less interested in philosophy than in the remedy for human misery and perpetual transmigration. He "turned aside from idle metaphysical speculations; if he held views on such topics, he deemed them valueless for the purposes of salvation, which was his goal" (Keith). Metaphysical speculations arose after his death, and naturally developed into a variety of Hnayna schools before and after the separation of a distinct school of Mahyna. Hnayna remains the form in Ceylon, Burma, and Siam, hence is known as Southern Buddhism in contrast with Northern Buddhism or Mahyna, the form chiefly prevalent from Nepal to Japan. Another rough division is that of Pali and Sanskrit, Pali being the general literary language of the surviving form of Hnayna, Sanskrit of Mahyna. The term Hnayna is of Mahynist origination to emphasize the universalism and altruism of Mahyna over the narrower personal salvation of its rival. According to Mahyna teaching its own aim is universal Buddhahood, which means the utmost development of wisdom and the perfect transformation of all the living in the future state; it declares that Hnayna, aiming at arhatship and pratyekabuddhahood, seeks the destruction of body and mind and extinction in nirva. For arhatship the 四谛Four Noble Truths are the foundation teaching, for pratyekabuddhahood the 十二因缘 twelve-nidnas, and these two are therefore sometimes styled the two vehicles 二乘. Tiantai sometimes calls them the (Hnayna) Tripiaka school. Three of the eighteen Hnayna schools were transported to China: 舍 (Abhidharma) Koa; 成实 Satya-siddhi; and the school of Harivarman, the律 Vinaya school. These are described by Mahynists as the Buddha's adaptable way of meeting the questions and capacity of his hearers, though his own mind is spoken of as always being in the absolute Mahyna all-embracing realm. Such　is the Mahyna view of Hnayna, and if the Vaipulya stras and special scriptures of their school, which are repudiated by Hnayna, are apocryphal, of which there seems no doubt, then Mahyna in condemning Hnayna must find other support for its claim to orthodoxy. The stras on which it chiefly relies, as regards the Buddha, have no authenticity; while those of Hnayna cannot be accepted as his veritable teaching in the absence of fundamental research. Hnayna is said to have first been divided into minority and majority sections immediately after the death of kyamuni, when the sthvira, or older disciples, remained in what is spoken of as "the cave", some place at Rjagha, to settle the future of the order, and the general body of disciples remained outside; these two are the first 上坐部 and 大部 q. v. The first doctrinal division is reported to have taken place under the leadership of the monk 大天 Mahdeva (q.v.) a hundred years after the Buddha's nirva and during the reign of Aoka; his reign, however, has been placed later than this by historians. Mahdeva's sect became the Mahsghik, the other the Sthvira. In time the two are said to have divided into eighteen, which with the two originals are the so-called "twenty sects" of Hnayna. Another division of four sects, referred to by Yijing, is that of the 大部 (Arya) Mahsaghanikya, 上座部 ryasthavir, 根本说一切有部 Mlasarvstivda, and 正量部 Samaty. There is still another division of five sects, 五部律. For the eighteen Hnayna sects see 小乘十八部.The three characteristic marks of all Hnayna stras: the impermanence of phenomena, the unreality of the ego, and nirva.The nine classes of works belonging to the Hnayna, i.e. the whole of the twelve discourses; the Vaipulya, or broader teaching; and the Vykaraa, or prophesies.The 上座部 Sthaviravdin, School of Presbyters, and 大部 Sarvstivdin, q.v.The Hnayna partial and gradual method of obeying laws and commandments, as compared with the full and immediate salvation of Mahyna.A Chinese list of the "eighteen" sects of the Hnayna, omitting Mahsghik, Sthavira, and Sarvstivdah as generic schools: I. 大部 The Mahsghik is divided into eight schools as follows: (1) 一说部 Ekavyavahrik; (2) 说出世部 Lokottaravdina; (3) 鸡胤部 Kaukkuik (Gokulik); (4) 多闻部 Bahuruty; (5) 说假部 Prajptivadina; (6) 制多山部 Jetavaniy, or Caityaail; (7) 西山住部 Aparaail; (8) 北山住部 Uttaraail. II. 上坐部 ryasthavir, or Sthviravdin, divided into eight schools: (1) 雪山部 Haimavat. The 说一切有部 Sarvstivda gave rise to (2) 犊子部 Vtsputry, which gave rise to (3) 法上部 Dharmottary; (4) 贤胄部 Bhadrayny; (5) 正量部 Samaty; and (6) 密林山 Saagarik; (7) 化地部 Mahsak produced (8) 法藏部 Dharmagupt. From the Sarvstivdins arose also (9) 光部 Kyapy and (10) 经量部 Sautrntik. v. 宗轮论. Cf Keith, 149-150. The division of the two schools is ascribed to Mahdeva a century after the Nirva. Under I the first five are stated as arising two centuries after the Nirva, and the remaining three a century later, dates which are unreliable. Under II, the Haimavat and the Sarvstivda are dated some 200 years after the Nirva; from the Sarvstivdins soon arose the Vtsputryas, from whom soon sprang the third, fourth, fifth, and sixth; then from the Sarvstivdins there arose the seventh which gave rise to the eighth, and again, nearing the 400th year, the Sarvstivdins gave rise to the ninth and soon after the tenth. In the list of eighteen the Sarvstivdah is not counted, as it split into all the rest.Tiantai's division of Hnayna into four schools or doctrines: (1) 有门 Of reality, the existence of all phenomena, the doctrine of being (cf. 发智六足论, etc.); (2) 空门 of unreality, or non-existence (cf. 成实论); (3) 亦有亦空门 of both, or relativity of existence and non-existence (cf. 毗勒论); (4) 非有非空 of neither, or transcending existence and non-existence (cf. 迦旃延经).Hnayna and the heretical sects; also, Hnayna is a heretical sect.The commandments of the Hnayna, also recognized by the Mahyna: the five, eight, and ten commandments, the 250 for the monks, and the 348 for the nuns.The Hnayna stras, the four sections of the gamas 阿含经 v. 小乘九部.The Hnayna stras or Abhidharma.The philosophical canon of the Hnayna, now supposed to consist of some thirty-seven works, the earliest of which is said to be the Guanirdea <foreign lang="sa">stra</foreign>, tr. as 分别功德论 before A.D. 220. "The date of the Abhidharma" is "unknown to us" (Keith).The robe of five patches worn by some monks in China and by the 净土宗 Jdo sect of Japan; v. 挂.To urinate; also 小行. Buddhist monks are enjoined to urinate only in one fixed spot.antar-kalpa, or intermediate kalpa; according to the 舍论 it is the period in which human life increases by one year a century till it reaches 84,000 with men 8,400 feet high; then it is reduced at the same rate till the life-period reaches ten years with men a foot high; these two are each a small kalpa; the 智度论 reckons the two together as one kalpa; and there are other definitions.(小千) A small chiliocosm, consisting of a thousand worlds each with its Mt. Sumeru, continents, seas, and ring of iron mountains; v. 三千大千世界.Small group, a class for instruction outside the regular morning or evening services; also a class in a household.
