oral and evanescent.<term lang="sa">aesa</term>. Without remainder, no remnant, final; applied to the section of the Vinaya regarding expulsion for unpardonable sin from the monkhood; also to final <foreign lang="sa">nirva</foreign> without remainder of reincarnation.(无余依盘) <term lang="sa">anupadhiea</term>, the <foreign lang="sa">nirva</foreign> state in which exists no remainder of the karma of suffering; it is also the <foreign lang="sa">nirva</foreign> of <foreign lang="sa">arhat</foreign> extinction of body and mind, described as 无余灰断.Complete or final prediction, e.g. to Buddhahood, as contrasted with partial prediction.Not creating; uncreated; not doing; inactive, physically or mentally; independent of action, word, or will i.e. natural, intuitive.无表戒 The intangible, invisible moral law that influences the ordinand when he receives visible ordination; i.e. the internal spiritual moral law and its influence; the invisible grace of which the visible ordination is a sign; v. 无表 <foreign lang="sa">avijapti</foreign>.Nothing on which to rely; unreliable.Final <foreign lang="sa">nirva</foreign>, v. 无余, nothing for reincarnation to lay hold of.Not upside-down, seeing things right-side up, or correctly, i.e. correct views of truth and things, e.g. not regarding the seeming as real, the temporal as eternal, etc.An unilluminating Buddha, a useless Buddha who gives out no light.The undiminished powers of a bodhisattva after attaining Buddhahood; i.e. undiminished power and zeal to save all beings, power of memory, wisdom, <foreign lang="sa">nirva</foreign>, and insight attained through <foreign lang="sa">nirva</foreign>; cf. 智度论 26; also for a list of twenty-two cf. 唯识论 10.A bandit without a sword, e.g. a virtueless monk robbing others of their virtue.<term lang="sa">nirvikalpa</term>. Non-discriminating.The mind free from particularization, especially from affection and feelings; passionless; translates <foreign lang="sa">avikalpa</foreign>; (a) unconditioned or absolute, as in the 如; (b) conditioned, as in <foreign lang="sa">dhyna</foreign>. Particularization includes memory, reason, self-consciousness; the mind free from particularization is free from these.The unconditioned or passionless mind, see 无分别心.The absolute dharma underlying all particular dharmas, the absolute as contrasted with the relative.Without merit, or virtue.Without effort.<term lang="sa">akobha</term>; imperturbable, calm, serene, unagitated.Akobhya, cf. 阿婆 and 不动佛 The unperturbed Buddha, sometimes tr. as motionless, but the reference is to his calmness, serenity, and absence of passion; he is one of the Five Dhyni-Buddhas, and generally reigns over the east, his kingdom being Abhirati; realm of mystic pleasure. In the <title>Lotus Stra</title> he is named as the first of the sixteen sons of Mahbhijbhibhu. One of his principal characteristics is that of subduing the passions.idem 不动明王.Insatiable, name of a <foreign lang="sa">rkas</foreign>, v. 十罗女.Neither going nor coming, eternal like the <foreign lang="sa">dharmakya</foreign>.Mokala, also 无罗叉 'A native of Kustana who laboured in China as a translator and introduced there a new alphabet (A. D. 291) for the transliteration of Sanskit.' Eitel.No more birth-and-death, the bodhisattva who will not again be subject to the wheel of transmigration.<term lang="sa">vimala</term>; <term lang="sa">amala</term>. Undefiled, stainless; similar to 无漏.The stage of undefilement, the second stage of a bodhisattva; also applied to the final stage before attaining Buddhahood.The stage of undefiled endurance, the final stage of a bodhisattva, see无垢地.The stainless garment, the monastic robe of purity.<term lang="sa">amala</term>, undefiled or pure knowing or knowledge, formerly considered as the ninth, later as the eighth <foreign lang="sa">vijna</foreign>.The silent clepsydra, incense in the shape of ancient characters used to indicate the time.<term lang="sa">asakhyeya kalpa</term>, a period of numberless <foreign lang="sa">kalpa</foreign>s.Without beginning, as is the chain of transmigration.元品无明 (or 根本无明) The period of unenlightenment or ignorance without beginning, primal ignorance, also called 无始间隔, the period of transmigration which has no beginning; since under the law of causality everything has a cause, therefore no beginning is possible; for if there were a beginning it would be without cause, which is impossible. Also primal ignorance is without beginning; and the 如 is without beginning, the two terms connoting the same idea. 生死 Birth and death, or transmigration are 无始无终 also without beginning or end, but about the 'end' there is difference of interpretation.The Buddha-truth is without beginning and infinite.Transmigration which has existed without beginning through vast <foreign lang="sa">kalpa</foreign>s.Without beginning and unreal, void without beginning, the abstract idea of 无始 i.e. without beginning.<term lang="sa">aaika</term>. No longer learning, beyond study, the state of <foreign lang="sa">arhat</foreign>ship, the fourth of the <foreign lang="sa">rvaka</foreign> stages; the preceding three stages requiring study; there are nine grades of <foreign lang="sa">arhat</foreign>s who have completed their course of learning.The way of the <foreign lang="sa">arhat</foreign>, especially his attainment to complete truth and freedom from all illusion, with nothing more to learn.Dustless, without an atom of the material or unclean, immaterial, pure.The immaterial realm out of which all things come.Inexhaustible, without limit. It is a term applied by the 权教 to the noumenal or absolute; by the 实教 to the phenomenal, both being considered as infinite. The <title>Huayan stra</title> 十地品 has ten limitless things, the infinitude of living beings, of worlds, of space, of the <foreign lang="sa">dharmadhtu</foreign>, of <foreign lang="sa">nirva</foreign>, etc.Inexhaustible intention, or meaning, name of Akayamati, a bodhisattva to whom kyamuni is supposed to have addressed the Avalokitevara chapter in the <title>Lotus Stra</title>.The Buddha-truth as inexhaustible as the ocean.The one lamp which is yet limitless in the lighting of other lamps; the influence of one disciple may be limitless and inexhaustible; also limitless mirrored reflections; also an altar light always burning.法界缘起 Unlimited causation, or the unlimited influence of everything on all things and all things on everything; one of the Huayan 四种缘起.The inexhaustible treasury.Self-attained enlightenment, wisdom attained without a teacher, that of Buddha.<term lang="sa">anitya</term>. Impermanent; the first of the 三明 <foreign lang="sa">trividy</foreign>; that all things are impermanent, their birth, existence, change, and death never resting for a moment.The reliance of the impermanent, i.e. Buddha, upon whom mortals can rely.无常院; 延寿堂; 盘堂 The room where a dying monk was placed, in the direction of the sunset at the north-west corner.无常钟 The passing bell, or gong, for the dying.The bird which cries of impermanence, messenger of the shades, the goat-sucker.<term lang="sa">nirbhsa</term>, without image or shadow, without semblance or appearance.Mindless, without thought, will, or purpose; the real immaterial mind free from illusion; unconsciousness, or effortless action.无心定 The <foreign lang="sa">samdhi</foreign> in which active thought has ceased.The hermit or saint in ecstatic contemplation, as with emptied mind he becomes the receptacle of mystic influences.<term lang="sa">aoka</term>, 'without sorrow, not feeling or not causing sorrow.' M. W.Aokrma, a <foreign lang="sa">vihra</foreign> in Paliputra in which the 'third synod was held'. Eitel.<foreign lang="la">
