igratory suffering); away from the downflow into lower forms of rebirth.(无漏最后身) The final pure or passionless body.Passionless purity as a cause for attaining <foreign lang="sa">nirva</foreign>.Reality as passionless or pure.无漏智 Passionless, or pure, wisdom, knowledge, or enlightenment.The true knowledge of the Mahyna in its concept of mental reality, in contrast with Hnayna concepts of material reality.The result of following the way of 戒, 定, and 慧, i.e. purity, meditation, and wisdom, with liberation from the passions and from lower incarnation.The three roots which produce pure knowledge, 三无漏根 q.v.The way of purity, or escape from the passions and lower transmigration.The pure, passionless dharma-nature.The way of purity, or deliverance from the passions, i.e. 戒定慧 supra; the fourth of the four dogmas 灭 cessation, or annihilation of suffering.<term lang="sa">sravakaya-jna</term>, entry into spiritual knowledge free from all faults, the last of the 六通 q.v.Free from trouble, the thirteenth <foreign lang="sa">brahmaloka</foreign>, the fifth region of the fourth <foreign lang="sa">dhyna</foreign>.<term lang="sa">anavatapta</term>, heatless.The Anavatapta, or Atapta heaven, without heat or affliction 热恼; the second of the 五净天 in the fourth <foreign lang="sa">dhyna</foreign> heaven.The lake without heat, or cold lake, called Mnasarovara, or Mnasa-saro-vara, 'excellent <foreign lang="sa">mnasa</foreign> lake,' or modern Manasarovar, 31° N., 81° 3 E., 'which overflows at certain seasons and forms one lake with' Rakas-tal, which is the source of the Sutlej. It is under the protection of the <foreign lang="sa">nga</foreign>-king Anavatapta and is also known by his name. It is said to lie south of the Gandha-mdana mountains, and is erroneously reputed as the source of the four rivers Ganges, Indus, t (Trm River), and Oxus.Without love, or craving, or attachment.Not born, without being born or produced; uncreated; no rebirth; immoral; <foreign lang="sa">nirva</foreign> as not