n, and for confession, penance, and remission.<term lang="sa">aprama</term>; <term lang="sa">amita</term>; <term lang="sa">ananta</term>; immeasurable, unlimited, e.g. the 'four infinite' characteristics of a bodhisattva are 慈悲喜舍 kindness, pity, joy, and self-sacrifice.Infinite meaning, or the meaning of infinity; the meaning of the all, or all things.The <term lang="sa">anantanirdeapratihna samdhi</term>, into which the Buddha is represented as entering before preaching the doctrine of infinity as given in the <title>Lotus Stra</title>.<foreign lang="sa">aprambha</foreign>. Immeasurable, or infinite light or splendour.Amitbha, v. 阿.The heaven of boundless light, the fifth of the <foreign lang="sa">brahmaloka </foreign>s.Amitbha.Amitbha's land of infinite light.(无量净天) Apramaubha, boundless purity, the second of the heavens in the third <foreign lang="sa">dhyna</foreign> heavens of form.The Buddha of boundless purity, Amitbha.Boundless, infinite life, a name for Amitbha, as in无量寿佛; 无量寿如来; 无量寿王.The <title>Sukhvatvyha-stra</title> is tr. as the <title>Amityus stra</title>, and there are other treatises with similar titles, cf. 观无量寿经, etc.The infinite honoured one, Amitbha.<term lang="sa">anantamati</term>, boundless mind, intention, will, or meaning.Infinite wisdom, a term applied to a Buddha.Infinite enlightenment, name of Amitbha.The unsectarian, Chan or meditative sect, so called because it claimed to derive its authority directly from the mind of Buddha.Unasked; not to ask; volunteered.<term lang="sa">udna</term>, that part of the canon spoken voluntarily and not in reply to questions or appeals; but Kern defines <foreign lang="sa">udna</foreign> as 'enthusiastic utterances in prose and verse'.<term lang="sa">avci</term>, uninterrupted, unseparated, without intermission.The unintermitted karma, or unintermitted punishment for any of the five unpardonable sins; the place of such punishment, the <foreign lang="sa">avci</foreign> hell; also styled <foreign lang="sa">n