sful, a term of the esoteric sect when prayer is answered.A thing per se, i. e. the false notion of anything being a thing in itself, individual, independent, and not merely composed of elements to be disintegrated. 法我见 The false view as above, cf. 我见.Holding to things as realities, i. e the false tenet that things are real.The <foreign lang="sa">trikya</foreign>: 法 <foreign lang="sa">dharmakya</foreign>, the absolute or spiritual body; 报 <foreign lang="sa">sabhogakya</foreign>, the body of bliss; 化 <foreign lang="sa">nirmakya</foreign>, the body of incarnation. In Hnayna 法身 is described as the commandments, meditations, wisdom, nirva, and nirva-enlightenment; 报身 is the reward-body of bliss; 化 or 应 (化) is the body in its various incarnations. In Mahyna, the three bodies are regarded as distinct, but also as aspects of one body which pervades all beings. Cf. 三身.Buddhism.The categories of Buddhism such as the three realms, five <foreign lang="sa">skandha</foreign>s, five regions, four dogmas, six paths, twelve <foreign lang="sa">nidna</foreign>s, etc.The literature of Buddhism.The day of abstinence observed at the end of each half month, also the six abstinence days, in all making the eight days for keeping the eight commandments.The almsgiving of the Buddha-truth, i. e. its preaching or explanation; also 法布施.<foreign lang="sa">dharmanairtmya</foreign>. Things are without independent individuality, i.e. the tenet that things have no independent reality, no reality in themselves. 法无我智 The knowledge or wisdom of the above.(法无碍解 or法无碍智) Wisdom or power of explanation in unembarrassed accord with the Law, or Buddha-truth.Dharmaprabhsa, brightness of the law, a Buddha who will appear in our universe in the Ratnvabhsa-kalpa in a realm called Suviuddha 善净, when there will be no sexual difference, birth taking place by transformation.The wisdom of the pure heart which illumines the Way of all Buddhas.The teaching which sheds light on everything, differentiating and explaining them.Faxian, the famous pilgrim who with fellow-monks left Chang'an A.D. 399 overland for India, finally reached it, remained alone for six years, and spent three years on the return journey, arriving by sea in 414. His 佛国记 <title>Records of the Buddhistic Kingdoms</title> were made, for his information, by Buddhabhadra, an Indian monk in China. His own chief translation is the 僧祗律, a work on monastic discipline.Dharma-wisdom, which enables one to understand the four dogmas 四谛; also, the understanding of the law, or of things.The false view of Hnayna that things, or the elements of which they are made, are real.The Sarvstivdins who while: disclaiming the reality of personality claimed the reality of things.法衣 Dharma garment, the robe.The root or essence of all things, the <foreign lang="sa">bhtatathat</foreign>.The dharma-tree which bears nirva-fruit.The bridge of Buddha-truth, which is able to carry all across to nirva.The temple, or hall, of the Law, the main hall of a monastery; also the Guanyin hall.Inferring one thing from another, as from birth deducing death, etc.Buddha-truth likened to water able to wash away the stains of illusion; 法河 to a deep river; 法海 to a vast deep ocean.One of the four <foreign lang="sa">pramit</foreign> bodhisattavas in the Diamond realm.The extinction of the Law, or Buddhism, after the third of the three stages 正像末.The lamp of dharma, which dispels the darkness of ignorance.The torch of Buddhism.According to rule, naturally; also 法尔; 自然.Dharma-shining; name of the fourth patriarch of the 莲宗 Lotus sect.Religious love in contrast with 欲爱 ordinary love; Dharma-love may be Hnayna desire for nirva; or bodhisattva attachment to illusory things, both of which are to be eradicated; or Tathgata-love, which goes out to all beings for salvation.Dharmarja, King of the Law, Buddha.Son of the Dharma-king, a bodhisattva.<foreign lang="sa">dharmadhtu</foreign>, 法性; 实相; 达磨驮都 Dharma-element, -factor, or-realm. (1) A name for "things" in general, noumenal or phenomenal; for the physical universe, or any portion or phase of it. (2) The unifying underlying spiritual reality regarded as the ground or cause of all things, the absolute from which all proceeds. It is one of the eighteen <foreign lang="sa">dhtu</foreign>s. These are categories of three, four, five, and ten <foreign lang="sa">dharmadhtu</foreign>s; the first three are combinations of 事 and 理 or active and passive, dynamic and static; the ten are: Buddha-realm, Bodhisattva-realm, <foreign lang="sa">pratyekabuddha</foreign>-realm, <foreign lang="sa">rvaka</foreign>, <foreign lang="sa">deva</foreign>, Human, <foreign lang="sa">asura</foreign>, Demon, Animal, and Hades realms-a Huayan category. Tiantai has ten for meditaton, i.e. the realms of the eighteen media of perception (the six organs, six objects, and six sense-data or sensations), of illusion, sickness, karma, <foreign lang="sa">mra</foreign>, <foreign lang="sa">samdhi</foreign>, (false) views, pride, the two lower Vehicles, and the Bodhisattva Vehicle.region of reality apart from the temporal and unreal.The essential unity of the phenomenal realm.Intelligence as the fundamental nature of the universe; Vairocana as cosmic energy and wisdom interpenetrating all elements of the universe, a term used by the esoteric sects.The <foreign lang="sa">dharmadhtu</foreign> Buddha, i.e. the <foreign lang="sa">dharmakya</foreign>; the universal Buddha; the Buddha of a Buddha-realm.Mutual dependence and aid of all beings in a universe.The universe is mind only; cf. <title>Huayan Sutra</title>, <title>Lakvatra Sutra</title>, etc.The perfect intercommunion or blending of all things in the <foreign lang="sa">dharmadhtu</foreign>; the 无碍 of Huayan and the 性具 of Tiantai.In <foreign lang="sa">dharmadhtu</foreign> meditation, a term for Vairocana in both <foreign lang="sa">maala</foreign>s.<foreign lang="sa">dharmadhtu</foreign>-reality, or <foreign lang="sa">dharmadhtu</foreign> is Reality, different names but one idea, i.e. 实相 is used for 理 or noumenon by the 别教 and 法界 by the 圆教.The <foreign lang="sa">dharmadhtu</foreign>-palace, i.e. the shrine of Vairocana in the <foreign lang="sa">garbhadhtu</foreign>.idem 法界 and 法性.法界佛边智 The unimpeded or unlimited knowledge or omniscience of a Buddha in regard to all beings and things in his realm.The universal outflow of the spiritual body of the Buddha, i.e. his teaching.The <foreign lang="sa">dharmadhtu</foreign> as the environmental cause of all phenomena, everything being dependent on everything else, therefore one is in all and all in one.The treasury or storehouse or source of all phenomena, or truth.The <foreign lang="sa">dharmakya</foreign> (manifesting itself in all beings); the <foreign lang="sa">dharmadhtu</foreign> as the <foreign lang="sa">buddhakya</foreign>, all things being Buddha.The aspects of characteristics of things-all things are of monad nature but differ in form. A name of the 法相宗 Faxiang or Dharmalakaa sect (Jap. Hoss), called also 慈恩宗 Cien sect from the Tang temple, in which lived 窥基 Kuiji, known also as 慈恩. It "aims at discovering the ultimate entity of cosmic existence n contemplation, through investigation into the specific characteristics (the marks or criteria) of all existence, and through the realization of the fundamental nature of the soul in mystic illumination". "An inexhaustible number" of "seeds" are "stored up in the laya-soul; they manifest themselves in innumerable varieties of existence, both physical and mental". "Though there are infinite varieties. . . they all participate in the prime nature of the <foreign lang="sa">laya</foreign>." Anesaki. The Faxiang School is one of the "eight schools", and was established in China on the return of Xuanzang, consequent on his translation of the Yogcrya works. Its aim is to understand the principle underlying the 万法性相 or nature and characteristics of all things. Its foundation works are the 解深密经, the 唯识论, and the 瑜伽论. It is one of the Mahyna realistic schools, opposed by the idealistic schools, e.g. the 三论 school; yet it was a "combination of realism and idealism, and its religion a profoundly mystic one". Anesaki.(大乘法相教) The third of the five periods of doctrinal development as distinguished by 圭 Guifeng.The (bodhisattva) dharma-eye able to penetrate all things. Name of the founder of the法眼宗 Fayan sect, one of the five Chan (Zen) schools.To see clearly or purely the truth: in Hnayna, to see the truth of the four dogmas; in Mahyna, to see the truth which releases from reincarnation.The emptiness or unreality of things, everything being dependent on something else and having no individual existence apart from other things; hence the illusory nature of all things as being composed of elements and not possessing reality.The <foreign lang="sa">bhtatathat</foreign> as understood when the non-individuality or unreality of "things" is perceived.Meditative insight into the unreality of all things.Dharma-caused, i.e. the sense of universal altruism giving rise to pity and mercy.idem 法执.The end of the monk's year after the summer retreat; a Buddhist year; the number of 夏 or 戒腊 summer or discipline years indicating the years since a monk's ordination.Ministers of the Law, i.e. bodhisattvas; the Buddha is King of the Law, these are his ministers.A bodhisattva's complete dialectical freedom and power, so that he can expound all things unimpeded.One of the four fallacies connected with the reason (因), in which the reason is contrary to the truth of the premiss.(法身舍利); 法身偈 The <foreign lang="sa">arra</foreign>, or spiritual relics of the Buddha, his sutras, or verses, his doctrine and immutable law.法船 The barque of Buddha-truth which ferries men out from the sea of mortality and reincarnation to nirvana.The sprout or bud of Buddhism.The garden of Dharma, Buddhism.The medicine of the Law, capable of healing all misery.The Buddha's detailed teaching, and in this respect similar to 法藏.Dharma-store; also 佛法藏; 如来藏 (1) The absolute, unit