eneral acceptation is the extinction or end of all return to reincarnation with its concomitant suffering, and the entry into bliss. Nirva may be enjoyed in the present life as an attainable state, with entry into <foreign lang="sa">parinirva</foreign>, or perfect bliss to follow. It may be (a) with a 'remainder', i.e. the cause but not all the effect (karma), of reincarnation having been destroyed; (b) without 'remainder', both cause and effect having been extinguished. The answer of the Buddha as to the continued personal existence of the Tathgata in nirva is, in the Hnayna canon, relegated 'to the sphere of the indeterminates' (Keith), as one of the questions which are not essential to salvation. One argument is that flame when blown out does not perish but returns to the totality of Fire. The <title>Nirva Sutra</title> claims for nirva the ancient ideas of 常乐我净 permanence, bliss, personality purity in the transcendental realm. Mahyna declares that Hnayna by denying personality in the transcendental realm denies the existence of the Buddha. In Mahyna final nirva is transcendental, and is also used as a term for the absolute. The place where the Buddha entered his earthly nirva is given as Kuinagara, cf. 拘.Nirva-joy or bliss.The nirva-form of Buddha; also 涅盘像 the 'sleeping Buddha', i.e. the Buddha entering nirva.<term lang="sa">nivsana</term>, an inner garment, cf. 泥.The eight <foreign lang="sa">rasa</foreign>, i.e. flavours, or characteristics of nirva-permanence, peace, no growing old, no death, purity, transcendence, unperturbedness, joy.The part, or lot, of nirva.(涅盘寂静印) The seal or teaching of nirva, one of the three proof that a sutra was uttered by the Buddha, i.e. its teaching of impermanence, non-ego, nirva; also the witness within to the attainment of nirva.? <term lang="sa">nidhpana</term>, <term lang="sa">nirdahana</term>, cremation.Nickname of 道生 Daosheng, pupil of Kumrajva, tr. part of the <title>Nirva Stra</title>, asserted the eternity of Buddha, f