rst part of the <title>Nirva Stra</title> of the Mahyna. The complete translation is 大般涅盘经 tr. by Dharmaraka A.D. 423, B.N. 113; v. a partial translation of fasc. 12 and 39 by Beal, in his <title>Catena of Buddhist Scriptures</title>, pp. 160-188. It is sometimes called 北本 or Northern Book, when compared with its revision, the Southern Book, i.e. 南方大般涅盘经 <title>Mahaparinirva Stra</title>, produced in Jianye, the modem Nanjing, by two Chinese monks, Huiyan and Huiguan, and a literary man, Xie Lingyun. B.N. 114. 大般涅盘经后分 The latter part of the <title>Mahaparinirva Stra</title> tr. by Jnabhadra together with Huining and others of the Tang dynasty, B.N. 115, a continuation of the last chapter of B.N. 113 and 114.The fetter of nirva, i.e. the desire for it, which hinders entry upon the bodhisattva life of saving others; it is the fetter of Hnayna, resulting in imperfect nirva.Nirva-colour, i.e. black, representing the north.The gate or door into nirva; also the northern gate of a cemetery.The region of nirva in contrast with that of mortality.The nirva-wind which wafts the believer into <foreign lang="sa">bodhi</foreign>.Nirva food; the passions are faggots, wisdom is fire, the two prepare nirva as food.<term lang="sa">nikala</term>, without parts; seedless; indivisible; or perhaps <term lang="sa">nikla</term>, but a short time to live, intp. as 暂时 a shot time, temporary.Melt, disperse, expend, digest, dispose of.The monk's robe as putting an end to illusion.To put an end to, cause to cease.To disperse, or put an end to calamity.To solve and explain.To eradicate.To well, spring up.To spring forth.The springing fountain, i.e. the sutras.Moisten, soak, enrich, fertilize, sleek, smooth, profit.Fertilized karma, the original karma fertilized by the passions and distresses of life.The fertilization of the natural conditions which produce rebirth, especially those of the three kinds of attachment in the hour of death, love of body, of home, and of life.To drip, sprinkle, soak.D