 cause, in contrast with 因 <foreign lang="sa">hetu</foreign>, the direct or fundamental cause. <foreign lang="sa">hetu</foreign> is as the seed, <foreign lang="sa">pratyaya</foreign> the soil, rain, sunshine, etc. To reason, conclude. To climb, lay hold of. The mind 能缘can reason, the objective is 所缘, the two in contact constitute the reasoning process. The four kinds of causes are 因缘; 次第缘; 缘缘, and 增上缘 q.v.The place or idea on which the mind is centralized.To lay hold of, or study things or phenomena, in contrast to principles or noumena, cf. 缘理; meditation on the Buddha's <foreign lang="sa">nirmakya</foreign> and <foreign lang="sa">sabhogakya</foreign>, in contrast with the <foreign lang="sa">dharmakya</foreign>.A deceased relative or friend, i.e. a Buddha connected with me.<term lang="sa">pratyaya-bala</term>; the power of the conditioning cause, circumstance, or contributing environment, in contrast with the 因力 direct cause.To convert or instruct those under influence.Developing cause, i.e. development of the fundamental Buddha-nature, cf. 缘正.The <foreign lang="sa">gua</foreign>s, qualities, or sense-data which cause the six sensations of form, sound, odour, taste, touch, and thought.The conditioned mind, the mind held by the phenomenal.缘想 Thoughts arising from environment, similar to the last entry.The phenomenal, whatever is by causal conditions.The day of the month on which a particular Buddha or bodhisattva is worshipped, he being in special charge of mundane affairs on that day, e.g. the 5th is Maitreya, 15th Amitbha, 25th Majur, 30th kyamuni.Conditions opportune; favourable circumstances; cause and conditions co-operating for achieving Buddhahood.<term lang="sa">bjapra</term>, or <term lang="sa">bjapraka</term>; described as a citron. M.W. A fruit held in one of the hands of Kunti Guanyin.Conditioned and fundamental; 正 refers to the Buddha-nature, the <foreign lang="sa">bhtatathat</foreign> 正因佛性; 缘 to the Buddha-nature in all undergoing development 缘因佛性.To study, or reason on fundamental principles; to contemplate ultimate reality, cf. 缘事.By the consideration of the tenth realm only, i.e. the Buddha-realm, to cut off the illusion of the nine other realms of time and sense.Produced by causal conditions. The twelve <foreign lang="sa">nidna</foreign>s are also called 十二缘生. Cf. 缘起.Reasoning, mentality, the mind.The reasoning mind, or the mind reasoning, intelligence in contact with its object; later termed 所缘缘, i.e. 所缘 being the object and 缘 the mind; the relationship being like that of form or colour to the eye.The rational cogitating mind; also 虑知心 the cogitating perceiving mind.The phenomenal and noumenal, i.e. the observed and the observing, the object and subject.<term lang="sa">pratyekabuddha</term> 辟支佛; 辟支迦佛; 剌翳伽陀 (剌翳伽佛陀) In the early translations it was rendered 缘觉, i.e. enlightened through reasoning on the riddle of life, especially as defined in the twelve <foreign lang="sa">nidna</foreign>s. Later it was rendered 独觉 or individual enlightenment, i.e. one who lives apart from others and attains enlightenment alone, or for himself, in contrast with the altruism of the <foreign lang="sa">bodhisattva</foreign> principle. The term <foreign lang="sa">pratyekabuddha</foreign> is not limited to Buddhists, but is also general for recluses pondering alone over the meaning of life, an illustration being the rhinoceros, which lives in isolation. The non-Buddhist enlightenment is illusion, e.g. from observing the 'flying flowers and falling leaves'; the Buddhist enlightenment arises from pondering over the twelve <foreign lang="sa">nidna</foreign>s. As a degree of saintship it is undefined by early Buddhism, receiving its definition at a later period.The 'middle conveyance' period, characterized as that of the <foreign lang="sa">pratyekabuddha</foreign>, who is enlightened by the twelve <foreign lang="sa">nidna</foreign>s; it is considered as an advance on the Hnayna, cf. <foreign lang="sa">rvaka</foreign>, but not yet the standard of the altruistic <foreign lang="sa">bodhisattva</foreign>-vehicle, the Mahyna.The <foreign lang="sa">pratyekabuddha</foreign> realm, one of the ten Tiantai categories of intelligent beings.The <foreign lang="sa">pratyekabuddha</foreign> form of enlightenment, for self.The <foreign lang="sa">pratyekabuddha</foreign> or personal appearing of the Buddha.Arising from conditional causation; everything arises from conditions, and not being spontaneous and self-contained has no separate and independent nature; cf. 缘生. It is a fundamental doctrine of the Huayan school, which defines four principal uses of the term: (1) 业感缘起 that of the Hnayna, i.e. under the influence of karma the conditions of reincarnation arise; (2) 赖耶缘起 that of the primitive Mahyna school, i.e. that all things arise from the <foreign lang="sa">laya</foreign>, or 藏 fundamental store; (3) 如来藏缘起 that of the advancing Mahyna, that all things arise from the <foreign lang="sa">tathgatagarbha</foreign>, or <foreign lang="sa">bhtatathat</foreign>; (4) 法界缘起 that of complete Mahyna, in which one is all and all are one, each being a universal cause.<term lang="sa">prattya-samutpda</term>; idem 十二缘起, i.e. the twelve <foreign lang="sa">nidna</foreign>s, cf. 十二因缘, 缘起偈; 缘起颂 (缘起法颂) The <foreign lang="sa">gth</foreign> of three of the four fundamental dogmas of Buddhism; than all is suffering, that suffering is intensified by desire, and that extinction of desire is practicable. This is found in 智度论. It is also called 缘起法颂. It is placed in the foundations of pagodas and inside of images of Buddha and so is called 法身偈 <foreign lang="sa">dharmakya</foreign>
