nscious life; (4) <foreign lang="sa">nirva</foreign>, i.e. the Dharma par excellence, the object of Buddhist teaching; (5) the absolute, the real; (6) the teaching or religion of Buddha; (7) thing, object, appearance. Also, Damo, or Bodhidharma, the twenty-eighth Indian and first Chinese patriarch, who arrived in China A.D. 520, the reputed founder of the Chan or Intuitional School in China. He is described as son of a king in southern India; originally called Bodhitara. He arrived at Guangdong, bringing it is said the sacred begging-bowl, and settled in Luoyang, where he engaged in silent meditation for nine years, whence he received the title of wall-gazing Brahman 壁观婆罗门, though he was a <foreign lang="sa">katriya</foreign>. His doctrine and practice were those of the 'inner light', independent of the written word, but to 慧可 Huike, his successor, he commended the <title>Lakvatra-stra</title> as nearest to his views. There are many names with Dharma as initial: Dharmapla, Dharmagupta, Dharmayaas, Dharmaruci, Dharmaraka, Dharmatrta, Dharmavardhana, etc.The Damo, or Dharma sect, i.e. the 禅宗 Meditation, or Intuitional School.The anniversary of Bodhidharma's death, fifth of the tenth month.<term lang="sa">dharma-rayaka</term>, meditators on the principle of inactivity, or letting Nature have its course; see 阿兰若.<term lang="sa">dharmadhtu</term>, tr. 法界 'the element of law or of existence' (M.W.); all psychic and non-psychic processes (64 <foreign lang="sa">dharma</foreign>s), with the exception of <foreign lang="sa"> rpa-skandha</foreign> and <foreign lang="sa">mano-ayatana</foreign> (11), grouped as one <foreign lang="sa">dharma</foreign> element; the storehouse or matrix of phenomena, all-embracing totality of things; in the Tantric school, Vairocana divided into Garbhadhtu (material) and Vajradhtu (indestructible); a relic of the Buddha.Dravia, a district on the east coast of the Deccan.Dalai Lama, the head of the Yellow-robe sect of Tibetan Buddhism, and chief of t