e <foreign lang="sa">skandha</foreign>s.The <foreign lang="sa">skandha</foreign>-illusion, or the unreality of the <foreign lang="sa">skandha</foreign>s.The illusion of the <foreign lang="sa">skandha</foreign>s like a passing thought.The five <foreign lang="sa">skandha</foreign>s like a passing illusion.The five <foreign lang="sa">skandha</foreign>s and the eighteen <foreign lang="sa">dhtu</foreign>.A retractable penis -- one of the thirty-two marks of a Buddha.Paper money for use in services to the dead.The five <foreign lang="sa">skandha</foreign>s considered as <foreign lang="sa">mra</foreign>s or demons fighting against the Buddha, nature of men.<term lang="sa">a</term> or <term lang="sa"></term>, , . It is the first letter of the Sanskrit Siddham alphabet, and is also translit. by 曷, 遏, 安, □, 韵, 恶, etc. From it are supposed to be born all the other letters, and it is the first sound uttered by the human mouth. It has therefore numerous mystical indications. Being also a negation it symbolizes the unproduced, the impermanent, the immaterial; but it is employed in many ways indicative of the positive. Amongst other uses it indicates Amitbha, from the first syllable in that name. It is much in use for esoteric purposes.
