 been associated with the west, where in his Paradise, Suikhvat, the Western Pure Land, he receives to unbounded happiness all who call upon his name (cf. the Pure Lands 净土 of Maitreya and Akobhya). This is consequent on his forty-eight vows, especially the eighteenth, in which he vows to refuse Buddhahood until he has saved all living beings to his Paradise, except those who had committed the five unpardonable sins, or were guilty of blasphemy against the Faith. While his Paradise is theoretically only a stage on the way to rebirth in the final joys of nirvana, it is popularly considered as the final resting-place of those who cry <foreign lang="sa">na-mo a-mi-to-fo</foreign>, or blessed be, or adoration to, Amita Buddha. The 净土 Pure-land (Jap. Jdo) sect is especially devoted to this cult, which arises chiefly out of the <title>Sukhvatvyha</title>, but Amita is referred to in many other texts and recognized, with differing interpretations and emphasis, by the other sects. Eitel attributes the first preaching of the dogma to 'a priest from Tokhara' in A. D.147, and says that Faxian and Xuanzang make no mention of the cult. But the Chinese pilgrim 慧日Huiri says he found it prevalent in India 702-719. The first translation of the <title>Amityus Sutra</title>, circa A.D. 223-253, had disappeared when the Kaiyuan catalogue was compiled A.D. 730. The eighteenth vow occurs in the tr. by Dharmaraka A.D. 308. With Amita is closely associated Avalokitevara, who is also considered as his incarnation, and appears crowned with, or bearing the image of Amita. In the trinity of Amita, Avalokitevara appears on his left and Mahsthmaprpta on his right. Another group, of five, includes Kitigarbha and Ngrjuna, the latter counted as the second patriarch of the Pure Land sect. One who calls on the name of Amitbha is styled 阿弥陀圣 a saint of Amitbha. Amitbha is one of the Five '<foreign lang="sa">dhyni</foreign> buddhas' 五佛, q.v. He has many titles, amongst which are the following twelve relating to him as Buddha of light, also his title of eternal life: 无量光佛Buddha of boundless light; 无边光佛 Buddha of unlimited light; 无碍光佛 Buddha of irresistible light; 无对光佛 Buddha of incomparable light; 焰王光佛 Buddha of <foreign lang="sa">yama</foreign> or flame-king light; 净光佛 Buddha of pure light; 欢喜光佛 Buddha of joyous light; 智慧光佛 Buddha of wisdom light; 不断光佛 Buddha of unending light; 难思光佛 Buddha of inconceivable light; 无称光佛Buddha of indescribable light; 超日月光佛 Buddha of light surpassing that of sun and moon; 无量寿 Buddha of boundless age. As buddha he has, of course, all the attributes of a buddha, including the <foreign lang="sa">trikya</foreign>, or 法报化身, about which in <foreign lang="la">
