</foreign>, or brahminical heretics, given to extravagant austerities; his doctrine was that the happiness of the next life is correlative to the sufferings of this life.<term lang="sa">agni</term>, fire, v. 阿只 'Agni or Akni, name of a kingdom... north of lake Lop'. Eitel.<term lang="sa">jvika</term>, or <term lang="sa">jvaka</term>, 邪命 One who lives on others, i.e. by improper means; an improper livelihood (for one in orders).(or 阿耆多达 or 阿耆陀 or 阿耆多陀) Agnidatta, name of a king.v. 阿□ <term lang="sa">au</term>; and used for Anavatapta, infra.<term lang="sa">anuubh</term>; v, 阿.Anuruddha, son of Amtodana, and 'cousin german' to kyamumi (Eitel); not Aniruddha; cf. 阿那.(阿耨多罗三藐三菩提) <term lang="sa">anuttara-samyak-sabodhi</term>; or <term lang="sa">anubodhi</term>. Unexcelled complete enlightenment, an attribute of every buddha; tr. by 无上正偏知; 无上正等正觉, the highest correct and complete, or universal knowledge or awareness, the perfect wisdom of a buddha, omniscience.Anu Guanyin, the twentieth of the thirty-three forms of the 'Goddess of Mercy', seated on a rook scanning the sea to protect or save voyagers.阿那婆答多 (or 阿那波达多) Anavatapta, a lake in Jambudvpa, north of the Himlayas, south of 香山 Gandha-mdana, descrbed as about 800 <foreign lang="zh">li</foreign> in circumference, bordered by gold, silver, precious stones, etc. It is said to be the source of the four great rivers: east, the Ganges out of a silver ox mouth; south, the Indus out of that of an elephant; west, the Oxus; and north, the t, said to be the Yellow River. Eitel has the Brahmaputra, Ganges, atadru (or Sutlej), and the Oxus; but there is confusion in the records. The Dragon-king of this lake became a Bodhisattva and is exempt from the distresses of the other seven dragon-kings. The阿耨达山 are the mountains north of the lake.<term lang="sa">ya</term>, approach, drawing near.(or 阿也怛那) <term lang="sa">yatana</term>, seat, abode, intp. by 入 or 处 entrance, or place i.e. the  <foreign lang="sa">sadyatana</foreign>s, six entrances or places of sense-data, or sensation; v. 六 入.(or 阿耶揭□婆) Hayagrva, the horse-head Guanyin.Ayamukha, Hayamukha, an ancient kingdom in Central India.<term lang="sa">yan</term> has the same meaning as 阿耶, but is intp. by 观 to contemplate, look into.Aoka, 阿恕伽; 阿输迦(or 阿舒迦, or 阿叔迦) Grandson of Candragupta (Sandrokottos), who united India and reached the summit of his career about 315 B.C. Aoka reigned from about 274 to 237 B.C. His name Aoka, 'free from care,' may have been adopted on his conversion.  He is accused of the assassination of his brother and relatives to gain the throne, and of a fierce temperament in his earlier days.  Converted, he became the first famous patron of Buddhism, encouraging its development and propaganda at home and abroad, to which existing pillars, etc., bear witness; his propaganda is said to have spread from the borders of China to Macedonia, Epirus, Egypt, and Cyrene.  His title is Dharmoka; he should be distinguished from Kloka, grandson of Ajtaatru. Cf.　阿育伽经、 阿育伽传,　etc.The name of a tree under which the mother of the Buddha was painlessly delivered of her son, for which Chinese texts give eight different dates; the <foreign lang="la">
jonesia aoka</foreign>; it is also called 毕利叉 <foreign lang="sa">vka</foreign>.(阿若) jta-kuinya, 阿若□陈如 one of the first five disciples of kyamuni, said to be the first to realize the Buddha-truth.  <foreign lang="sa">jta</foreign>, his designation (i.e. recognized or confessed), is intp. as 巳知 Having known and 无知 Not knowing, or knowledge of non-existence. Or perhaps for <foreign lang="sa">jt</foreign>, confessor. Kaundinya, his surname, is said to mean a 'fire holder' from 'the early fire worship of the Brahmins.'<term lang="sa">au</term>, v. 阿□.<term lang="sa">anustubhchandas</term>, a metre of two lines each in 8 十 8 syllables; also 阿耨□都婆.<term lang="sa">asdhya</term>, incurable.<term lang="sa">ah</term>, is a double <foreign lang="sa">nakatra</foreign> (two lunar mansions) associated with 箕, stars in Sagittarius; this form is said to be <foreign lang="sa">prvh</foreign> and is intp. as 轸, i.e. stars in Corvus, but these stars are in the Indian constellation Hast, the Hand, which may be the more correct transliteration; cf. 阿沙陀.<term lang="sa">rksa</term>, 阿落迦婆 demons, evil spirts; rks are female demons, but are also said to be protectresses, cf. 罗叉婆.Avakan, Vakhan, Khavakan; Wakhan, an ancient kingdom on the borders of the present Afghanistan, described by Xuanzang as 200 <foreign lang="zh">li</foreign> south-east of Badakshan. Also 湿薄健; 劫薄健.(or 阿裟摩娑摩) <term lang="sa">asamasama</term>, one of the titles of a buddha; it is defined as 无等等 which has various interpretations, but generally means of unequalled rank. 阿娑弭 has similar meaning.<term lang="sa">a-vam-ram-ham-kham</term> is the highest formula of the 言 Shingon sect; it represents all the five elements, or composite parts of Vairocana in his corporeal nature, but also represents him in his 法身 or spiritual nature; cf. 阿卑, etc., and 阿罗 Arapacana.(or 阿恃单□那)  <term lang="sa">ajitajaya</term>, invincible, a charm for entering the meditation on invincibility.  Cf. 阿恃.Agiras, one of the seven <foreign lang="sa">deva-