ilence, that the absolute is indefinable, the doctrine of Vimalakrti.Answering a foolish or improper question by silence.Smart, clever, intelligent.Worldly wisdom, cleverness, intelligence.A drum.Drum-music and singing with stringed instruments.The drum-<foreign lang="sa">deva</foreign>, thunder.The rolling of drums.<term lang="sa">mua</term>; <term lang="sa">khu</term>; a mouse, rat.Vain discussions, like rat-squeakings and cuckoo-callings.<term lang="sa">ghra</term>. The nose; one of the five 根 <foreign lang="sa">indrya</foreign>s; the organ of smell; one of the six <foreign lang="sa">vijna</foreign>s (六识) or perceptions, the sense of smell; translit. <foreign lang="sa">vai</foreign>, <foreign lang="sa">vi</foreign>.Organ and sense of smell.Vaikha, the second month of spring.see 毗, Vibh.The breath of the nostrils; also the perception of smell.The organ of smell.v. 毗 Virhaka.The sensation, or perception of smell.Virpka. One of the <foreign lang="sa">lokapla</foreign>, or guardians of the four cardinal points of Mount Sumeru. In China known as 广目 wide-eyed, red in colour with a small pagoda in his right hand, and a serpent in his left; in China worshipped as one of the twenty-four Deva rya 天尊. Also, a name for Mahevara or Rudra (iva). Cf. 毗 and 髀.cf. 毗 Vinaya.<foreign lang="sa">dhyna</foreign> master with nose (and other organs) shutoff from sensation, i.e. a stupid mystic.(or鼻致迦) <term lang="sa">bjaka</term>, a seed, v. 种.Even, level, equal, uniform; complete, perfect; equalize; tranquillize; alike; all; at the same time, altogether.The final body which brings to an end all former karma.Speaking and hearing together, or at the same time.The teeth, especially the front and upper teeth; toothed, serrated; age, class.A serrated seal, or serrations as evidence.<term lang="sa">dantakha</term>. A stick for cleaning the teeth.Blue or Green dragon.
A dragon, dragon-like, imperial; tr. for <foreign lang="sa">nga</foreign>, which means snake, serpent; also elephant, elephantine, serpent-like, etc., cf. 那.
A begging-bowl formerly used by a certain monk for obtaining rain, the dragon descending into his bowl.A tr. of Ngasena, v. 那先; 那伽犀那; and the 那先比丘经 <title>Milindapaha stra</title>.Maitreya's assembly under the 龙华树 dragon-flower tree for preaching the Buddha-truth. The eight of the fourth moon has been so called, an occasion when the images are washed with fragrant water, in connection with the expected Messiah.<term lang="sa">nga-pupa</term>; 奔那伽 <term lang="sa">pupanga</term>, the dragon-flower tree, which will be the <foreign lang="sa">bodhi</foreign>-tree of Maitreya, the Buddhist Messiah, when he comes to earth.Dragon kings and <foreign lang="sa">deva</foreign>s; also Ngrjuna and Vasubandhu.<foreign lang="sa">nga</foreign>s, <foreign lang="sa">deva</foreign>s, <foreign lang="sa">rkasa</foreign>s, <foreign lang="sa">gandharva</foreign>s, <foreign lang="sa">asura</foreign>s, <foreign lang="sa">garua</foreign>s, <foreign lang="sa">kinnara</foreign>s, and <foreign lang="sa">mahoraga</foreign>s.A <foreign lang="sa">samdhi</foreign> powerful like the dragon; abstract meditation which results in great spiritual power.Ngakany, a <foreign lang="sa">nga</foreign> maiden. Daughter of Sgara-ngarja, the dragon king at the bottom of the ocean; she is presented in the <title>Lotus Stra</title>, becoming a Buddha, under the tuition of Majur.Dragon palace; palaces of the dragon kings; also 龙户.Lumbin, v. 岚.The dragon-quarter, i.e. the north.Ngrjuna, v. 那.Dragon soup, a purgative concocted of human and animal urine and excrement; also called 黄龙汤.Another name for the river Nairajan, cf. 尼.Ngrjuna, v. 那.<term lang="sa">ngarja</term>, dragon king, a title for the tutelary deity of a lake, river, sea, and other places; there are lists of 5, 7, 8, 81, and 185 dragon kings.Dragon-pearl; pearl below the dragon's jaws; the sun or moon associated with the dragon and spring.A dragon-god, or spirit.(龙种上尊王佛) The Buddha of the race of honourable dragon kings, a title of Majur.Dragon books, i.e. the <foreign lang="sa">stra</foreign>s, so called because the Sanskrit writing seemed to the Chinese to resemble the forms of snakes and dragons.The Dragon Treasury or library, formerly in the 龙兴 Longxing monastery at Chang-an.Dragon elephant, or dragon and elephant, i.e. great saints, Buddhas, <foreign lang="sa">bodhisattva</foreign>s. A large elephant is called a dragon elephant. The term is also one of respect applied to a monk.Dragon coffins, i.e. those for monks.A shrine; a cabinet, box; a coffin (for a monk); to contain.A pagoda with shrines.Tortoise, turtle. The rareness of meeting a Buddha is compared with the difficulty of a blind sea-turtle finding a log to float on, or a one-eyed tortoise finding a log with a spy-hole through it.Kuch, also 库车; 屈支 (or屈茨); 丘兹; 支 An ancient kingdom and city in Eastern Turkestan, 41°45' N., 83°E. It is recorded as the native place of Kumrajva.The hair on a tortoise, i.e. the non-existent.The parable of the tortoise and the jackal, the tortoise hiding its six vulnerable parts, symbolizing the six senses, the jackal wailing and starving to death.